<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TrappedWhales 2ndLd-Writethru a0803 10-27 0833</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trapped Whales, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0803,0854</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Icebreakers Make Last Ditch Bid To Release Whales</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with plunging temperatures newly
endangering whales' escape, quotes, details; picks up 6th graf:
`Eskimos with ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARROW, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Faced with thickening ice, plunging
temperatures and the imminent departure of two Soviet icebreakers,
rescuers late Thursday made a last-ditch effort to free two whales
threatened again by the arctic icepack.
   The California gray whales, freed from nearly three weeks
confinement in their icebound breathing hole off Point Barrow, moved
closer to open water via man-made breathing holes and channels cut
in the ice by the Soviet ships.
   But as night fell Thursday, the whales were in the last breathing
hole cut for them, with about 300 meters of ice between the hole and
open water, said rescue coordinator Ron Morris.
   Temperatures Thursday hovered around 15 degrees below zero and
were expected to drop to minus 20 to 25 degrees below overnight,
cold enough to begin freezing over the adjoining open water of the
Arctic Ocean.
   Rescuers left a portable generator to power de-icing equipment at
the whale's last breathing hole and light a beacon for the
icebreaker Vladimir Arseniev, which was to make two or three final
runs to try to free the whales.
   ``This should free them,'' Morris said. ``Hopefully, the whales
will see the opportunity to leave. We've given them the best shot
tonight.'' Morris said the Soviets had to leave Thursday night.
   The plunging temperatures quickly refroze the channels the
icebreaker had made earlier Thursday. Eskimos broke out chain saws
and cut dozens more breathing holes leading away from the clogged
channel toward the open sea.
   By nightfall, the workers were encountering dangerously unstable
ice as a result of the icebreakers' earlier efforts.
   As they did Wednesday, the whales readily followed the path cut
for them by the Eskimos. As night fell, they had advance as far as
the last breathing hole.
   In a new tactic, rescuers carved 30 new holes Thursday in hopes
that the whales would follow the holes away from the channel and
eventually reach open water via another route the Soviet ships were
clearing.
   ``They're ready to go home'' after nearly six months at sea, said
Rear Adm. Sigmund Petersen of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration. ``We felt also with the weather creeping in like
this, we had to do something tonight.''
   Everyone hopes that when daylight arrives Friday, both the
Soviets and the whales will be gone, Petersen said.
   NOAA ice analyst Gary Huffard said the open water was definitely
beginning to freeze, but he remained optimistic that the whales
could escape if they could get beyond the edge of the pressure ridge
battered down by the icebreakers earlier in the week.
   Eskimos with chain saws had cut a series of breathing holes that
allowed the whales to swim well away from the original hole to which
they had been confined.
   The whales grew accustomed to the cutting and during a frenzy of
work Wednesday, in which 50 new holes were cut, the whales
repeatedly surfaced in the new holes before the last block of ice
was removed.
   Since the whales were accustomed to the noise of the saws, that
sound might be used to coax them forward toward open water, said
Morris, a biologist with the U.S. National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration.
   The Eskimos eventually worked the marine mammals to within a
quarter-mile of a channel carved through the 18-inch-thick ice by
two Soviet icebreakers late Tuesday and early Wednesday. Then the
icebreaker Vladimir Arseniev reopened the partially frozen channel.
   The man-made channel, aimed at guiding the whales to an natural
open ``lead'' through the ice and eventually to open water,
partially refroze during the night, Morris said.
   He said the whales were ``conditioning themselves back to
reality'' after nearly three weeks of confinement in the ice off the
coast near Point Barrow.
   He also announced a crackdown on access to the whales by
reporters and others. He said pilots entering restricted air space
over the whales were subject to fines of $25,000.
   A biologist for the North Slope Borough, Geoff Carroll, said
Thursday that the whales continued to appear healthy.
   The fate of the whales may never be known. Scientists involved in
the rescue that cost more than $800,000 didn't attach radio
transmitters to the whales to track them, in part because of concern
that the devices would only add to their stress, said federal marine
mammal biologist Jim Harvey.
   A whale that was trapped with the pair nearly three weeks ago
apparently died last week.
   The endangered California gray whales have one of the longest
migration routes of all mammals, 6,000 to 8,000 miles from summer
feeding grounds in the Arctic to the warm water off Baja California.
   Their population has risen to about 20,000, growing at an annual
average of 2.5 percent for the past decade, officials said.
</TEXT>
