<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GodAndDeath     10-27 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-God And Death,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Famous Consider God And Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One millionaire said he is sure he will go to
heaven when he dies but another thinks death really is the end.
   A third thinks of heaven as eternally watching cricket.
   The thoughts emerged in a new book today, ``My God,'' compiled by
actress Hayley Mills and rock music manager Marcus Maclaine. They
asked famous people for their personal concept of God and what
happens when they die.
   Succinct replies came from novelist Kingsley Amis and Royal Opera
House general director Jeremy Isaacs. They answered ``None'' and
``Nothing.''
   Lord Forte, millionaire hotel owner and caterer, was more
optimistic.
   ``I am certain that Heaven _ and I am confident I will not be
sent elsewhere _ will be a beautiful place, but I have no fixed
conception of what it will be like. I am prepared to be pleasantly
surprised,'' he said.
   Musician Paul McCartney, the former Beatle and also very rich,
thought God was a shortenened version of good and that ``When you
die you conk out.''
   Yoko Ono, widow of murdered Beatle John Lennon, said: ``God is
the unknown power which is within. Death is a transition.''
   Author-scientist Arthur C. Clarke doesn't believe in God but
added, ``I'm very interested in him.''
   Astrologer Patric Walker replied: ``All I know for sure about God
is that it isn't me.''
   Jeffrey Archer, the best-selling novelist, said he had no idea
what would happen to him after death, but hoped he would find
himself on top of the pavilion at Lord's cricket ground in London
watching the game.
   Bill Jordan, president of the 850,000-member Amalgamated
Engineering Union, replied: ``I only pray that when I die there will
be no pickets at the Pearly Gates, only a sign saying `Vacancies,
apply within.'''
</TEXT>
