<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Fashion     10-27 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fashion,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saint Laurent's Streamlined Classics</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yves Saint Laurent played it safe with streamlined
classics in his ready-to-wear show for next summer.
   Short and edited down to essentials, the show Wednesday was a
relief after other presentations that dragged out a hundred ways to
create draped, flowered sheaths for a sex kitten.
   Saint Laurent's fashion statement was short and pithy. And the
clothes often looked like simpler versions of his last couture
collection, just as deftly cut in their own way.
   In day wear, he led off with mariner-inspired suits _ in navy or
white broadcloth pants or skirts just above the knee _ with a
slightly fitted battle jacket or fitted blazer, both with brass
buttons, and topped with jaunty sailors berets.
   Saint Laurent kept to his favorite shaped shoulders and short
skirts, though he also dropped some hemlines in fluid, flared or
pleated skirts to below the knee and longer _ to midcalf length in
some pretty white belted sundresses with circular skirts.
   Saint Laurent's silk jersey sheath just barely caressed the body.
In tiny stripes, it was crisscrossed by diagonal buttoned piping. A
perfect little navy pleated dress with a white collar and bow could
not have been simpler, yet had the master's touch.
   Saint Laurent did not go in for the pyramidal trouser line
sweeping Paris, but kept his pants long and straight in suits or
narrow and cropped, matador style. For this peppy new line, he
teamed the cropped pants with fitted jackets that had big puffy
sleeves in colors like bright yellow and turquoise damasked cotton
pique.
   With few exceptions, the color themes were played in a low key.
Black, navy and white took precedence, with autumnal hues of beige,
khaki and ochre not far behind. Jazzy colors popped up in bicolored
suits in shades of turquoise, lime or corn yellow. The one flame red
cotton poplin dress with balloon sleeves was a standout among all
the sober clothes.
   There's good news for those who can't afford Saint Laurent
couture: In ready-to-wear, he offered an excellent version of the
tuxedo dress he did in 20 different ways for couture. Less
successful but still fun was the bright bicolored suit with
grape-bunch embroidery on shoulders and pockets, and even striated
grape-shaped buttons.
   Catching the mood of the times, Saint Laurent concentrated on
simple crepe de chine dinner dresses rather than
rhinestone-encrusted ball gowns loaded with flounces, frou-frou and
lace. Short kimono-wrapped silk dresses or variations on the
shirtwaist in silk had a kind of studied throwaway simplicity.
   For a finale, there were gold-belted draped white crepe gowns.
The show left some in the audience hungry for more, but there was
nothing extraneous. Everything in this understated collection was
wearable and chic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
