<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArmsInspections     10-27 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Inspections,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Pushing On-Site Inspection Plan For START Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is seeking agreement from
Moscow on an on-site inspection proposal his administration says
will make a strategic arms reduction treaty verifiable while
shielding ``legitimate U.S. secrets and interests.''
   State Department Spokesman Charles Redman said Wednesday that the
president recently made a number of verification-related decisions,
``including some on the approach we will take to so-called suspect
site inspections.''
   But he declined to spell out details while the U.S.-Soviet arms
reduction talks are continuing in Geneva. The two sides are seeking
to work out 50 percent cuts in their arsenals of strategic, or
intercontinental, nuclear weapons.
   Redman said that while ``considerable progress'' has been made at
the Geneva talks, ``much still remains to be done.''
   ``Our intention in the START talks is to flesh out the details of
our position, including the details of a START verification regime,
so that there will be a complete U.S. position on the table in
Geneva,'' he said.
   ``START will have the most extensive verification regime in
history, well beyond that of the verification measures of the INF
(Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces) treaty.''
   Redman added that ``We are convinced that these provisions will
make the treaty effectively verifiable. At the same time, we must be
careful to protect legitimate U.S. secrets and interests. ... We
believe the proper balance has been made between those two
considerations.''
   Redman also said the United States has completed its negotiating
position on space-based defenses with proposals intended to
``complement our initiative to permit the development, testing and
deployment of all space-based sensors ...''
   ``This element does not represent any change in longstanding U.S.
policy on the ABM (Anti-Ballistic Missile) Treaty and its proper
interpretation,'' he said, adding that administration policy on the
conduct of the Strategic Defense Initiative, as worked out with
Congress, also is unchanged.
   ``Testing of space-based components, which is permitted by the
ABM Treaty, does not represent deployment of such components,''
Redman said and added: ``U.S. policy remains that we will not accept
any restrictions on SDI beyond those of the ABM Treaty.''
</TEXT>
