<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0039EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WeatherOffices     10-27 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weather Offices,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weather Service Facing Cuts Due To Budget Squeeze</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A money shortage is threatening the National
Weather Service less than a month into the government's new fiscal
year, although officials say no decision has been made on whether to
close offices.
   An employee union said Wednesday it had obtained information from
the Commerce Department, parent agency of the weather service,
indicating that as many as 40 weather offices could be in jeopardy.
   Weather Service spokesman Donald Witten confirmed that the agency
is facing financial problems and said many options are being
considered for saving money. He said no decisions have been made on
any closings.
   A recently approved pay raise for federal workers, coupled with
budget cutbacks, is expected to leave the weather service about $25
million short of its needs for the fiscal year that started Oct. 1.
   ``Basically, we're looking at the operation and seeing what we
can do to meet that shortfall,'' Witten said in a telephone
interview.
   ``Obviously the sooner you do it in the fiscal year the better,
but the fact is we haven't decided on any specific reductions at
this time. We're looking at a lot of options,'' he said.
   Witten said the Weather Service has instituted a hiring freeze
and is considering offering early retirement to employees who may be
eligible to leave before the normal retirement age, as immediate
ways to save money. Salaries are by far the largest item in the
agency's budget.
   The National Weather Service Employees Organization issued a
statement claiming that plans have been drafted to close as many as
40 of the 191 weather offices.
   Such a series of closings could have a serious impact on
forecasting, particularly affecting airline operations, the group
said.
   The Weather Service offices collect hourly observations, which
are transmitted to the National Meteorological Center in Suitland,
Md., where a national forecast is developed. That is then sent to
local forecast offices, which use it along with their local
observations to issue local weather forecasts and alerts.
   This is not the first time Weather Service offices have been
threatened with closings in efforts to save money. Each time,
however, Congress has voted money to keep the offices open.
   Among the weather data collection offices that may be threatened,
according to the employees group, are:
   Eastern region: Mansfield, Ohio; Elkins, W.Va.; Reading, Pa.;
Lynchburg, Va.; Parkersburg, W.Va.
   Central region: Alamosa, Colo.; Dubuque, Iowa; Aberdeen, S.D.; La
Crosse, Wis.; Sheridan, Wyo.; Valentine, Neb.; Houghton Lake, Mich.;
Fort Wayne, Ind.; Rockford, Ill.; Springfield, Ill.; Peoria, Ill.;
Cairo, Ill.
   Southern region: Fort Myers, Fla.; Alexandria, La.; Clayton,
N.M.; Roswell, N.M.
   Western region: Flagstaff, Ariz.; Bakersfield, Calif.; Bishop,
Calif.; Santa Maria, Calif.; Stockton, Calif.; Lewiston, Idaho;
Havre, Mont.; Walla Walla, Wash.; Milford, Utah; Burna, Ore.;
Klamath Falls, Ore.
   Pacific region: Kahului, Hawaii.
   Alaska region: Barter Island, Alaska; Homer, Alaska.
   In addition, the employee association said there was the
possibility that the Juneau, Alaska, forecast office would be
downgraded and that hours would be reduced at offices in Flint and
Sault Ste. Marie, Mich.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
