<HEAD>Stumps For LA Supervisor Candidate; Opponents Charge Ulterior
Motives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Hope says he has been going to bat for
county Supervisor Mike Antonovich because the politician's a
``softball pitcher.''
   ``Softball and politics go hand in hand _ they're both
underhanded,'' Hope joked at a $500-a-plate fund-raiser Tuesday
night.
   But some opponents of Antonovich say the comedian is playing hard
ball, trying to score a starring role in what they have labeled his
latest road picture: ``The Road to Jordan Ranch.''
   Protesters outside the dinner said Hope is trying to win county
approval for a road that would lead through the Santa Monica
Mountains National Recreation area to the entertainer's 1,500-home
Jordan Ranch development in Ventura County.
   Hope denied he is trying to curry favor from Antonovich, but the
supervisor's opponent, Baxter Ward, has turned the matter into a
political issue.
   ``He is entertaining at Mr. Antonovich's fund-raiser ... I think
with a purpose in mind,'' Ward said at debate last month.
   Antonovich, at the debate, said ``adequate roads'' were needed in
the area and promised he would work with the community to reach an
environmentally sound decision if Ventura County approves the
housing project.
