<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-TV     10-27 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-TV,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Waging an Airwaves War in Hopes of Capturing Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Is there a market niche among swing voters for
a Massachusetts governor who's mounting an unprecedented television
sales campaign for himself? Probably not, analysts say, but he's got
the right idea.
   Saturation exposure is ``a perfectly reasonable strategy'' for
Democrat Michael Dukakis, given his double-digit deficit in the
polls and the proximity of Election Day, says Larry Sabato, a
political scientist at the University of Virginia.
   ``But you've got to have a product to sell. You have to have
something people want to buy,'' says Sabato. ``What they may not be
accounting for is the fact that most people have apparently
concluded that they don't want Michael Dukakis to be president.
Seeing him more often is not going to change that evaluation.''
   Dukakis is waging an airwaves war to ward off the closing of
American minds, abetted by TV news and interview shows that are
providing him with unprecedented blocks of free exposure to millions
of viewers.
   The invitations are flowing to both Dukakis and Republican
nominee George Bush. But while Bush, the nearly prohibitive
favorite, is still weighing whether and where to appear, Dukakis is
taking on all comers.
   ``He's going on every TV show he can find except Morton Downey
Jr.,'' joked Michael Robinson, a Georgetown University government
professor, pollster and author of two books about campaign media
coverage.
   ``Don't get me wrong, he's doing the right thing,'' Robinson
added. ``But will this turn the election around? Of course not.''
   Dukakis latest extended appearance, 90 minutes on ABC's
``Nightline'' Tuesday night, drew predictable raves from his own
spin doctors and equally predictable put-downs from the Bush camp.
   ``A terrific session,'' pronounced Dukakis adviser Steve
Engelberg.
   ``He got his pants chewed up,'' declared Bush spokesman Mark
Goodin.
   More objective reviewers noted that Dukakis passed up numerous
chances during the interview to stress his new populist image as a
fighter for ``Main Street'' Americans, a president who would be ``on
your side.'' He also failed to reject a Koppel suggestion that Bush
has nailed ``yoabato said.
``That was the dullest interview I've ever seen Ted Koppel conduct.
Dukakis' answers just weren't that lively or interesting. And he
missed so many opportunities to make useful points from his
perspective. Something to warm him up, something to make him appear
more human.''
   Dukakis is running the usual 30-second TV ads and a 5-minute
network spot summarizing his appeal. He has already appeared, in
addition to ``Nightline,'' on the morning news shows and the Larry
King talk show on Cable News Network.
   His wife, Kitty, was on CBS' ``Face the Nation.'' His running
mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, was on ABC's ``This Week with David
Brinkley'' and was interviewed on the CBS ``Evening News'' Wednesday
night.
   A new CBS News-New York Times poll indicates about a quarter of
the nation's probable voters still classify themselves as undecided.
Dukakis will have a few more shots at them, including lengthy
appearances on the CBS and NBC evening newscasts and an interview
with David Frost on the Fox network Nov. 6.
   ``Everything depends on his performance and how interested swing
voters or soft Bush supporters are in hearing him make his pitch,''
said John Buckley, a Republican consultant and CBS commentator.
   ``He has everything to gain because he has nothing to lose,''
Buckley added. ``He's behind in every poll. He's behind in more than
40 states. His only hope is to get as much exposure for himself as
possible and hope that what he says has some resonance with voters.''
   Robinson, a self-professed Democrat, said he can't imagine
Dukakis attracting anyone into his column ``by force of personality.
But he can't hide now, he's got to come out. He's got to be Michael
Dukakis. And he will go down in an honorable defeat.''
</TEXT>
