<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NuclearSafety 3rdLd-Writethru a0401 10-27 1089</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Safety, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0401,1,050</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Nuclear Group Urges Safety Overhaul at Atomic Weapons Plants</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 14th graf pvs bgng, `The New,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with Rockwell spokesman's comments, edit for transition</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anti-nuclear physicians' group on Wednesday
urged President Reagan to take drastic steps to improve safety at
U.S. nuclear weapons-making facilities, where production virtually
has halted because of safety concerns.
   Four major plants in the 14-facility manufacturing complex have
been wholly or partially closed for safety reasons and the
production of nuclear weapons has ground to a halt, according to
officials at the Energy and Defense departments.
   The anti-nuclear group, Physicians for Social Responsibility,
said in a statement that contamination and dubious safety procedures
at the plants ``have direct and potentially devastating medical
implications.''
   ``They constitute a public health emergency,'' said H. Jack
Geiger, a member of the committee and a professor at the City
University of New York Medical School.
   Geiger said not enough studies have been conducted to determine
whether nuclear wastes from the sites have caused cancer or other
illnesses among workers or nearby residents. The Energy Department
has estimated it would cost $66 billion to $110 billion in the
long-term to clean up the waste and upgrade the facilities, and
congressional estimates have run as high as $170 billion.
   In a letter to Reagan, the physicians' group urged the
administration to give the newly created National Defense Safety
Board the power to close down any Energy Department nuclear facility
it deems ``not ... in compliance with safety, public health,
occupations and environmental standards.''
   Congress created the board under the defense authorization bill
for fiscal 1989 to monitor DOE's beleaguered nuclear weapons
program, which manufactures atomic weapons for the Pentagon. The
board does not have powers of enforcement.
   DOE is reviewing the safety and operation of all of its plants to
report to Congress by mid-December on whether to close any of them.
   The Wall Street Journal on Wednesday said an early draft of that
report calls for permanent closing of two facilities, one in
Fernald, Ohio, and another near Denver, where work was interrupted
earlier this year because of health and safety reasons.
   At the Rocky Flats Plant near Denver, two workers and an Energy
Department inspector suffered low-level radioactive contamination on
Sept. 29, after which authorities closed Building 771, a plutonium
reprocessing facility there.
   The Energy Department cited the exposure of the workers when it
announced the closing earlier this month. However, the department
was aware of severe problems at the plant even before the accident,
a department official said late Wednesday.
   ``It's my understanding that (the contamination of the workers
and the inspector) was essentially a catalytic incident'' that
prompted the closing of the facility, said C. Anson Franklin, the
chief Energy Department spokesman said in an interview.
   Franklin said Energy Department inspectors had been in the plant
several times before the accident ``and had come up with quite a
long list of changes. We believe the contractor (Rockwell) was
sincere and committed to making these changes, but we felt the
progress (assessed after the accident) hadn't been as rapid as we
would like to see. So that feeling led to the conversations that
resulted in the shutdown of the facility.''
   Rockwell spokesman Ed Heintz on Wednesday emphasized that
although Building 771, the plutonium reprocessing building, is
closed down, that does not necessarily mean the plant's operations
are halted. However, he said he couldn't provide more specifics
because the quantity of plutonium stockpiled was classified.
   The New York Times in Thursday's editions quoted a General
Accounting Office report as saying that an inspector, identified in
the GAO report as J. Krupar, found a series of ``very serious''
violations at Rocky Flats that left ``no margins for safety.''
   His concerns included ``slow and unskilled'' work by employees
assigned to monitor radiation levels; radiological monitors that
were ``unchecked, out of service and out of calibration;''
``haphazard, inconsistent'' posting of warning signs outside rooms
with radioactive contamination, ``electrical safety is dangerously
managed,'' and ``attitudes are complacent.''
   The GAO report was prepared for Rep. David E. Skaggs, D-Colo.,
and a copy was obtained by The Times.
   Franklin told The Associated Press: ``I haven't seen the GAO
report, but it's my understanding that it essentially recaps the
findings of the Department of Energy's inspectors at Rocky Flats.''
   Workers at the Feed Materials Production Center in Fernald, about
20 miles north of Cincinnati, have been striking the plant for a
month, forcing it to suspend operations. And Ohio Gov. Richard
Celeste has urged that federal authorities close the Fernald plant,
which according to DOE documents filed in court, regularly has
dumped radioactive waste into the water and air.
   A DOE spokesman, Will Callicott, said that because the
department's study on whether to close any nuclear facilities was
not complete, ``it is premature to comment on its recommendations.''
   Two other major weapons facilities have been closed. The three
reactors at the Savannah River Plant at Aiken, S.C., where the
department manufactures plutonium and tritium for nuclear weapons,
were shut down earlier this year for safety reasons.
   The department is working on plans to restart one of the reactors
in December, although details have not been finalized, Callicott
said.
   The department closed down the other reactor at which it had been
manufacturing plutonium and tritium, in Hanford, Wash., and has no
current plans to reopen it, officials said.
   The physicians' committee urged Reagan to ``prohibit the
Department of Energy from restarting any of its reactors at Savannah
River, or reopening facilities presently closed at Fernald, Rocky
Flats and Hanford until (an independent commission) completes an
evaluation of the public health, occupational and environmental
safety risks of the continued operation of these facilities.''
   White House spokesman B. Jay Cooper said the president's office
had not received the letter from the physicians' committee and could
not comment directly on it.
   ``The Department of Energy is on top of this situation,'' said
Cooper. Energy Secretary John ``Herrington has developed a plan to
check out all the sites, to issue a report in December on all of the
sites, and rank the sites in order of safety.''
   ``The bottom line is that the president has said that we will not
operate an unsafe nuclear plant, and we will not,'' said Cooper.
   U.S. officials have said they have adequate supplies of
plutonium, but face critical shortages of tritium, a radioactive
isotope of hydrogen used to boost the power of nuclear explosions.
</TEXT>
