<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0021EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0797 10-27 1077</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0797,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush: Dukakis `Just Itching to Repeal' Reagan Tax Cuts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 27th graf pvs, `Literally, 11,' with gas
fumes aboard Air Force Two causing delay in flight.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential nominee George Bush said
Wednesday that Democratic rival Michael Dukakis sounds like a man
``just itching to repeal'' the income tax cuts of the past eight
years. Bush said his election would be a mandate against tax
increases.
   In an economics lecture stressing his week-long campaign theme,
the vice president said the Massachusetts governor ``never met a
payroll'' and doesn't understand the impact of taxes on business.
   Bush campaigned in Michigan, with 20 electoral votes at stake on
Nov. 8, before heading for rallies in Sioux Falls, S.D., and
Billings, Mont., small states where his aides said the race could be
close. ``We're going to shore up our support,'' said press secretary
Sheila Tate.
   Bush told more than 1,600 people at the Economic Club of Detroit
that Reagan administration policies have produced astounding
economic growth despite Democratic ``voices of doom.''
   The GOP nominee said he would seek to spur that growth by cutting
the capital gains tax rate, a proposal Dukakis has denounced
repeatedly as a tax break for the wealthy.
   Capital gains, realized on the sale of such assets as stocks and
real estate, are taxed like any other income under tax legislation
that took effect last year. Bush wants to restore preferential
treatment for capital gains, cutting the top rate from 33 percent to
15 percent.
   He said such a move has been ``endorsed by everyone,'' from John
F. Kennedy to President Reagan, from Democratic vice presidential
nominee Lloyd Bentsen to Bush running mate Dan Quayle.
   ``It's not a tax break for the rich, it is a break for those who
want to have a job in this country,'' Bush said. ``Unfortunately, my
opponent's only experience with business is regulating it and taxing
it.
   ``He's never run a business. ... He's never met a payroll. He
doesn't understand how when you're starting out, you need people to
join you in taking a risk. So he paints my proposal as an effort to
help the rich.''
   ``Wrong,'' said Bush. He said most capital gains are realized by
people who earn less than $50,000 a year.
   The Dukakis campaign on the other hand cites a Congressional
Budget Office study concluding more than half the capital gains are
realized by the 1 percent of richest Americans.
   As for income taxes, Bush said rates have been cut by an average
27 percent since Reagan took office in 1981, and the results in new
jobs and economic growth ``have been staggering.''
   ``Despite the certifiable success of our tax cuts in unleashing
the longest recovery in our history, my opponent thinks they were a
disaster,'' Bush said, recalling Dukakis' criticism of the cuts
during the Democratic primary campaign.
   ``Those sound to me like the words of someone who is just itching
to repeal one of the most successful economic policies in our
history,'' Bush said.
   He said the reason is that Dukakis is proposing ``mandated new
spending'' that would cost the government and business billions upon
billions of dollars.
   ``If I am elected in 13 days eight hours and 22 minutes from now
... I will work with Congress, telling them the American people, in
electing me, voted against a tax increase,'' Bush said.
   He said the voters also would be say they wanted the president to
have line-item veto authority, so he could delete specific spending
items from an appropriations bill without vetoing the entire measure.
   Answering written questions, Bush said the U.S. trade deficit
should shrink under current policies.
   ``I'm convinced that this is on the right track without further
legislation,'' he said. ``I have in the past supported the voluntary
restraint agreements as they affect autos and I am open-minded on
that question. But I am not one who favors protection.''
   Bush refused to say who he would nominate as secretary of state
on the ground that such a disclosure might break rules against
promising appointments. The Cabinet post is widely believed to be
earmarked for James A. Baker III, his campaign chairman, former
treasury secretary and a long-time Bush associate from Texas.
   Bush said that to answer questions about appointments to a Bush
administration ``conveys a sense of overconfidence that I do not
feel.''
   Bush wrapped up his campaigning with a rally in Billings, Mont.,
repeating that that Dukakis could raise income taxes.
   ``Don't elect him because he just might take that tax cut away
from the American people,'' Bush said again.
   At Rocky Mountain College on a gymnasium stage with Montana
Republicans and a dozen impassive Indians in full headress, Bush
also renewed his pledge to fight against gun control.
   ``I'm a sportsman, I'm a hunter, like to do it,'' he said. ``And
I don't believe we need the federal govenment going forward with gun
control legislation.''
   Urging Montana Republicans to turn out the vote on Nov. 8, Bush
had a little trouble with his arithmetic.
   ``Literally, 11 days and an hour, we're going to know the answer
to this,'' he said of an election 13 days away.
   In Billings, Air Force Two taxied to the runway for a flight to
Tacoma, Wash., but then turned back when the galley crew reported
gas fumes in the rear of the plane. Fire fighting crews were sent in
and the engines were turned off while an inspection was made.
   Bush and other members of his entourage remained on board.
   After about 20 minutes, it was determined that strong cross winds
had blown fuel fumes into the aircraft and they would dissipate on
takeoff, as they did when the plane departed.
   Some time after Bush left, the press plane chartered by media
covering the vice president was held on the ground because of high
winds that prevented takeoff, Bush officials said.
   At a Republican rally in the stockyards in Sioux Falls, Bush
challenged what he said were Democratic proposals to impose supply
controls on American farmers. He said Dukakis stands for such
tightened controls and ``I don't believe he should be against the
American farmer.''
   ``We are not going to pull the rug out from under the American
farmer and go to some kind of supply management,'' Bush told several
hundred people at the stockyards rally.
</TEXT>
