<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HomelessRally     10-27 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Rally,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Arrested in Homeless Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: With Laserphoto WX25</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four people, including former Green Bay Packers
halfback Travis Williams, were arrested Wednesday in a protest at
the Capitol against the plight of the homeless, police said.
   The four were charged with unlawful entry after staging a sit-in
at the reception area of California Sen. Alan Cranston's office,
said U.S. Capitol Police spokesman Dan Nichols.
   The maximum penalty for the charge is a $500 fine and six months
in prison. The four were being held pending arraignment in Superior
Court on Thursday.
   Williams, 42, of Richmond, Calif., said he has been homeless for
much of the last three years. Now, he said he is a security officer
in a soup kitchen and lives in a room that costs $200 a month.
   Since the daily protests began last month, 175 demonstrators have
been arrested. The protests, organized by the Community for Creative
Nonviolence, seek to point out to Congress the lack of affordable
housing in the United States.
   Arrested along with Williams were Susan Prather, 37, Crockett,
Calif.; Joanne Yerkes, 24, Berkeley, Calif., and Chester Celestine,
29, Richmond, Calif.
</TEXT>
