<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NATO     10-27 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Defense Ministers Meet On Upgrading Short-range Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO must maintain short-range
nuclear weapons now that the United States and the Soviet Union have
agreed to ban intermediate-range missiles, a new report says.
   The study will be the focus of a meeting beginning today of
defense ministers of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization,
officials said. Most NATO nations want to increase the range of the
tactical weapons to make up for the loss of intermediate-range arms.
   The defense chiefs will be asked to endorse the report, a
detailed look at the role of short-range nuclear rockets and
artillery in the Western alliance.
   ``The conclusion is yes, there will be a requirement for
short-range nuclear forces but there's no reason ... for a decision
on how to pursue that goal ... now,'' a U.S. official said on
condition of anonymity.
   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev signed
the treaty in December to eliminate all U.S. and Soviet land-based
missiles with ranges from about 300 miles to 3,400 miles.
   Since the agreement, the question of upgrading short-range
nuclear forces _ artillery and missiles with ranges up to about 300
miles _ has received more attention.
   ``The overall aim is the maintenance and enhancement of an
effective deterrence,'' said Frits Bolkestein, the Dutch defense
minister.
   He said the range of short-range, or tactical weapons, should be
extended and ``made more flexible and less vulnerable.''
   ``If systems can be made more effective and more survivable, the
number of warheads may consequently be reduced,'' he said.
   The ministers were expected to make no decisions on the
controversial issue of modernizing short-range weapons.
   Even so, the discussions probably will shape the debate leading
to a decision on whether to give NATO more powerful nuclear weapons
for the front lines. Analysts say ranges eventually may be extended
up to the treaty limits of about 300 miles.
   The United States and Britain have indicated support for
modernizing short-range weapons. But West Germany and the
Netherlands, with strong anti-nuclear groups, say NATO has no
pressing need now for such a decision.
   The most controversial of the weapons under discussion for
modernization is the Lance surface-to-surface missile, which was
introduced in 1972 and which military analysts say will be obsolete
by 1995.
   The Lance has a range of a little more than 60 miles, and a new
system might boost that up to more 250 miles.
   Also under discussion is a new tactical air-to-surface missile,
called a stand-off weapon, which would replace nuclear gravity
bombs. It would allow fighters to launch weapons to a target without
flying over heavy fighting.
   The short-range arsenal also includes nuclear artillery shells
for 155 mm and 203 mm howitzers, which have ranges up to 18 miles.
Work on upgrading these arms is under way.
   U.S. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci will attend the talks, held
twice a year on nuclear issues.
   Fourteen of NATO's 16 members will take part, with Iceland
attending as an observer. France is not part of NATO's joint
military structure.
</TEXT>
