<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0134EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Opera     10-27 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Opera,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cast, With Kathleen Battle, Shines In Met's `Barber'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for PMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For lovers of classical singing, the news at the
Metropolitan Opera's first ``The Barber of Seville'' this season is
that Kathleen Battle was in her usual radiant voice and the rest of
the cast was right up there with her.
   For musicologists, the news is that the remarkable third-act aria
which Rossini wrote for tenor Manuel Garcia, who sang Almaviva at
the 1816 premiere, was sung Wednesday night by American tenor
Rockwell Blake. Rossini took the aria out in 1817 when the tenor
engaged couldn't sing it. The Met had not included it for 25 years,
and possibly never had.
   Blake, who has the flexibility to sing pleasingly what really is
coloratura for a man, is used to singing the aria in Europe. In a
letter to critics last week, he expressed dismay that the Met had
cut 20 measures of it.
   Leo Nucci sang the barber, Figaro. He establishes his brash,
loud, wheeler-dealer character in his first entrance, coming on like
a snake-oil salesman. With that planted in listeners' minds, Nucci
tones down to become a fine singer and team player in an operatic
farce.
   Bass Enzo Dara was unusually funny as the guardian of Rosina
(Miss Battle) who intends to marry her. He will, of course, be
foiled by Almaviva, whose disguises as a soldier and a music
teacher, cooked up by Figaro, get him close to Rosina.
   Dara's comic timing and his singing are superb. To add humor, he
uses several different walks, including a fast, self-satisfied
shuffle, after he locks Rosina in the house.
   Miss Battle's voice is what a listener would dream it should be:
accurate, full of delicate warmth, floating with infinite grace.
   Robert Lloyd of Essex, England, made his Met debut as the
``real'' music teacher. He has a ripe bass and is commanding; it was
a delight to watch Dara respond to his stage business.
   Margaret Jane Wray has a small, often ignored scene as the
housekeeper which she sang so well as to be noticed.
   Ralf Weikert of Austria, who made his Met debut last season with
another bel canto opera, ``The Elixir of Love,'' conducted with
sensitivity.
   The Met last had presented ``The Barber'' in its 1984-85 season.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
