<HEAD>Casino Employees who said `No' to Drug Ribbon Reinstated with
Apology</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Casino employees suspended after they just said
no to an order to wear a ribbon proclaiming they are ``drug free''
have been returned to their jobs and given back all their lost pay
with an apology.
   ``In my enthusiasm to support the program, I decided to mandate
that you participate by wearing the ribbons. I made a mistake and
admit it,'' said Ronald S. Jeffery, senior vice president and
general manager of Harrah's Reno. In a memo to all employees of the
hotel-casino on Wednesday, Jeffrey defended his order as ``trying
too hard to show our support for an important national problem that
is threatening America.''
   Jeffrey said five or six employees were suspended Sunday and
Monday after refusing to wear the red ribbons that said, ``The
choice for me, drug free.'' On Monday, he made the ribbon-wearing
program voluntary after receiving complaints from the workers. They
had hired an attorney who claimed their First Amendment rights had
been violated.
