<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Dennis Quaid may be portraying rock
'n' roller Jerry Lee Lewis in an upcoming movie, but he won't get
the singing parts, Lewis says.
   ``You're not getting the soundtrack, boy,'' Lewis told Quaid at a
gathering Wednesday to promote the movie, ``Great Balls Of Fire,''
much of which will be filmed in Memphis.
   Filming is to begin Monday on the movie, named for one of Lewis'
best known recordings. The film will be based on the beginning of
Lewis' career, which got a major boost at the old Sun Records studio
in Memphis.
   Lewis said he is impressed with Quaid's piano playing and
singing, but plans to record the music for the movie himself,
although Quaid indicated he might try some of the musical parts.
   Quaid said he studied piano for several months, watched films of
Lewis' performances and attended his concerts in researching the
part.
