<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former members of the singing DeBarge
family and two associates have been convicted of conspiring to
transport cocaine from Los Angeles and distribute it in Michigan.
   A U.S. District Court jury on Tuesday convicted Jonathon
``Chico'' DeBarge, Robert ``Bobby'' DeBarge, Dwayne O. Hill and Mark
Douglas. Each could receive a maximum sentence of life imprisonment
at their January sentencing.
   The four were accused of conspiring with at least two other
people to distribute 2.2 pounds of cocaine in western Michigan.
   Jonathon DeBarge, 22, of Grand Rapids, recorded a solo album,
``Chico DeBarge,'' that reached No. 33 on the Billboard magazine pop
music charts in 1986. Robert DeBarge, 26, of Los Angeles, was a
former member of the singing group Switch.
   The family's most famous brother, El DeBarge, pleaded no contest
in September 1986 to assault and battery charges in Grand Rapids.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music star Waylon Jennings,
hospitalized after complaining of chest pains during a performance,
was simply suffering from exhaustion and will be home this weekend,
a spokeswoman said.
   Doctors examining Jennings after he was hospitalized Monday
determined the singer hadn't suffered a heart attack, spokeswoman
Marylou Hyatt said Wednesday from Jennings' office in Nashville,
Tenn.
   ``He's strong as an ox,'' she said.
   Jennings, 51, became ill during a performance in Santa Ana, 30
miles south of downtown Los Angeles.
   Jennings, who has won two Grammy Awards and four Country Music
Association Awards, is probably best known for his duet with Willie
Nelson on ``Mamas Don't Let Your Babies Grow Up to Be Cowboys.''
