<HEAD>One Billion Dollars Worth of Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second straight summer drought has
caused $1 billion worth of damage to Yugoslavia's corn, sugar beet,
sunflower and soya crops, the state Tanjug news agency reported.
   Wednesday's report quoted Sava Vujkov, president of the Federal
Committee for Agriculture, as saying the drought, which scorched
wide areas of farmland, was ``on the scale of a natural disaster
occurring once in 30 years.''
   He was quoted as saying Yugoslavia's agricultural industry lacks
the material and financial means to bear the burden of two years of
consecutive droughts. The country is saddled with a $21 billion
foreign debt and 217 percent annual inflation.
</TEXT>
