<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--FishKillPenalty     10-27 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Fish Kill Penalty,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reporters Fined for Fish Death in Chemical Accident Re-Creation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BASEL, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court ordered two Swiss television
journalists to pay fines of $65 each for killing a fish during a
re-creation of a chemical accident two years ago that seriously
polluted the Rhine river.
   A Basel court ruled Wednesday that the journalists violated
animal protection laws when they put a fish in a container of water
they said was polluted in the same way the Rhine had been after the
accident, and filmed the fish in its death throes.
   The filming took place three months after the Nov. 1, 1986
accident at the chemical plant in Schweizerhalle, near Basel, a
statement from Swiss television said. The sequence was never
broadcast.
   The statement, issued after the ruling, said the sequence was
intended to give viewers a ``visual warning'' about the damage
caused by such accidents.
   The statement said the journalists might appeal the ruling.
</TEXT>
