<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Gulf     10-27 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Gulf,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq's U.N. Ambassador Says Shatt Waterway Could Be Replaced With
New Port</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the Iran-Iraq peace talks break down
over the disputed Shatt-al-Arab waterway, Iraq will re-open a
deepwater port west of the waterway, its U.N. ambassador says.
   The ambassador, Ismat Kittani, predicted resolution of the issue
and also was optimistic about an exchange of tens of thousands of
prisoners of war held by each side, saying, ``That is the brightest
part of the picture.''
   The Iran-Iraq peace talks are to resume Monday in Geneva. The two
enemies agreed to a cease-fire in August, halting the war that began
in 1980.
   Kittani said one key to the talks is that his country is seeking
a pledge from Iran not to resume stopping ships in the Persian Gulf
to search for Iraq-bound war cargo.
   Iran has not searched any ships since the cease-fire began Aug.
20, but says it retains that right.
   Kittani made his comments Wednesday night at his home before
returning to Baghdad for consultations.
   The deepwater port at Khor Zouber, said Kittani, was productive
before the war began and could be restored if Iran won't guarantee
free navigation on the Shatt-al-Arab as well as agree to its being
dredged.
   The Khor Zouber port just west of the Shatt-al-Arab is entered
through the Khor Abdallah channel, which empties into the Persian
Gulf.
   The Shatt-al-Arab was Iraq's primary outlet to the gulf before
the war, but it has been blocked by sunken ships, unexploded
ordnance and an accumulation of eight years of silt.
   Asked if Iraq wishes to develop an alternative deep-water port,
Kittani replied, ``We'll have to'' if Iraq won't agree to begin
dredging and re-open the Shatt, known to Iran as the Arvand River.
   Clearing the Shatt will take two years, he said, adding that the
United Nations could be called in to help the dredging.
   ``The U.N. cleared the Suez Canal of ordnance two times'' after
wars in 1956 and 1973 between Israel and Egypt, Kittani noted.
   Iran insists the 1975 Algiers Treaty that defines their border as
running down the middle of the Shatt be maintained. President Saddam
Hussein of Iraq rejected the treaty in 1980.
   Asked how long Iraq was willing to continue the Geneva talks,
Kittani said: ``We are ready to stay there until hell freezes over
or until we reach complete agreement.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
