<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gulf-USForces     10-27 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-US Forces,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nuclear-Powered U.S. Carrier And Support Ships Arriving In Persian
Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The arrival of the nuclear-powered carrier
USS Nimitz and eight support ships in the Arabian Sea this weekend
will not change the number of Navy ships in the Persian Gulf region,
officials say.
   The new U.S. carrier contingent in Battle Group Bravo will
replace a similar unit led by the carrier Carl M. Vinson. Both
groups are part of the U.S. Pacific Fleet.
   The change will leave the United States with 26 ships, one fewer
than on Aug. 20 when a cease-fire took effect in the 8-year war
between Iran and Iraq, U.S. officials said Wednesday.
   The U.S. contingent is by far the largest of seven foreign naval
units in the region. About 16 U.S. ships, including six mine
sweepers, are in the gulf at any given time.
   The impending switch in U.S. carrier battle groups returns one of
the Navy's powerful Aegis-type missile cruisers to the area for the
first time since the USS Vincennes left.
   Officials said the USS Antietam, one of the newest of the
high-tech, billion-dollar warships, is making its first trip to the
region as a Nimitz escort.
   Other ships in the battle group are the nuclear cruiser
California, missile destroyers Waddell and Benjamin Stoddert,
frigate Barbey, ammunition ship Kiska, supply ship Mars and the
oiler Willamette.
   Pentagon officials say the American force in the gulf will be
scaled back to five or six ships if the truce continues to hold.
   That was the size of the Navy's Middle East Force when the war
escalated in mid-1987 and the United States began escorting
Kuwaiti-owned tankers that had been given U.S. registry and flew the
American flag.
   The officials have not disclosed a timetable, but military
sources say some reductions probably will come through attrition or
changing the orders of ships marked for gulf duty.
   Military sources say a U.S. carrier force probably will continue
to operate in the Indian Ocean for about half the time, as it did
before the gulf crisis.
   In the only force cutback to date, the Aegis-type cruiser Mobile
Bay had its orders for the gulf canceled Aug. 12, the day before it
was to leave for the Middle East to replace its sister ship, the
Vincennes.
   The Vincennes' departure in early September reduced the U.S.
strength to 26 ships.
   Although fleet strength has not been reduced further, the Navy
has curtailed air surveillance activities and ended the close
escorting of U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tankers through the gulf.
   U.S. warships now monitor the tankers' movements, ready to
respond in case of trouble. No armed incidents have been reported in
the gulf since the truce, military and shipping officials say.
   Britain and Italy also have announced they no longer will
accompany commercial ships in convoy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
