<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0467 10-27 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0467,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Warns that Democratic Prosperity Means High Interest Rates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS final graf, Some time, to include details on plane
troubles; Tops prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush, after challenging
Michael Dukakis in states often ignored in presidential politics, is
plunging back into the hotly contested battle in California, warning
that the Democrats' definition of prosperity means high interest
rates.
   ``We don't need that kind of Democratic prosperity,'' Bush said
Wednesday, noting that the prime interest rate reached 21.5 percent
under the Carter administration, more than twice what it is now.
   ``We need the kind that Ronald Reagan has brought to this
country,'' Bush declared.
   After stops Wednesday in Detroit, Sioux Falls, S.D., and
Billings, Mont., Bush flew here for an endorsement today by a
maritime union and a rally. Washington is considered a tossup state.
   Then, he was heading for California where 47 electoral votes, the
largest prize in the nation, are at stake. Bush will spend two days
in California before heading back east.
   Bush's chief of staff, Craig Fuller, said that in the 12 days
remaining before the election, ``We're going to focus on states
where we think the support is soft, where the margin is close.
   ``We're pleased and encouraged by the polls but we are going to
continue to work to make sure we've locked up the necessary
electoral votes,'' Fuller said.
   Bush made a point Wednesday of claiming that Michael Dukakis, his
Democratic opponent, would put in jeopardy the income tax cuts
enacted during the Reagan administration.
   He said Dukakis called the tax cuts ``one of the worst bills that
Congress ever could have passed.''
   ``Well, don't elect him cause he might just take that cut away
from the American people and I will not do that,'' Bush told a
cheering crowd of perhaps 2,000 people in a gymnasium at Rocky
Mountain College in Billings.
   A determined Dukakis supporter, a young woman who gave her name
as Victoria Brown, dashed back and forth through the audience with a
Dukakis sign until it was snatched away by someone in the crowd. She
tussled with her antagonist, and both were led away by a policeman.
   While Bush is waging a determined battle to win the 20 electoral
votes in Michigan, where he spent Wednesday morning, he had conceded
South Dakota during the primary session to then-rival Bob Dole.
   Taken together, South Dakota and Montana offer only seven of the
270 electoral votes needed to win the White House. Wednesday's visit
was his only stop in each state in the general election campaign.
   Asked as he left Billings why he even bothered to stop there,
Bush replied, ``There's a lot at stake here. You've got two
congressional seats, you've got a governor's seat, you've got a
Senate seat, you've got the president and the vice president.
   ``So it is very, very important and it shows that we are taking
absolutely nothing for granted,'' the vice president told reporters.
   Recalling the words he had said inside the gym, Bush said, ``I am
running like I am behind, and I mean it. And we are not going to
lighten up at all.''
   In Billings, Air Force Two taxied to the runway for the flight to
Tacoma but then turned back when the galley crew reported gas fumes
in the rear of the plane. Fire fighting crews were sent to the plane
and the engines were turned off while an inspection was made.
   Bush and other members of his entourage remained on board. After
about 20 minutes, it was determined that strong cross winds had
blown fuel fumes into the aircraft and they would dissipate on
takeoff, as they did when the plane departed.
   Some time after Bush left, the press plane chartered by media
covering the vice president was held on the ground for a couple
hours because of high winds that prevented takeoff, Bush officials
said. It aborted three takeoffs because of a stalled engine before
finally departing.
</TEXT>
