<HEAD>Kahane Gets Court OK To Make U.S. Speaking Tour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brooklyn-born Rabbi Meir Kahane will be allowed
to travel here from Israel for a speaking tour while he challenges a
government finding that he had renounced his U.S. citizenship.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker on Wednesday ordered the
State Department not to interfere with Kahane's plan to enter the
United States early Thursday to begin a three-week speaking tour at
a suburban Washington synagogue.
   An attorney for Kahane, the founder of the militant Jewish
Defense League, argued in a hearing that Kahane only signed papers
renouncing his U.S. citizenship so he could retain his seat in the
Knesset, the Israeli parliament.
   Kahane sent a telegram to withdraw the renunciation after the
Israeli Supreme Court ruled his anti-Arab political party was racist
and therefore ineligible to participate in the Nov. 1 parliamentary
election.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Affirmative Action, South African Embargo Sought from Japanese</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Business
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``Model Japanese Code of Conduct'' issued by
the head of the Congressional Black Caucus asks Japanese business to
expand minority training, work and management opportunity in its
American subsidiaries and to pull out of South Africa.
   Rep. Mervyn Dymally, D-Calif., issued the code Wednesday after he
held hearings on what he called insensitivity in Japan to Black
Americans.
   Japan's ``extraordinary achievements'' in industry and technology
``are tainted by a narrow, egocentrist view of the human family,''
Dymally said in a preamble to the code.
   Dymally said he sent the model code to the Japanese Embassy and
released it ``in a quest to support the goal of racial equality and
to insure the full dignity of all people of good will in America and
Japan.''
   The code asks that Japanese-owned firms in the United States
``conform to the standard created by the most advanced U.S.
corporations in promoting minority participation at all levels and
in all aspects of industrial activity.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Government Sets Insurance Rates For Rocket Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Transportation is requiring
three U.S. rocket companies to obtain up to $80 million in property
damage insurance coverage before using federal facilities for
commercial space launches.
   The orders call for $80 million in insurance for Martin Marietta
Corp. and for McDonnell Douglas Co., and $75 million for General
Dynamics Inc. Martin Marietta makes the Titan launch rocket,
McDonnell Douglas builds the Delta and Delta II, and General
Dynamics makes the Atlas-Centaur.
   Representatives of the rocket companies said Wednesday the
insurance demand was about what had been expected from the DOT.
   Orders were expected today to cover any liability claims by third
parties. Under terms of a commercial space transportation bill
passed by Congress and now on President Reagan's desk, the third
party liability requirement could be set as high as $500 million for
each launch.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Warning Issued on Mobile Home Furnaces</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The manufacturer of Coleman mobile-home
furnaces will inspect the furnaces and offer a discount on
replacements because the furnaces could pose a danger if
inadequately maintained.
   About 100,000 Model 8600 Solar Pak mobile home-furnaces are
involved in the warning, the Consumer Product Safety Commission
reported Wednesday.
   The commission said that both it and Coleman have received
reports of carbon monoxide poisoning involving furnaces that have
either been inadequately maintained or altered in some way.
   The suspect furnaces can be identified by the name Coleman on the
front and the rating plate inside the furnace door, which will state
if it is a Coleman 8600 Solar Pak. Owners of the furnaces, and those
uncertain about their units, can telephone Coleman at 1-800-232-SOLR.
</TEXT>
