<DOCNO> AP881027-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Swindall Bjt   10-27 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swindall, Bjt,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Comes Out Swinging After Setback In Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge's decision has forced Rep. Pat Swindall to
fight an uphill battle for re-election while under a perjury
indictment. But he has said he hasn't lost any moral high ground to
his opponent, former actor Ben Jones.
   In one of the nation's bitterest campaigns, Swindall, R-Ga., has
repeatedly brought up his Democratic rival's admitted alcoholism and
past brushes with the law. Jones, who played ``Cooter'' on
television's ``The Dukes of Hazzard,'' has proposed in turn that
Swindall be tested for drug use and psychiatric problems.
   The battle returned to the limelight Wednesday when U.S. District
Judge Robert Vining halted the two-term congressman's trial on 10
perjury counts until after the Nov. 8 election.
   Swindall's high-speed strategy of representing himself as his own
attorney amid the campaign backfired when Vining brought into court
two recent campaign mailings, one of which mentioned Swindall's
claim that a private polygraph test supports his defense.
   Vining, who disallowed a polygraph test as evidence in the trial,
said the literature might influence jurors. He also said he wanted
the Justice Department to investigate whether Swindall violated
court rules governing comments lawyers may make outside the
courtroom.
   The judge then dismissed the jury and later rejected Swindall's
last attempt at a quick trial, a request that Vining hear the case
without a jury. Prosecutor Craig Gillen also was willing to allow
Vining to render the verdict, but federal court rules also require
the judge's consent.
   Swindall, who had demanded his own indictment from the floor of
the House, said he ``very much would have liked to have had an
exoneration before the election.''
   ``However, I knew that with a campaign with only two weeks to go,
and with the issue of perjury uppermost in many people's minds, that
it was important for me to get that polygraph evidence out to the
voters of the 4th District, because it totally exonerates me,'' he
said.
   Swindall is accused of lying to a grand jury when he said he did
not remember being told that an $850,000 home mortgage loan he was
seeking might be coming from illegal drug proceeds. Swindall
negotiated the loan with a money broker who turned out to be an
undercover federal agent, and the prosecution has a recording of the
agent telling Swindall he had a ``gut feeling'' drugs were involved.
   Jones would not comment on the case. ``We had an 18-point lead
before the indictment, and we got it not because of his problems,
but because of our hard work,'' he said.
   A poll by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution after Swindall's Oct.
17 indictment found the challenger leading 53-27 percent.
   ``We're going to run the last two weeks of this campaign just as
we had planned to _ not talking about Pat Swindall at all,'' Jones
said. ``We're going to be talking about Ben Jones and taking the
high road.''
   Nonetheless, the campaign has featured Swindall's repeated
questions about Jones' own legal problems and his admitted bout with
alcoholism.
   During his drinking days, Jones acknowledged, he was arrested on
several occasions for what he called ``stupid alcoholic behavior,''
referring to old disorderly conduct charges.
   Swindall also called for new debates Wednesday and said Jones
recently had avoided them, adding, ``if I held positions that are so
clearly liberal, I wouldn't want to face the voters'' either.
   Jones denied ducking Swindall. He said he has debated the
congressman eight times and claimed Swindall declined seven
invitations to attend forums with Jones.
   But he said his schedule for the remainder of the campaign is
already set and will not include debates.
   Swindall said he will ask voters to support him with the
understanding he would resign if convicted. That approach, he said,
would ensure that a new Republican candidate could enter the
subsequent special election.
   ``I believe they will re-elect me with the understanding that an
exoneration after the election is just as good as an exoneration
before the election,'' he said.
</TEXT>
