<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--New York Poll,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presidential Dead Heat in New York</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The presidential race in New York remains a
virtual dead heat between Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis and
Republican George Bush, according to a poll published today.
   Bush led Dukakis by 46-44 percent in the New York Post statewide
survey of 677 registered voters who were questioned Sunday.
   The difference was well within the poll's margin of error of plus
or minus five percentage points. It indicated little shift since a
Post poll a month ago put Bush less than half a percentage point
ahead of Dukakis.
   With 36 electoral votes, New York is second only to California in
importance in the Electoral College.
   ``This is literally a dead-even race, a very close election in
New York, said pollster Arthur Finkelstein, whose firm, Diversified
Research Inc., conducted the telephone survey.
