<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-27 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Dives, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged against the Japanese yen
Thursday, while share prices rose moderately on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 125.90 yen, down 0.90 yen from Wednesday's
close of 126.80 yen. Opening at 125.95 yen, the currency moved
within a range of 125.80 yen to 126.15 yen.
   The dollar tumbled following a U.S. Commerce Department report
Wednesday that the nation's gross national product, the main
economic indicator, grew at an annual rate of 2.2 percent in the
third quarter, after increasing at 3.4 percent in the first quarter
and 3 percent in the second quarter.
   Dealers said the market had expected a 3 percent to 3.5 percent
increase and the low growth rate pushed the dollar down.
   Takamasa Yamasaki of Daiwa Bank said the Bank of Japan intervened
in the market shortly after trading started to support the dollar.
   ``But it is unlikely that only the BOJ's intervention helped the
dollar recover,'' he said, adding that if the dollar fell to the
125-yen level again the central bank would intervene.
   The bank does not comment publicly on its activities.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 199.11-point
winner Wednesday, gained another 102.31 points, or 0.37 percent, to
finish trading at 27,722.92.
   ``Concern over inflation and higher interest rates in the United
States is gone now, and investors are showing strong interest in
buying stocks,'' said a dealer with a major securities firm in
Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
