<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TrappedWhales-Chronolgy     10-27 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trapped Whales-Chronolgy,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Key Events in Attempts To Free Whales</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Trapped Whales Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of major events in the attempts to free the
trapped whales in Barrow, Alaska:
   Oct. 13 _ Three California gray whales are discovered trapped in
ice east of Point Barrow. They apparently became stuck a week
before. Biologists are unable to contact an icebreaking ship to give
aid.
   Oct. 14 _ Whales continue to swim several hundred feet offshore,
using two holes in the ice to breathe. Biologists believe time is
running out for the grays as temperatures drop to minus 13 degrees,
threatening to shrink the whales' breathing space. Efforts fail
again to contact an icebreaker.
   Oct. 18 _ Biologist says one whale may have pneumonia, as an
Alaska Army National Guard Skycrane helicopter sets out to tow a
185-ton Hovercraft-type icebreaking barge 200 miles northwest to the
whales. President Reagan telephones with his support.
   Oct. 19 _ Eskimos cut new holes in the ice, but the barge effort
is hampered by shallow water. Biologists say the whales' health
appears stabilized, and that they are handling their captivity
better than first believed.
   Oct. 20 _ Barge begins its journey but moves only six miles
through sand bars, mud and shallow water. Two Minnesota
brothers-in-law arrive with de-icers to enlarge breathing holes for
the whales.
   Oct. 21 _ One of the whales, nicknamed ``Bone,'' disappears and
is presumed dead. Rescuers try ``Plan B:'' a 5-ton concrete
``bullet'' wielded by a helicopter loaned by the National Guard. An
easterly wind opens ``leads,'' or open water, through the ice within
four miles of the whales. The Soviet Union offers an icebreaker to
help in the rescue.
   Oct. 22 _ Eskimos using chain saws lead the whales almost a
half-mile closer to open water by carving 24 breathing holes in the
ice. The Skycrane dropping its ``bullet'' punches four 15-to-20-foot
holes in the ice at 75-yard intervals, but a massive pressure ridge
of ice stands in the way.
   Oct. 24 _ Whales, apparently spooked by shallower water over a
shoal, reverse course, retreating 800 yards towards shore.
Scientists probe the ice ridge for a weak spot that arriving Soviet
icebreakers could attack.
   Oct. 25 _ Two Soviet icebreakers arrive and begin work smashing
through the ice ridge. The whales follow a detour cut by Eskimos
using chain saws around the shoal they had refused to pass.
   Oct. 26 _ The Soviet ships move within a quarter-mile of the line
of breathing holes. Rescuers used a gargantuan, tractor-like device
propelled by pontoon augers to clear the ice cut by the ships. The
whales moved into the new waterway cut by the vessels, and were seen
swimming in the channel that leads to the open sea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
