<DOCNO> AP881027-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LegalCanons Bjt   10-27 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Legal Canons, Bjt,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers Toot Their Own Horns</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When David Katz made his motion before Judge Julia
Nowicki, Her Honor eyed him with great seriousness, then performed
the opening strains of ``Marche Militaire Francaise.''
   No, they aren't a pair of comics. They're members of the Chicago
Bar Association Symphony Orchestra, a 47-member ensemble of lawyers
who want to make motions in music as well as in the courtroom.
   ``It's a real nice break,'' said Ms. Nowicki, 40, a domestic
relations judge by day, cellist by night with the 2-year-old
orchestra.
   ``It's real nice to be with lawyers and not fighting.''
   Katz, the orchestra's conductor, is the only non-lawyer among the
performers, who get together once a week in Ms. Nowicki's courtroom
for practice.
   About 30 lawyer-musicians were free of their legal duties
Wednesday night when Katz brought down the baton for the orchestra's
fall debut _ its ninth performance since its founding.
   Saint-Saens' ``Marche Militaire'' was followed by Rossini's
``Overture to The Barber of Seville,'' Sir Arthur Sullivan's
``Overture to H.M.S. Pinafore'' and a tribute to another Illinois
lawyer, ``Lincoln Portrait,'' by Aaron Copland.
   Asked to assess the performance, Ms. Nowicki _ whose only formal
music training came during her years in the Chicago public school
system _ at first didn't want to have any part of what might be
self-incriminating testimony.
   But she finally allowed, judiciously, that it was ``pretty good.''
   What the orchestra lacks in musicianship, it makes up in spirit
and seriousness.
   ``I did this only for you,'' bassoonist Carl Silberman told Katz
at the end of the performance in paneled hall at the University Club.
   ``I came into the Rossini cold,'' he added, explaining that he
had never before played the composition.
   Katz, who heads the Adrian (Mich.) Symphony Orchestra, said one
of the pleasant challenges of working with the lawyers is the
variety of ability and experience they bring to their performance.
   ``They take it very seriously, but it's fun for them and that's
what makes it fun to conduct this orchestra,'' said Katz.
   The lawyers' orchestra has its orgin at a Chicago Symphony Chorus
``Messiah'' concert in which amateur singers and musicians perform
with professionals.
   Ms. Nowicki, one of the ``Messiah'' participants, discovered she
was sitting next to another cellist-lawyer. Why not get lawyers
together to make music, they thought.
   ``Part of being a lawyer is the ability to focus in on the work
they do,'' said Katz. ``I think lawyers are all performers at heart
and they always rise to the occasion.''
   Practice is a little nerve-wracking for the courthouse guards
when the players file in for practice.
   Just what might be in those black cases? Everyone's seen the
movies of Prohibition Era gangsters and their machine guns.
   ``This is Chicago, and walking into the courthouse with violin
cases was a real problem for the guards,'' said Katz.
   But everything considered, the musician-lawyers do well, he said.
   ``It's good therapy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
