<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HostageBirthday     10-27 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hostage Birthday,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sister, Friends, Well-Wishers Mark Terry Anderson's 41st Birthday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CADIZ, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now and then, Peggy Say allows herself to think
about what would happen if Terry Anderson does not come home. The
brother she has not seen in 3{ years marked his 41st birthday today
still in captivity.
   ``I tried to think what if he didn't come back, what if they
killed him. I don't know what I would do because I would be so
angry,'' Mrs. Say said during a recent interview at her home in a
lakeside community near Cadiz.
   Anderson's birthday, his fourth in captivity since he was
abducted March 16, 1985, in Beirut was being celebrated with
parties, prayer services and rallies by friends and well-wishers
from the Middle East to his home town of Batavia, N.Y.
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, is the longest held of the 14 foreign hostages abducted in
Lebanon. He was kidnapped by the pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem faction
called Islamic Jihad, or Holy War.
   ``We aren't forgetting him,'' said Terri Fritz of Batavia's radio
station WBAT, which along with a merchants group sponsored a
birthday party with a huge cake decorated with 1,321 candles, one
for each day of captivity.
   In Lebanon, seven newspapers published a letter to Anderson on
the eve of his birthday from a group of journalists working for his
release.
   ``We join our hearts with yours in yearning for your freedom. We
greet you, we salute you and we encourage you,'' said the letter
from the Journalists' Committee to Free Terry Anderson. ``All free
men and women who live by the pen share ... in your captivity.''
   Mrs. Say, 47, who planned to spend Anderson's birthday with
family and friends in New York City, has devoted most of her energy
since his abduction to gaining his release.
   While she has tried to contemplate the worst, she and her
husband, David, are hopeful her brother will see freedom by the
presidential election, less than two weeks away.
   ``It's such an agony of anticipation,'' Mrs. Say said. ``Having
been burned so many times in the past, you try not to think about
it.''
   Something else she would prefer not to think about is how to tell
her brother of the family changes that have occurred during his
absence.
   Their father, Glenn R. Anderson died of cancer in February 1986.
Four months later, their 46-year-old brother, Glenn Jr., died of
cancer. He died four days after making a videotape from his bed
appealing to Anderson's captors.
   Anderson's daughter Gabrielle, who was 10 years old when he was
kidnapped, is now a teen-ager. He has yet to meet a second daughter,
Sulome, whose third birthday was June 7.
   Mrs. Say, a quiet woman with piercing brown eyes, has led
candlelight vigils outside the White House and had coffee with
President Reagan. In 1986, she made a 5,000-mile trip to the
Mideast, and she has appeared on national talk shows.
   ``I simply want my brother back,'' she said.
   Today, students at Buffalo State College in New York planned to
hold a rally on Anderson's behalf, while in Catskill, south of
Albany, parishioners of St. Patrick's church scheduled a prayer
service.
   ``We see it as a chance to sensitize students to the issues of
freedom,'' said Paul DeWald, a journalism professor who organized
the rally. ``Terry is Joe America to us and we have to stand up for
him.''
   Students were to wear armbands with Anderson's name and sign a
huge birthday card that will be forwarded to Lebanon, DeWald said.
   A birthday card also was signed by Anderson's colleagues at the
AP and other journalists in New York City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
