<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-Refugees     10-27 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Refugees,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Participates In Boat People Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in a decade, Vietnam
participated today in multilateral discussions on the problems
caused by Vietnamese fleeing by boat to the shores of Southeast
Asian nations.
   Vietnam's communist ally Laos also took part in the meeting with
members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations and Hong Kong,
which bear the brunt of the exodus, and with Western countries that
resettle the boat people.
   ASEAN groups Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia, Singapore, the
Philippines, and Brunei.
   The two days of informal discussions in Thailand are organized by
the United Nations High Commissioner For Refugees, which is also
participating.
   It was the first time since a 1979 international refugee
conference that Vietnam has participated in talks on a comprehensive
strategy for alleviating the problem. Aid officials say there is a
good possibility of another international conference early next year.
   Some Southeast Asian countries adopted tough policies, even
pushbacks, against Vietnamese boat people after they surged into the
region in 1987 in the highest level in years.
   Vietnam, eager to mend frayed relations with its non-communist
neighbors, agreed this year to cooperate in finding a solution and
has separately held talks with Hong Kong and Malaysia on a possible
program to repatriate some of the Vietnamese.
   A repatriation agreement recently was reached with Hong Kong.
   A total of 28,116 Vietnamese boat people fled to neighboring
countries in 1987, the highest annual figure since 43,676 fled in
1982, according to UNHCR figures. The highest number, 11,195,
arrived in Thailand, nearly triple the 1986 figure.
</TEXT>
