<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wintry Weather in the Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A wintry storm packing snow and winds gusting to 67 mph howled
into the northern Plains from the northern Rockies today, triggering
blizzard warnings in Montana.
   At midnight Wednesday, snow showers extended over sections of
Montana, Wyoming, North Dakota and Minnesota. Scattered rain fell
over southern Minnesota and southern North Dakota.
   In six hours overnight, 2 inches of snow fell in both Billings
and Great Falls, Mont.
   Winds gusted to 67 mph in Rapid City, S.C., and 60 mph in
Sheridan, Wyo.
   A winter storm warning for as much as 4 to 8 inches of snow,
strong winds and local blizzards was issued for east-central Montana
today.
   Snow advisories were posted for the rest of Montana east of the
Continental Divide and northwest Minnesota, and advisories for snow
and gusty winds were up in northern Wyoming and North Dakota. A
watch for winds gusting 60 to 80 mph was in effect for the Front
Range foothills of central Colorado.
   In the East, a lake snow advisory was issued for parts of central
and western New York state, and gale warnings were up for much of
the Great Lakes area.
   Rain fell late Wednesday on southeast Maine and eastern South
Carolina, and scattered thunderstorms boomed over Texas' Big Bend.
   The weather was cold in the Northeast. At midnight, frost and
freezing temperatures chilled the northern Appalachians and the
upper Ohio Valley.
   Today's forecast called for snow over the northern Rockies, the
upper Missouri Valley, North Dakota and northwest Minnesota; and
rain showers from the rest of Minnesota to upper Michigan and
Wisconsin. Showers and occasional thunderstorms were expected from
Illinois to most of Missouri, western Kentucky, Arkansas and much of
Oklahoma; and strong, gusty winds from the Great Lakes to the upper
half of the Mississippi Valley, much of the Plains and the central
Rockies.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 30s in Montana, northern
Wyoming, North Dakota and northern South Dakota; the 40s and 50s
from New England to Virginia, the northern Appalachians, the Great
Lakes, the upper half of the Mississippi Valley, the central Rockies
and much of Washington state; the 80s in much of Florida, the
central Gulf Coast and Texas; the 80s and low 90s in the desert
Southwest; and the 60s and 70s in the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 23
degrees at Elmira, N.Y., to 77 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 53 cloudy; Boston 42 fair; Buffalo 35 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 58 cloudy; Cincinnati 28 fair; Cleveland 29 fair;
Detroit 28 fair; Miami 69 fair; New York 42 fair; Philadelphia 32
fair; Pittsburgh 31 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine 39 partly cloudy;
Washington 36 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 38 windy; Chicago 37 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 59 foggy; Denver 47 fair; Des Moines 46 cloudy;
Indianapolis 32 fair; Kansas City 52 partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 47 cloudy; Nashville 35 fair; New Orleans 65 partly cloudy; St.
Louis 46 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 51 fair; Anchorage 27 snow; Las Vegas 66 fair;
Los Angeles 60 hazy; Phoenix 75 fair; Salt Lake City 49 fair; San
Diego 63 cloudy; San Francisco 53 cloudy; Seattle 44 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 34 fair; Toronto 36 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
