<DOCNO> AP881027-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0613EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea     10-27 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-U.S. Protests Escalate, Campus Clashes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students burned an effigy of
Uncle Sam today and pelted riot police with hundreds of firebombs
and rocks as anti-U.S. and anti-government protests continued on
campuses.
   ``Drive out the Yankees,'' they shouted.
   Dozens of police were hit with rocks and burned by exploding
firebombs in violent protests at two university campuses in Seoul _
Konkuk and Dongkuk.
   The demonstrations were confined to the streets in front of the
campuses.
   Earlier today, about 20 students shouting ``Yankee go home''
attacked the Koram Bank, a Korea-U.S. joint venture bank in southern
Seoul, with firebombs and rocks. Police said two students were
arrested. No damage was reported.
   At Seoul National University, about 300 students demonstrated
peacefully, demanding the withdrawal of U.S. soldiers and nuclear
weapons they claim the American military keeps in South Korea.
   Students also urged the U.S. government to repeal its agreement
with South Korea that allows the U.S. military jurisdiction over
military personnel and their dependents involved in criminal
proceedings.
   On two campuses in Kwangju and Taegu, south of Seoul, police said
hundreds of students hurled firebombs and stones and police fired
tear gas to block them from marching off their campuses after
anti-government, anti-U.S. rallies.
   It was not immediately known if anyone was injured or arrested.
   Anti-U.S. protests have been on the rise in recent weeks, fanned
by radical students demanding the withdrawal of the 42,000 U.S.
troops stationed here under a mutual defense pact.
   On Wednesday, radicals attacked a U.S. cultural center in Taegu,
damaging three cars in the center in the third assault on U.S.
facilities in two weeks.
   U.S. military authorities confirmed today that tight security
measures adopted at U.S. installations during the Olympic Games
would continue due to ``continued unsettled conditions.''
   Bill Fullerton, a U.S. Army spokesman, said the military would
continue procedures such as tightened identification checks and
security monitoring.
   He said an advisory aimed at military personnel and their
families was issued through the American Forces Korea Network and
the newspaper Pacific Stars and Stripes.
   The advisory cautioned U.S. troops to ``be mindful of their
personal conduct while off U.S. installations'' and not to interfere
in South Korean political affairs.
   The release also said local commanders may further increase
security around their installations to avoid potential problems
related to ``continued unsettled conditions.''
   South Korean police also have stepped up security around U.S.
legations with more contingents of police patrols in response to
firebomb attacks by radical students.
</TEXT>
