<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0621EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PentagonInquiry     10-27 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pentagon Inquiry,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Documents Detail Attempts To Destroy Evidence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of a paper supply company being
investigated in the Pentagon fraud and bribery probe told employees
to throw out documents that prosecutors say contained incriminating
evidence, court papers show.
   Federal agents seized the documents later that day, June 21, from
trash containers at the Kane Paper Co. on Long Island, according to
the search warrant application, which along with other court papers
was first made public Wednesday.
   The papers, released by U.S. District Judge Edward Korman in
response to a newspaper request, show that James Kane, the firm's
founder, called his company three times to talk with employees about
throwing out business papers.
   Kane's conversations were intercepted by FBI agents who had been
secretly monitoring phone conversations at Kane Paper, which
supplies paper products to aerospace companies.
   Kane is also the president of the Long Island Aerospace Political
Action Committee and has been described by officials as an associate
of Charles Gardner, a private consultant and a former vice president
of the Unisys Corp. whose home has also been searched.
   Unisys is one of the nation's largest computer manufacturers and
a major military contractor. Search warrants were served at the
company's Eagen, Minn., and Great Neck plants.
   A secretary at Kane Paper said Kane was out of town Wednesday and
unavailable for comment. A message left with Kane's attorney,
Vincent Fuller in Washington, was not immediately returned.
   Authorities have said agents deliberately had not gone to Kane's
plant on June 14 when they staged the first nationwide series of
raids involving the defense contracting scandal because they wanted
to continue monitoring the wiretaps.
   On June 21, Kane called in the morning and spoke to an employee
identified as Thomasa Avellina, according to court testimony by FBI
agent Dan Melore.
   ``Kane says to Avellina, `I think what you should do quietly is
go through anything that might be around, that you want to get rid
of, OK?''' Melore said. ``Avellina says, `To throw them out?'''
Melore said. ``Kane: `No. Yeah.''' Avellina answers, `OK,''' Melore
said.
   Kane again called Avellina in mid-morning and asked him, ``Did
you get rid of the (blank) did you get rid of most of yours,''
Melore said. ``Avellina: yeah.''
   Kane called a third time around noon and spoke with another
employee, Daniel Carroll, to ask if Avellina had thrown out the
documents, Melore said.
   Under questioning by Korman, Melore said agents at the plant had
seen business documents in at least one trash container. Those
documents were later seized.
   ``That's the circumstances which leads us to believe that at this
point they were attempting to destroy incriminating documents,''
Melore said.
   Court documents made public earlier indicated that investigators
were seeking information at Kane Paper about the possible extortion
of campaign contributions from companies by private consultants and
others.
   Korman also questioned Melore about Kane's relationship with
Gardner.
   ``I know when we did the wiretap, you persuaded me that Kane was
engaging in conversations with Gardner that would relate and could
relate to the Unisys matter in which Gardner was involved,'' Korman
said. ``But with respect to documents that are at Kane's place of
business, that's another story. Kane wasn't involved in defrauding
Unisys.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881027-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0649EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SavannahRiver     10-27 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Savannah River,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Number Of Leukemia Deaths Reported Near Savannah River Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nuclear Safety</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal study of workers at the Savannah
River nuclear plant found twice the usual rate of deaths from
leukemia.
   The finding by the Oak Ridge Associated Universities Center for
Epidemiologic Research is consistent with the results of a study by
the Du Pont Co. released in 1976, plant officials said in a
statement Wednesday. Du Pont runs the federal plant under contract.
   The Oak Ridge study included 1,274 male hourly workers who were
hired before 1955 and worked five to 15 years. Overall, they had
fewer than expected deaths from all causes, but six leukemia deaths,
a greater number than would be expected.
   ``The finding of an increase in the number of leukemia deaths in
this population warrants further investigation. We are conducting a
study in which a full assessment will be made of radiation and
chemical exposure,'' said Donna L. Cragle, head of a team of
researchers at the Oak Ridge center.
   Cragle said in a statement released by the plant that further
studies are under way to determine if the leukemia deaths are in any
way related to the workers' exposure to radiation or chemicals on
the job.
   Radiation monitoring data for the men who died of leukemia showed
that all were exposed to less than the current annual occupational
radiation limit.
   The researchers' findings were reported this month in the
American Journal of Industrial Medicine. They have been presented to
plant employees and managers.
   Oak Ridge Associated Universities is a private, non-profit
association of 49 colleges and universities based in Tennessee that
is a management and operating contractor for the Department of
Energy.
   In a related development, a national group of 60,000 physicians
and medical students called Wednesday for the creation of a national
medical board to assess public and environmental health problems
associated with the operation of the Savannah River plant and other
U.S. nuclear weapons plants.
   Physicians for Social Responsibility said production of nuclear
weapons should not be resumed at Savannah River until public health
questions related to the plant's operation are resolved.
   And 28 members of the House Armed Services Committee called
Wednesday for the Department of Energy to prove that the plant's
reactors are safe before they are restarted.
   In separate but similar letters to President Reagan and Energy
Secretary John Herrington, the bi-partisan coalition also urged the
department to ask for enough money to correct mounting technical and
environmental problems at the facility, near Aiken, and at other
nuclear weapons production facilities.
   The letters, written by Rep. John Spratt, D-S.C., and signed by
about 27 others, place blame for the deteriorating complex on the
department.
   They say the result is that the nation is ``unable to produce
nuclear materials needed to maintain the deterrent value of our
nuclear weapons.''
   Unlike a similar letter signed last week by 12 congressmen, the
Spratt letters do not criticize Du Pont or any other contractors
that operate DOE's weapons facilities.
   ``The crisis has not arisen suddenly but over a long period, and
it stems from inadequate attention to maintenance, safety and
operating conditions,'' said the letter to Herrington.
   Among the demands in the letter to Reagan is the appointment of a
five-member safety panel approved by Congress during the summer. The
panel would represent another check on the Energy Department's
operations.
   Herrington announced Oct. 11 that the department plans to restart
one of the Savannah River reactors by Dec. 31. Except for an
abortive attempt to restart another reactor in August, all of the
plant's reactors have been shut since April due to safety concerns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
