<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Ruby-Survivors     10-27 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ruby-Survivors,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`In Less Than One Minute, The Ship Was Gone'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Ruby</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALBERTO MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TACLOBAN, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vilma Bande was frightened as giant
waves rocked the passenger ship Dona Marilyn, but the crew urged her
to remain calm and take off her life jacket.
   Moments later, she was adrift in stormy seas and the vessel was
gone.
   The 19-year-old nurse, en route to visit her parents in Tacloban,
was among up to 500 passengers bound for Tacloban from Manila aboard
the ship when it sank Monday during the height of Typhoon Ruby.
   She and more than 100 other survivors _ dazed and sullen after
their ordeal _ arrived today in this city 350 miles southeast of
Manila. The survivors included at least six children, one a
4-year-old girl.
   Asked what happened to her parents, the girl sighed: ``They're
gone.''
   Survivors appeared bruised and shaken. Several told of struggling
for three or more hours in violent seas before washing ashore on
small islands near where the vessel sank.
   Few survivors smiled or waved as they walked from the ship that
brought them to Tacloban. Some still clutched the life jackets that
had saved them.
   In Manila, the coast guard said some survivors remained today on
small islands _ too shaken to agree to board rescue vessels.
Officials said several were in shock.
   Miss Bande said that as giant waves battered the 2,855-ton Dona
Marilyn on Monday, she and hundreds of others anxiously waited on
deck as the crew frantically tried to pump water from the ship.
   ``There was no announcement. The crew members were shouting
`don't panic, remove your life jackets, relax, this is normal,'''
she said. But few passengers, if any, heeded the advice.
   Suddenly, she recalled, a giant wave ``as tall as a building''
crashed over the deck and the vessel rolled to the side.
   ``I jumped and in less than one minute, I turned my back and the
ship was gone,'' she said.
   Lea Hugo, 29, donned a life jacket and leaped into the raging sea
although she did not know how to swim.
   ``I was struggling in the water,'' she said. ``I saw a piece of
wood and clung to it. The next thing I knew, somebody grabbed me and
helped me to shore.''
   Miss Hugo washed ashore on Almagro island, about 20 miles from
where officials believe the Dona Marilyn sank.
   She said some island fishermen braved the raging seas and set out
in small boats to rescue passengers. Other survivors washed up on
the beaches, barely strong enough to walk.
   The ordeal has left Miss Hugo, a nurse, temporarily blinded.
Still, she is thankful to be alive.
   ``I am looking at you but I can only see your silhouette,'' she
said as tears streamed down her bruised face. ``I guess I'm just
lucky.''
</TEXT>
