<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0455,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Issue Leaflets Asking Israelis To Withdraw</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Offbeat Politics, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with 14 wounded today. CHANGES byline.
No pickup.
^By G.G. LaBELLE</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and wounded 14
Palestinians during stone-throwing clashes in the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip today, Arab reports and hospital officials said.
   A fundamentalist Moslem group called for more general strikes
against Israeli occupation. ``Let's burn the land under the
occupiers,'' said a leaflet distributed by the Hamas, or Zeal,
movement.
   The PLO-backed underground leadership of the Palestinian uprising
also issued a new leaflet, addressed to the Israeli people,
appealing for Israel's withdrawal from the occupied lands and
establishment of a Palestinian state.
   Clashes with soldiers were reported in at least four cities and
towns in the West Bank and Gaza. The army said it was checking
reports of 14 Palestinians wounded.
   In Nablus, the West Bank's largest city, Palestinian youths threw
stones and bottles at soldiers at a protest called by underground
leaders against Israel's demand for new license plates on West Bank
cars, Arab reporters said.
   Soldiers responded with tear gas and live ammunition, wounding
six Palestinians ranging in age from 14 to 24, said officials at
Al-Ittihad and St. John's hospitals.
   The protest involved hundreds of cars and trucks blocking roads
in response to an appeal over loudspeakers to stop vehicles wherever
they were at 9 a.m. The move was to protest a plan to require
license plates that show exactly where the car is registered and
cost owners $250.
   A 17-year-old girl and a 16-year-old boy were wounded in the West
Bank village of Idna, according to hospital officials who said
soldiers shot when residents tried to block an army unit from
entering the village near Hebron.
   In the Gaza Strip, six Palestinians were reported shot with
plastic bullets after a stone-throwing melee began on Palestine
Street in Gaza City and youths set ablaze tires in the Khan Yunis
refugee camp.
   One of the wounded in Khan Yunis was a 41-year-old woman shot in
the chest with a plastic bullet, hospital officials said.
   Three schools in Gaza City were ordered closed by the army today
to halt violence, Arab reports said. They said three other schools
were shut down by soldiers Wednesday in Khan Yunis.
   In violence Wednesday, a 3-year-old Palestinian girl died in the
Gaza Strip town of Khan Yunis, and her family claimed the death was
caused by tear gas inhalation, the army said. Arab sources said 10
Palestinians were shot and wounded by soldiers during scattered
clashes with soldiers.
   At least 303 Palestinians have been killed, along with six
Israelis, since the uprising against Israeli occupation began last
Dec. 8.
   The new Hamas leaflet urged Palestinians to stage four general
strikes against Israeli rule in the next three weeks.
</TEXT>
