<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless Hoax,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Promise of Free Dinners for Homeless Turns Out to be Hoax</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bright yellow handbills offering free food for
the homeless turned out to be bogus after dozens of people showed up
looking for dinner at a downtown restaurant.
   ``I'm really outraged,'' said Lymon Lindstrom, a homeless person
who waited outside the Kansas City Barbeque restaurant for several
hours Wednesday before finding out the offer was a hoax.
   The sponsor was listed as the San Diego Active 20+30 Club, a
charitable organization with about 30 members which was having a
meeting inside the restaurant at the time the handbills said the
free dinners would be served.
   ``Someone is playing a joke. That's all I know,'' said club
president George Kvaas, whose phone number was on the handbills.
   Cindy Blair, one of the restaurant owners, said limited supplies
made it impossible to provide food for those attracted by the
handbills. An apology sign was placed in a window.
   Steve Sapper, a former club president whom the handbills credited
with donating their printing cost, called the incident ``a cruel
hoax'' by unknown individuals.
   ``We don't understand any of this. We've done a lot of good
things for the community,'' said Sapper, noting that helping
underprivileged children has been a primary focus for the group.
