<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0438,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Voters Should Elect Bush ``As Act of Self-Defense'</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release 11:30 a.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON </HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 16 grafs new with Reagan embargoed speech; picks up pvs
5th graf bgng, In light; DELETES last 7 grafs to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said today Americans
should vote for Republican George Bush ``as an act of self-defense''
because Democratic rival Michael Dukakis favors gun controls, and to
say ``no'' to higher taxes.
   Playing to the conservative values of his audience of GOP
partisans at a Little Rock airport rally, the president portrayed
Dukakis as a far-out liberal who would raise taxes and threaten the
nation's defenses _ but is trying to disguise his real goals from
the voters.
   ``I have to say, how can a man running for president of the
United States look the American people in the eye and tell you that
his ideology doesn't matter?'' Reagan asked in a prepared speech.
   In one of his hardest-hitting speeches yet as Bush's chief
surrogate on the campaign trail, Reagan suggested that the
Massachusetts governor has used his newly toughened attacks on the
GOP nominee to hide his own liberal record.
   ``Ladies and gentlemen, if he is saying to you that what he
believes doesn't matter, isn't he really saying that what each one
of us believes doesn't matter?'' Reagan asked.
   Embarking on a week-long, cross-country tour, Reagan was
traveling from Arkansas to Missouri and California to tout his vice
president as crime-busting yet compassionate man who deserves to
inherit the White House Oval Office.
   ``On Nov. 8th, go into that polling booth and do some negative
campaigning of your own, the right kind of negative campaigning: Say
`no' to new taxes and `yes' to the Republican ticket,'' the
president told his audience.
   He charged that Dukakis would allow only ``the military and
police'' to carry guns, and said voters should cast their ballots
for Bush and his running mate, Dan Quayle, ``as an act of
self-defense.''
   Dukakis says he wants to keep guns out of the hands of criminals,
but favors their ownership by hunters, sportsmen and homeowners who
want to protect their lives and property.
   Throughout his speech, Reagan boasted of what ``George and I''
had achieved. ``For eight years, George Bush and I have worked
side-by-side in the White House, during times of crisis and times of
historic triumph and achievements,'' he said.
   For example, the president said, ``You know, violent crime has
fallen significantly since 1981 because George and I put criminals
on notice.''
   The president claimed that under Bush's leadership, a federal
task force had slashed 600 million man-hours of paperwork a year
from the government's workload, spearheaded the administration's
anti-drug offensive and paved the way toward the U.S.-Soviet treaty
banning medium-range nuclear missiles.
   Reagan praised Bush as ``strong, decent loyal, wise, capable and
compassionate _ a man who has the qualities necessary to fill the
office of president.''
   He added: ``As for a certain governor from a certain New England
state, I'd best let someone else do the talking. Former Arkansas
Congressman Ed Bethune said he'd met this fellow 10 years ago and
his reaction was, let me quote him now, `I have never met a person
in my whole life who is more liberal'.''
   Reagan, obviously buoyed by recent polls showing Bush widening
his lead over the Democratic nominee, said, ``I have little doubt
that the people of the United States are going to do exactly what I
did eight years ago: They are going to choose George Bush.''
   At a GOP fund-raising luncheon Wednesday in Baltimore, the
president said Bush has Democrats ``squirming'' and ``squealing''
because he's shown them to be what ``they really are,'' as liberals
who stand outside the mainstream of American values.
   In light of Bush's double-digit leads in the polls, Reagan also
will spend some time next week boosting local GOP candidates in
several cities in southern California, as well as Nevada and
Wisconsin.
   Amid his hectic schedule of cross-country campaigning, Reagan has
sandwiched in a weekend respite at his Santa Barbara ranch with his
wife, Nancy.
   Since Labor Day, Reagan has made 21 political appearances in 13
states and has raised about $8.8 million for the national and state
Republican campaign coffers.
</TEXT>
