<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTL     10-27 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Canadian Back in Running for PTL</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second Canadian businessman is back in
the bidding for the assets of PTL, the financially troubled ministry
of deposed television evangelist Jim Bakker.
   Real estate magnate Peter Thomas of Vancouver asked U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds to consider his proposal along with
that of Stephen Mernick of Toronto.
   Four of PTL's largest creditors joined in Thomas' motion, which
was filed Wednesday in federal bankruptcy court. Attorneys for two
creditors said they weren't endorsing Thomas's $113 million offer
over Mernick's $115 million bid, but that they want Reynolds to have
a choice from at least two competing bids.
   Reynolds is scheduled to rule on Thomas' motion Nov. 16, which is
the same day he has set to consider a motion approving a sale to
Mernick.
   PTL, which has been in bankruptcy proceedings since June 1987,
must sell its assets to pay debts that could amount to more than
$130 million.
   PTL's holdings include the 500-acre Heritage USA theme park,
1,700 acres of undeveloped land and the PTL satellite TV network.
   Mernick had apparently won the bidding Oct. 4, when PTL trustee
M.C. ``Red'' Benton accepted his $115 million offer and promised not
to negotiate further with anyone else. Other bidders can go directly
to the court, but none had done so until Thomas filed his motion
Wednesday.
   In accepting Mernick's bid, Benton said he had rejected a $113
million offer by Thomas in September, because Thomas's $46 million
cash down payment would not be due until September 1989.
   Mernick's offer includes $50 million cash by Dec. 31. However,
Mernick has until Nov. 15 to back out of the deal with no penalty.
   Thomas' new offer still has a $113 million total price, but
matches Mernick's $50 million cash. Thomas would have until Feb. 28
to back out, and until June 30 to close the sale and come up with
the cash.
   Thomas announced his re-entry in the bidding at his Vancouver,
British Columbia, headquarters.
   ``We're elated,'' Thomas said. ``We didn't like being on the
sidelines. We always felt our offer was one of the best.''
   In a telephone interview with The Charlotte (N.C.) Observer,
Thomas said he thinks his offer may be more attractive to Reynolds
because he promises to maintain Heritage USA as a Christian retreat,
while Mernick, who is Jewish, makes no such pledge.
   ``I think Mernick's and my offers are so dramatically different
that it's right the judge should look at them,'' Thomas said. ``My
offer is committed to keep the ambience of the site like it is ...
and Mr. Mernick's offer is more of paving it and putting a shopping
center on it.''
   Mernick said two weeks ago that he had made no decision about
what he would do with Heritage USA, but added that the undeveloped
land would be ``excellent for condominiums, shopping centers and
commercial buildings.''
</TEXT>
