<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CabotPrizes     10-27 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cabot Prizes,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>4 Journalists Awarded 50th Annual Cabot Prizes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Journalists from Argentina, Brazil, Peru and the
United States have won the 50th annual Maria Moors Cabot Prizes for
fostering understanding between the Americas, Columbia University
announced.
   The winners announced Wednesday were Nicholas Clark Asheshov,
editor of The Lima Times and The Andean Report of Lima, Peru; Robert
Civita, creator and publisher of Veja of Sao Paulo, Brazil; Stephen
Kinzer, foreign correspondent of The New York Times; and
Hermenegildo Sabat, staff cartoonist of Clarin in Buenos Aires,
Argentina.
   The awards, to be presented in ceremonies at the university this
evening, are given for distinguished contributions to inter-American
understanding and freedom of information.
   The winners receive gold medals and $1,000. Clarin and The New
York Times are previous Cabot winners and will receive silver bars
to be added to plaques the newspapers received earlier.
   The Cabot prizes, the oldest international journalism awards,
were established by Godfrey Lowell Cabot of Boston as a memorial to
his wife. Since 1939, 179 medals and 139 special citations have been
given to journalists from 30 countries.
   Asheshov is also the correspondent in Lima for The Sunday Times,
the Daily Mail and The Daily Telegraph, all of London, and The Miami
Herald.
   Civita is also president of the Brazilian Magazine Publishers
Association.
   Kinzer, a former aide to Democratic presidential candidate
Michael Dukakis, has been correspondent for the Times in Nicaragua
since 1983. Sabat has been a cartoonist for Clarin since 1973.
</TEXT>
