<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0515,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Funerals Held For 19 Killed In Israeli Air Raid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with funerals. TRIMS to tighten. No
pickup.
^By FAROUK NASSAR</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smarting from one of the heaviest Israeli
air raids on their strongholds this year, Palestinians today buried
19 people killed in an air assault and ensuing ground battle near
the port city of Sidon.
   Although the Palestine Liberation Organiztaion said it planned
mass funerals for the victims, they were buried in quiet ceremonies
in Sidon's main cemetery and a Palestinian graveyard in the nearby
village of Darb el-Seem.
   There were no anti-Israeli chants or cries for revenge that had
characterized funerals for victims of previous Israeli attacks.
   ``We just couldn't risk mass gatherings,'' said a guerrilla
officer at one of the funerals. He refused to give his name. ``With
Israel's appetite for attacking at its peak, we figured it's prudent
to keep a low profile.''
   Police said rescuers using gasoline lanterns searched the rubble
of a guerrilla base of 30 buildings pulverized in the Wednesday
morning bombing of Sidon's Mieh Mieh refugee camp. They dug out nine
bodies.
   A family of six _ a man, his wife and their two sons and
daughters _ were among the bodies. The children's ages ranged
between six and 15, police said. The three other victims were
guerrillas.
   Six bodies were found immediately after the air raid on the base,
which belonged to Palestine Liberation Organization chairman Yasser
Aarafat's mainstream Fatah guerrilla group.
   Four other Palestinian guerrillas were killed in a ground battle
that began after the raid with Israel's main proxy force, the South
Lebanon Army militia.
   The four guerrillas belonged to the radical Fatah-Revolutionary
Council, which is headed by the notorious Palestinian terrorist
mastermind, Abu Nidal.
   The Mieh Mieh air raid claimed the second heaviest casualty toll
of Israel's 18 air strikes in Lebanon this year. Twenty-six people
were killed and 30 wounded in the first air raid north of Sidon Jan.
3.
   Police and guerrilla spokesmen regarded Wednesday's assault as
the worst in terms of destruction and guerrilla casualties.
   ``Mieh Mieh has suffered the most severe destruction since
Israel's 1982 invasion'' of Lebanon, said a police spokesman in
Sidon. He cannot be named under standing regulations.
   Among those killed was Col. Mustafa Daoud, commander of the
1,000-strong Fatah militia.
   The Mieh Mieh raid was followed 4{ hours later by two bombing
runs against guerrilla bases of pro-Syrian Palestinian factions just
south of Beirut and in hills overlooking the coastal town of Damour,
midway between Beirut and Sidon. At least one guerrilla was wounded.
   The Israeli strikes followed two foiled Palestinian guerrilla
attempts to infiltrate into northern Israel from south Lebanon on
Tuesday. The attempts were uncovered by Israeli troops and the
predominantly Christian SLA militiamen who patrol Israel's
self-designated ``security zone'' in south Lebanon.
   Israel warplanes struck bases in Lebanon on Friday and Sunday in
retaliation for a suicide car bombing in the security zone last week
in which eight Israeli soldiers were killed and nine people wounded.
   Twenty-one people were killed and 34 wounded in the two strikes,
which were directed against Palestinian and Lebanese Shiite Moslem
bases in south and southeast Lebanon.
   The pro-Iranian Shiite Hezbollah, or Party of God, had claimed
responsibility for the suicide bombing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
