<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Gacy-GOPLeaflet 1stLd-Writethru a0498 10-27 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gacy-GOP Leaflet, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0498,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Aide Questions Authenticity of Gacy Letter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, `The letter...', with 2 grafs to add that
similar letter sent to AP. Picks up 12th graf pvs, `The state...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERRI COLBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats and Republicans traded
recriminations after condemned multiple murderer John Wayne Gacy
apparently criticized the use of his name in GOP campaign leaflets
as ``disgusting and exploitive.''
   Gacy, through a spokesman for the Illinois Department of
Corrections, confirmed Wednesday that he sent a letter to GOP
officials about leaflets that say Gacy would have been ``eligible
for weekend passes'' had he committed his 33 murders in
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis' home state.
   The Republican leaflets were labeled ``garbage'' earlier this
month by Dukakis, the Democratic presidential candidate. And GOP
presidential candidate George Bush said Saturday he disapproved of
them.
   But Judith Erwin, Illinois communications director for Dukakis'
campaign, suggested Wednesday that Republicans might have somehow
concocted Gacy's letter.
   ``It is really right up their alley, and an alley is where they
are trying to conduct the campaign,'' she said.
   ``The language in that letter is language out of a campaign
brochure. Tell me how a man on Death Row is so well informed about
the inner workings of a presidential campaign.''
   Earlier, Stuart Piper, executive director of the Illinois
Republican Party, had characterized the letter by saying, ``Here
again we have another example of a criminal who is apparently
supportive of Mike Dukakis.''
   Later, he denied any party involvement.
   ``We don't condone such campaign tactics or those remarks from
the Dukakis campaign,'' he said. ``We held this letter for two days
and it wasn't until Gacy apparently sent this letter to a news
organization that this story came about. We had nothing to do with
it and didn't feel that it merited any further public discussion due
to the source.''
   In a one-page typewritten letter received Monday at state
Republican headquarters, Gacy wrote: ``It is an insult to the voting
public that the Illinois Republican State Central Committee has to
drop to such a sleazy level by exploiting the name of John Wayne
Gacy in order to scare people into voting for George Bush.''
   A virtually identical letter, dated Oct. 23, was mailed to The
Associated Press. After a request from the AP, GOP officials
provided a copy of the letter they received.
   The letter sent to the Republicans called the campaign literature
``disgusting and exploitive'' and said, ``Can't Bush run on his own
record and the truth, instead of all this scarey (sic) fantasy?''
   The state GOP mailings refer to a furlough program for prisoners
carried on under Dukakis' administration and to a convicted killer,
Willie Horton, who brutalized a Maryland couple while on furlough
from a Massachusetts prison.
   ``If John Wayne Gacy had committed his atrocious crimes in Boston
instead of Chicago, he would be eligible for weekend passes under
Michael Dukakis' furlough program,'' the leaflets said.
   Gacy was convicted in 1980 in the killings of 33 young men and
boys, 29 of whom were found buried in his home near Chicago.
   He was sentenced to death and is imprisoned at the Menard
Correctional Center in southern Illinois, but appeals are pending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
