<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Ecclesia-Abuse     10-27 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ecclesia-Abuse,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Child Allegedly Beaten To Death At Father's Commune Is Buried</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 8-year-old girl who was allegedly beaten to
death by members of a commune founded by her father was mourned by
about 150 people, including her uncle, who said he hoped others
could learn from the tragedy.
   Dayna Lorea Broussard's uncle, Henry Webb, was the only speaker
at the funeral Wednesday at the Angelus Crenshaw Chapel to refer
directly to the circumstances surrounding the girl's death.
   ``This is an experience that we've never experienced before,''
Webb told the mourners, as Dayna's body lay in a pink embossed
casket. ``Through this experience may we learn to love one another
better and to experience life more.''
   The girl's parents did not attend the service.
   Dayna, who would have turned 9 on Monday, died Oct. 14 allegedly
from beatings and whippings administered by members of the Ecclesia
Athletic Association, a group formed to help inner-city children.
   The girl's parents stayed away from the funeral because of the
media attention it has attracted, said the child's maternal
grandmother, Viola Grant, who arranged the service.
   Dayna's father, Eldridge Broussard Jr., a former college
basketball star in Oregon, organized the athletic commune in Sandy,
Ore., as a training center and an extension of the Watts Christian
Center, founded by his father.
   Authorities in Clackamas County, Ore., have alleged that the
children found at a home there were forced to watch as adults, using
paddles or electrical cords, administered ritualistic beatings to
children.
   Broussard was in Los Angeles at the time of his daughter's death
but has since returned to Sandy.
   Broussard has maintained that Ecclesia no longer exists,
sabotaged by biased news media portrayals that likened his group to
a cult. He also has blamed the media for his daughter's death.
   Four people have been charged with first-degree manslaughter in
the Ecclesia case, and the Oregon Children's Services Division has
taken more than 50 children into protective custody.
   The four people charged in the girl's death have pleaded innocent.
   Meanwhile, a misdemeanor complaint alleging child endangerment
and inflicting illegal corporal punishment was filed Wednesday in
Los Angeles against Alvin Elvis Broussard, the 25-year-old brother
of Eldridge.
   The complaint stemmed from a police visit to the Watts Christian
Center on Oct. 16 that was prompted by news reports of Dayna's death
in Oregon, said Mike Qualls, a spokesman for City Attorney James
Hahn.
   Officers at the center found a 10-year-old boy with bruises who
said he had been struck by Alvin Broussard, Hahn said in a statement.
</TEXT>
