<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Customs-Protest     10-27 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Customs-Protest,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Customs Inspectors Claim Computer System Lets Illegal Drugs
In</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Customs Service inspectors are protesting a computer system
that they say allows more drugs to enter the country because it
tells them how thoroughly to search, or not to search, cargo
shipments.
   Seven years ago, Customs agents say, they examined about a
quarter of all cargo imported through Miami International Airport,
but now 90 percent of the items pass through untouched under the
program that has computers target likely contraband shipments.
   ``They have created an honor system for importers,'' said Reta
Grant, president-elect of the National Treasury Employees Union in
Miami. ``Instead of being on site to inspect merchandise, we are
sitting behind computers. It's like taking a policeman off the beat
and putting him in an office and expecting him to do his job.''
   But agency administrators say that the nationwide computer system
that was the target of the protest Wednesday was responsible for
recent seizures of large amounts of cocaine and that any problems
with the system were being corrected.
   ``We know that incidents have happened and where we can make a
change or an adjustment we do that,'' said Robert Murphy, deputy
assistant regional commissioner of commercial operations for the
Customs Service in Chicago. ``If it was not for the system, there
would be a lot more incidents and shipments of drugs getting
through.''
   About 20 Customs workers picketed outside the Miami airport,
carrying signs bearing slogans such as ``Customs computer system is
a welcome mat for drug smugglers'' and ``Customs commission's
computers create chaos.''
   Federal workers also demonstrated outside the Customs Service's
regional office in Chicago, and similar demonstrations were held at
other large ports of entry.
   The Customs Service began using the computer system in 1984 and
it is now operating at all of the 300 official ports of entry in the
United States, said spokesman Ed Kittredge in Washington.
   The system targets specific cargo shipments for thorough searches
based on various criteria, including whether the shipment is a
first-time import to a particular company, whether the merchandise
comes from a drug-related country and whether people suspected by
the Customs Service handled the goods, he said.
   Anthony Hartnett, a customs inspector at Chicago's O'Hare
International Airport, said the agency was relying too much on the
computers.
   ``Computers are good, but they should be a tool and not the sole
thing the agency relies on, and that's what's happened,'' said
Hartnett. ``When the computer and the inspector disagree, the final
vote should go to the inspector.''
   While inspectors technically may ignore the computer's advice,
``We've been told that when the computer said an extensive search
was not necessary we should go along with it,'' Hartnett said.
   Kittredge said the computer is only a tool. ``Any inspector is
encouraged to look at any cargo he or she suspects,'' he said.
   In at least one case, drugs were discovered by inspectors who
disregarded the computer's determination that a shipment needed only
a cursory check, said George King, a union spokesman in Chicago.
   In that incident in July, the computer said a shipment labeled
coffee that arrived at Newark International Airport in New Jersey
did not need to be checked thoroughly, he said. But the inspector
was suspicious because the shipment weight a lot more than others
the importer had received, he said.
   ``The inspector ... searched intensively and found 6,000 pounds
of cocaine concealed in blocks of chocolate,'' he said. ``The
computer said, `Let it go.' The person said, `Wait a minute.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881027-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NebraskaSenate 1stLd-Writethru a0452 10-27 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nebraska Senate, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0452,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Republican Nebraska, Democrat Kerrey Top Contender for Senate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 9th graf bgng ``No'' to add audience response</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT SONNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republican designation next to a
candidate's name in Nebraska usually means an election winner, but
Democrat Bob Kerrey has emerged as the leading contender for the
state's U.S. Senate seat.
   ``In this state, George Bush will win if all he is doing is
breathing that day,'' state Sen. Ernie Chambers, the New Alliance
Party candidate for the Senate, said referring to the GOP
presidential nominee.
   Only one Democratic presidential candidate, Lyndon B. Johnson,
has carried Nebraska since Franklin D. Roosevelt's win in 1936.
   ``This is a Republican state,'' said Rep. Virginia Smith, R-Neb.,
the 77-year-old grand dame of Nebraska politics. ``Nebraskans'
philosophy is a relatively conservative philosophy.''
   But the 45-year-old Kerrey, former governor of Nebraska, leads
Republican Sen. David Karnes by more than 20 points in recent
statewide polls, and political observers are hard-pressed when asked
for clear reasons.
   Some cite Kerrey's record in the Vietnam War where he lost part
of his leg and received the Medal of Honor. Others attribute his
success to good looks and star quality; Kerrey attracted national
attention when he dated actress Debra Winger.
   Still others believe Kerrey's independence from the Democratic
Party makes him appealing to Nebraskans.
   At a recent Rotary Club speech, Kerrey was asked if he could
provide one good reason, other than his party affiliation, for
supporting Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   ``No,'' Kerrey replied, sending his audience into peals of
laughter.
   He later explained to the group that he supports the Democratic
ticket but that he and the White House contender don't agree on
everything.
   ``Bob Kerrey is a unique individual who personifies certain
traits that Nebraskans respect,'' said Dave Heineman, an adviser to
Rep. Hal Daub, R-Neb. ``He is uniquely different.''
   To make matters worse for Republicans, Karnes has encountered a
series of problems since his appointment by GOP Gov. Kay Orr to the
Senate after the death of Ed Zorinsky.
   Many Republicans believed Daub deserved the appointment, and
although Karnes and his backers say the wounds have healed others
say bad feelings still exist.
   ``There is a deep wound, a deep split in the Republican Party,''
said Sen. J. James Exon, D-Neb., a former governor now in his second
term in the Senate.
   ``Hal Daub had done his homework and carried the water for the
elephants for a long time. He was entitled more to the job and then
he was hit in the head with a two-by-four by the Republican
governor,'' Exon said.
   Daub challenged Karnes in a heated May primary and was favored,
but Karnes scored an upset win.
   In the one and only debate between Kerrey and Karnes, the
Republican candidate elicited boos from some in the crowd of 2,000
when he said, ``We need fewer farmers at this point in time.''
   Karnes, who has an interest in a family farm in central Nebraska
and whose commercials have portrayed him as a ``farmer senator,''
later said he misspoke.
   ``I obviously don't support that statement,'' he said.
   Karnes also encountered some difficulties when he noted that the
list of ``Hollywood-types'' supporting Kerrey include Jane Fonda,
who came under attack for her wartime visit to North Vietnam.
   Kerrey angrily denied any association with Fonda, saying her trip
during the war hurt him and his fellow soldiers. The Democrat's
staff pointed out that while Kerrey was earning the Medal of Honor,
Karnes was using college draft deferments.
   ``I have not gone through Dave Karnes' campaign list and said
`Gee, you're going to be beholden to Donald Trump because he holds a
fund-raiser for you,'' Kerrey said. ``It's just old politics and the
anger that I feel toward Jane Fonda is that I and a lot of other
Vietnam vets suffered as a result of her actions.
   ``I understand she is connected to this political action
committee, but she has made no direct contribution to me and I
wouldn't accept it.''
   Karnes says his ideals are more in tune with those of the late
Zorinsky than are Kerrey's.
   ``Ed Zorinsky was a conservative. He voted a number of times with
President Reagan. That's why he was popular. It wasn't because he
dated a movie star,'' Karnes said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
