<2ND_LINE>PM-Lawyer Jailed,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detroit Legal Chief Jailed for Refusing to Release Records</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's legal director, jailed on contempt of
court charges, says Detroit officials broke no laws in spending
$42.1 million to assist in an industrial development project.
   Wayne County Circuit Judge James Rashid this week ordered
Corporation Counsel Donald Pailen held indefinitely in the county
jail after Pailen refused to supply The Detroit News with public
records related to its 1987 purchase of 15 acres of riverfront
property for construction of a Chrysler Corp. assembly plant.
   But Mayor Coleman A. Young praised the city's top lawyer
Wednesday for defying Rashid's order and going to jail.
   ``I think he's a hero,'' Young said. ``I think he's standing up
for all of our rights. And I'm proud of him. The principle here is
how much license does the press have to destroy people's
reputations. That's why Don Pailen is in jail.''
   Other city officials had joined Pailen in arguing that the
documents should be withheld while a federal grand jury investigated
the transaction.
   ``We, of course, take the position that there is no criminal
wrongdoing associated with anything related to this deal,'' Pailen
said Tuesday after calling a WXYT-AM talk-show host collect from his
cell.
   ``In this case, the grand jury convened to look into this issue.
They should be the ones to determine the truth of the matter,'' he
said. ``This is not a situation in our view that should be dealt
with and tried on the front page of the press.''
   Detroit officials have asked the Michigan Supreme Court to stay
Rashid's order to release the documents and to stay the judge's
decision to hold Pailen in civil contempt of court. The court had
not acted on those requests by Wednesday afternoon, clerk Monica
Kohmetscher said.
   ``I make no apologies (and) no excuses'' for refusing to release
the documents, Pailen told WXYT. ``It is my principle of law, and I
think it's one the courts will ultimately have to recognize as
having validity. Until that happens, I'm content to be here.''
   Pailen is segregated from other inmates in the 1,551-bed facility
and has been conducting limited office work, officials said.
</TEXT>
