<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MarijuanaTreatment     10-27 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marijuana Treatment,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Marijuana Arrives For Glaucoma Victim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman nearly blinded by glaucoma
is happily puffing on her first shipment of government-grown
marijuana _ a drug federal officials took months to approve for her
medical use.
   ``This is going to mean I'm not going to wonder where my next
dosage of medication is going to come from,'' said Elvy Musikka at a
Wednesday press conference to announce the government's decision.
   Ms. Musikka, 44, was tried in August on charges of growing
marijuana plants in her back yard. She and her physician
successfully argued that using the drug was the only way to relieve
glaucoma's pressure on her eyes.
   After her arrest eight months ago, she applied to the Food and
Drug Administration for a federal program to receive pot legally for
medical treatments.
   Ms. Musikka, who is already blind in her right eye, said she was
slowly losing the remaining sight in her left eye waiting for her
application to be processed.
   Her first monthly supply of 300 free marijuana cigarettes arrived
at the Bascom Palmer Eye Institute in Miami on Friday, Ms. Musikka
said.
   She now carries a brown plastic container for her marijuana
cigarettes. She is said to be only the third person in the United
States given permission to smoke the drug legally for medical
reasons.
   Ms. Musikka hopes the marijuana will save the 10 percent eyesight
she has left.
   ``Ten percent is not much,'' said Ms. Musikka, who says she had
smoked marijuana for 12 years before her arrest. ``But that's a
whole lot better than none at all. When your vision is gone, it
can't be replaced.''
   She can use the marijuana anywhere tobacco smoking is permitted,
said her attorney Norman Kent.
   At the news conference, Kent lauded the FDA, the Drug Enforcement
Administration and the National Institute on Drug Abuse, each of
which had to approve Ms. Musikka's application for marijuana.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
