<2ND_LINE>PM-DC Homicides,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turf Battles by Drug Dealers Drive Homicide Rate Toward Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death of an unidentified man has pushed the
District of Columbia's 1988 homicide rate to within one of the
city's all-time total, a police spokesman said today.
   The victim found shot to death Wednesday night was the city's
286th reported homicide since Jan. 1, 1988, said police officer
Walter Ferguson. The highest homicide total, 287, was recorded in
1969. There were 227 homicides in the district last year.
   Police attributed the increase to violent turf battles by drug
dealers in the city. Authorities estimate that 60 percent of this
year's killings have been drug-related, compared to 1987 when 33
percent of the homicides involved drugs.
   It was not known if the most recent slaying was drug-related,
Ferguson said.
   ``We don't have organized crime in this city, so we have a lot of
young entrepreneurs fighting for turf,'' Police Chief Maurice T.
Turner said Wednesday during a news conference on the homicide rate.
