<1ST_LINE>u i PM-France-Pill 1stLd-Writethru a0523 10-27 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Pill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0523,0774</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Company Official Says Distribution Could Resume</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with reax from government, political
parties and anti-abortion groups. TRIMS to tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official of the French pharmaceutical company
that suspended distribution of the abortion pill RU 486 said today
the pill could become available again if public opposition to it
subsides.
   A communique issued by the company Wednesday said distribution of
the drug worldwide was stopped in response to an ``outcry of public
opinion at home and abroad.'' The story was front-page news in
French and U.S. newspapers.
   The company's decision to suspend distribution was hailed by two
anti-abortion groups in France but criticized by government.
   Michele Andre, the Cabinet minister responsible for women's
rights, told a news conference the drug company's decision was a
``disagreable blow.''
   ``I think that all of a sudden this company gave in to pressure
from a large number of people,'' she said. ``Often questions
involving morals and women bring about a backlash.''
   She indicated she would contact the Ministry of Health to see
what could be done about getting other pharmaceutical companies to
produce the drug.
   Pierre Joly, vice president of the pharmaceutical company that
makes the pill, Roussel-Uclaf, said today on French radio, ``We
could resume distribution of RU 486 if the atmosphere returns to
normal.''
   Joly denied reports the company halted distribution because it
feared a threatened boycott of its other products.
   ``A boycott could only be carried out by doctors who have to put
the interests of their patients above everything else,'' he said.
   When the French government last month authorized use of the
anti-hormone substance in registered abortion clinics, Joly said a
controversy developed.
   ``Public opinion was unleashed. We witnessed an orchestrated
campaign that grew in strength,'' he said, referring to
anti-abortion groups in the United States, France and West Germany.
   One French anti-abortion group, the Committee To Save Infants to
be Born, called for the ``destruction of all the stocks of this
chemical weapon RU486.'' Another, the National Circle of European
Women, said the decision to halt distribution was a ``great victory
for women and for families who mobilized to bring about suppression
of the drug and everyday acceptance of abortion in favor of pro-life
measures.''
   The Socialist Party and Communist parties protested the decision.
   The Socialists denounced the company's action as a ``new attack
on the freedom of women to choose a new medical method.'' The
statement said the Socialists, who lead the present French
government, were astonished at the move, announced one month after
the Ministry of Health authorized the drug.
   The Marseille daily Le Provencal said in an editorial that when
the pill was invented the World Health Organization welcomed it,
China was enthusiastic and the United States said it met all medical
specifications.
   ``It is true that the religious authorities and the right-to-life
groups were shocked by this progress,'' the paper said. ``But all
the same, are we going to be without a voice when confronted with
these fundamentalist manifestations of faith against science and
against the law?''
   The company's decision was hailed by Cardinal Albert Decourtray,
head of the French Roman Catholic conference of bishops.
   At the Ministry of Health, which authorized prescription of the
drug Sept. 23 subject to strict medical supervision, an official
said the decision ``makes one wonder about who's in charge'' at
Roussel-Uclaf.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he
regretted that the company decided to stop distribution after all
the research, medical trials and other steps necessary to get the
pill to the market.
   He said he was surprised by the reasons the company gave because
``in France, anyway, the protests were pretty weak and did not lead
to either catastrophe or strong feelings. The company acted to
preserve its image abroad.''
   The official said the government could not reverse the decision
because it was a minority shareholder in the Paris-based company.
The majority shareholder is the West German chemical group Hoechst.
   The pill, also known as Mifepristone, is an anti-hormone that
acts by blocking the action of progesterone, a hormone essential in
all phases of pregnancy. Researchers say it is highly effective in
the first seven weeks of pregnancy, particularly when used in
conjunction with a second product called Sulprotone, or
prostaglandine E.
   The new drug is not a do-it-yourself morning after pill that can
be purchased at the supermarket and taken at home.
   It must be used under medical supervision.
</TEXT>
