<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle 2ndLd-Writethru a0538 10-27 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0538,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Says Dukakis Tried to Hide Ideology</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Quayle on homeless, subbing 5 grafs for 6th graf
pvs, After the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASHEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen Dan Quayle said today that Democratic
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis has tried to keep his ideology
from the American people in a ``cynical political move.''
   Quayle, addressing a breakfast of several hundred supporters at
the Grove Park Inn resort, said the Republicans are ``the party of
the future ... we're the ones that are out there talking about
ideas.''
   Recalling Dukakis' statement at the Democratic convention that
the election is about competence rather than ideas, Quayle said, ``I
can tell you ideology is important. Ideas are important, and to
think you can fool the American people by not talking about ideology
was a cynical political move that will not work.''
   Keeping up the Republican strategy of portraying the
Massachusetts governor as a liberal who is out of step with
mainstream America, Quayle said, ``Liberalism is a philosophy of the
past. It is a philosophy that failed.''
   On another subject, Quayle said to reporters in Asheville that
homelessness in America is not due to a lack of low-income housing.
   ``I would guess that there's adequate low-income housing in the
country today but that doesn't mean that is the only answer or the
solution to the problem. That's one of them, and if we can find out
it is not adequate low-income housing we'll have to see what we can
do about it,'' Quayle said.
   ``It's a problem that we're going to have to identify. First, who
are the homeless? What are their needs? Are they on the streets
because they don't have adequate housing?''
   He added, ``I bet you will find maybe in some cases that there is
some housing. Are there some volunteer shelters that can be used?''
   Later, Quayle was heading to Charlotte, N.C. for a rally at the
University of North Carolina, and then traveling to campaign stops
in New Jersey and New York.
   A day earlier, in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., Quayle noted the recent
frequent television appearances by Dukakis and Democratic running
mate Lloyd Bentsen.
   ``Actually I think it's their swan song,'' he said, talking to
reporters as he left a fund-raising event. ``A nice way for Michael
Dukakis to say goodbye to America.
   ``I think Sen. Bentsen has a different agenda. He's been very
good at pumping himself up. He hasn't been too good at pumping up
Michael Dukakis. As a matter of fact he talks more about himself
than he does the top of the ticket. I don't blame him.''
   Quayle made the comments as a new CBS-New York Times poll showed
Bush with a 13-point lead over Dukakis. A Los Angeles Times poll
gave Bush an 11-point lead in the critical state of California.
   In Florida, Quayle also stumped in Miami's Little Havana district
on Wednesday and he was enthusiastically received at a rally of
about 400 Cuban-Americans.
   He told them that being in the Cuban community, ``I have been
able to feel the spirit of America.''
   He said he and Bush ``will invest in our people, quality
education, job opportunity, family, neighborhood and, yes, a thing
we call America. A thing we call America because this country is
still the beacon of hope for millions around the world.''
   Earlier, at Miami High School, which Quayle aide Jim Ciccone said
has a high dropout rate and a 90-percent Hispanic student body,
Quayle promised that a Bush administration would make sure anyone
who wants to has the opportunity to go to college.
   Answering a question on immigration, Quayle told the students:
``The United States of America will always have an open door policy
... We all are from somewhere.'' He told them his own ancestors were
from the Isle of Man.
   In his home state of Indiana, the state Supreme Court rejected on
Wednesday two requests to open his application to the bar.
   A Wisconsin attorney and The Indianapolis News had made separate
requests for the application under the Indiana Public Records Law.
   The application contains several questions asking whether the
applicant has been dishonest or had academic difficulties.
   Supreme Court Administrator Karl Mulvaney said the court cited a
provision allowing exemption of records ``declared confidential by
or under rules adopted by the supreme court of Indiana.''
</TEXT>
