<HEAD>Supervisor Beaten to Death at Illinois' Stateville Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Prison Hostage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOLIET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prison-supply supervisor was beaten to
death early today, apparently by a pipe-wielding inmate, prompting a
lockdown at Stateville Correctional Center, a Department of
Corrections spokesman said.
   ``The entire institution is under lockdown,'' said Nic Howell of
the agency. ``It will stay on indefitnitely ... until we get to the
bottom of this.''
   The employee was identified as Suon Treoung, 53, of Romeoville.
He was pronounced dead on arrival at Silver Cross Hospital, Howell
said.
   An inmate discovered near the prison supply store, where
Treoung's body was discovered at about 7 a.m., was taken into
custody and held in the prison's segregation unit, the spokesman
said.
   ``We did recover some physical evidence that links the inmate to
the attack,'' said Howell. ``We also recovered a piece of pipe we
believe may have been used in the attack.''
   He declined to identify the inmate suspected in the attack, but
did say the man was serving a 60-year term after his conviction for
a 1981 murder in Cook County.
   He said the investigation would be turned over to the Will County
state's attorney's office.
