<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1208EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Radar     10-27 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Radar,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Make New Offer on Radar Opposed by Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will give to its Academy of Sciences
a radar station that the United States contends is in violation of
the Antiballistic Missile Treaty, a Soviet spokesman said today.
   Gennady I. Gerasimov, the Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman, also
said the government has offered to eliminate radar at two other
sites, both of which have been challenged by the United States.
   However, Gerasimov said the moves do not constitute an admission
the radar equipment violates the 1972 Antiballistic Missile Treaty.
The pact bars the two superpowers from developing new defenses
against missiles.
   The United States has rejected anything short of dismantling the
giant radar station at Krasnoyarsk, which Gerasimov said will
instead be given to the Academy of Sciences. Washington says such
facilities must be located on the periphery of the Soviet Union, not
in the interior.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev previously offered to turn
over it over to a civilian agency. Gerasimov said it will be turned
into an international center for the study of space, as promised.
   He also said today the Kremlin was acting on U.S. complaints
about two other radar sites.
   ``We meant to use those elements for economic purposes, which is
not against the clauses of the ABM treaty,'' he said at today's
briefing for Soviet and foreign reporters.
   ``Being guided by the interests of preservation and strengthening
the ABM treaty, we are prepared to make another constructive step in
that regard; that is to eliminate the radar elements of Flat Twin
and Pawn Shop in the regions of Gomel and Moscow,'' he said.
   A U.S. State Department report in December 1987 charged the
locations of Flat Twin and Pawn Shop fall outside a permitted
deployment area or test range under the treaty. Asked later what he
meant by the offer to eliminate the radar components, Gerasimov
said, ``Eliminate them physically.''
   The spokesman repeated a call on the United States to take
similar measures with two radar sites the Soviets contend violate
the treaty, one in Greenland and one under construction in Britain.
</TEXT>
