<HEAD>Convict Men Who Hijacked Jetliner From China to Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men were convicted Thursday of
hijacking a jetliner with 118 people aboard from China to Taiwan in
May, and they were sentenced to 3{ years in prison.
   Chang Ching-kuo said he and fellow hijacker Lung Kuei-yun will
appeal their conviction to the Taiwan High Court because
``anti-communist defectors should not be guilty.''
   Chang, 27, told the court he and Lung, 26, hijacked the Boeing
737 of China's state-run Civil Aviation Administration of China on
May 12 to defect to Taiwan, stronghold of the rival Nationalist
Chinese government. He said they had not intended to harm the
passengers.
   The hijackers appeared surprised at the sentence because
prosecutors had urged leniency for the ``freedom-seekers.'' They
could have been sentenced to death.
   They used a toy gun and fake explosives to force the pilot to fly
to an air base in Taiwan shortly after the jetliner took off on a
domestic flight from Xiamen, across the Taiwan Strait, to Canton in
southern China.
   The Nationalist Chinese government granted them political asylum
and allowed the plane and its other passengers to return to China
five hours later.
