<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SculptureFall 1stLd-Writethru a0520 10-27 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sculpture Fall, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0520,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Workers Hurt By Falling Artwork</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to recast, bringing up reference to second
accident. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `Police officers ....'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fall of a 16-ton steel sculpture that pinned
two art gallery workers to the floor, crushing one man's leg, was
the second accident involving one of artist Richard Serra's massive
and sometimes controversial works.
   The accident Wednesday at the Leo Castelli Gallery in Soho
occurred as the workers were removing the piece, ``Reading Cones,''
after an exhibition. A set of heavy-duty jacks collapsed and dropped
the artwork in the first-floor gallery, said Fire Department
spokesman Efrain Parrilla.
   In the early 1970s, a worker in Minneapolis was killed when part
of a Serra sculpture collapsed.
   At the Castelli Gallery, the sculpture knocked down two of nine
cast-iron structural support columns in the five-story loft
building. The building was evacuated for the remainder of the day
while city inspectors assessed the damage.
   Police officers were able to free one of the workers, Daniel
Hafner, almost immediately. But Joseph Gallo, 30, was pinned for
three to six minutes, police said.
   Surgeons were unable to save Gallo's right leg, which was
amputated below the knee, according to a Bellevue Hospital
administrator, John Clark, who said Gallo was admitted in serious
but stable condition.
   Hafner, in his 30s, was taken to Beekman-Downtown Hospital
complaining of shoulder and leg injuries, and was treated and
released, said a hospital spokeswoman, Maureen Flatley.
   A spokeswoman for the gallery, Susan Brundage, said the sculpture
was being placed in storage following a show.
   The curved piece of steel is 3 inches thick, 14 feet high, 17
feet long and weighs 32,000 pounds, she said.
   It was one of two identical pieces by Serra at the gallery, she
said. The two combined are priced at $200,000.
   Another Serra sculpture, ``Tilted Arc,'' has been the center of
controversy at a federal building in lower Manhattan.
   Critics, including more than 1,000 government employees who
signed a petition, want it moved. They say the 12-foot-high,
112-foot-long, rusting curve of metal obstructs views, sunlight and
traffic flow.
   In the early 1970s, a worker was killed while helping install a
two-piece Serra sculpture at the Walker Art Center in Minneapolis.
One of the sculpture's steel plates fell over.
   In a subsequent lawsuit, the jury found that the fault was with
the steel fabricator, for poor technique in making the piece, and
with the rigger for failing to follow instructions.
   Serra and the art center were absolved of any blame.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
