<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NorthernIreland     10-27 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Says It Killed Post Office Manager</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Irish Republican Army today
claimed responsibility for killing a Post Office manager in a
booby-trap car bombing outside Belfast's main postal sorting center.
   The outlawed IRA, in a coded message to the media, gave no reason
for targeting Wilson Smith, 41, a postal transport manager and
father of three who police said had no connection with the security
forces.
   A bomb exploded under Smith's car in a multi-story parking garage
across the road from the sorting office moments after he drove
toward the exit Wednesday evening, police said.
   Fred Weir, spokesman for the Post Office Workers Union, said the
killing was ``an attack on the working class'' and could not be
justified. ``We serve both sides of the community,'' he said. ``We
deliver to all parts of Belfast.''
   In June 1987, another Post Office worker was killed in a similar
car bombing in the street outside the sorting office. Nathaniel
Cush, 47, had resigned weeks earlier from the Ulster Defense
Regiment, a predominantly Protestant auxiliary of the British army.
   The predominantly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to rid
Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland of British rule and unite the
province with the Catholic Republic of Ireland under socialist rule.
   A policeman, 20-year-old Hugh McCrone, was killed and his partner
seriously wounded when their car was ambushed Wednesday evening near
the village of Kinawley, 70 miles southwest of Belfast, police said.
   No one has claimed responsibility.
</TEXT>
