<1ST_LINE>u p PM-NAACP-Bush     10-27 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NAACP-Bush,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National NAACP Orders Retraction of Ohio Bush Endorsement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NAACP executive director Benjamin Hooks
today ordered the head of the Columbus chapter to retract an
endorsement of Republican presidential candidate George Bush or face
immediate suspension.
   Columbus chapter president Melanie Mitchell said in a statement
Wednesday that the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People ``does not give political endorsements ... (but) we
must offer support to those persons who hold political offices, or
are seeking such offices, whose ideals, activities, practices or
policies are in the best interest of minorities.''
   In a news release issued from NAACP headquarters in Baltimore
today, Hooks said Ms. Mitchell has been ``directed to issue a public
statement repudiating, in its entirety, this position immediately.
... Failure to do so will result in your immediate suspension.''
   She was given until the end of the day to comply.
   Ms. Mitchell was not available for comment today, but chapter
vice president Cornell McCleary said Wednesday night that the
decision to support Bush was made because the overwhelming black
allegiance to the Democratic Party has been ``totally
counterproductive.''
   Bush ``believes in affirmative action. He always has believed in
it. He has sent a signal that there is a place for blacks in the
Republican Party,'' McCleary said.
   Bush's Ohio campaign chairman Keith McNamara said today the
campaign ``is delighted to have won this endorsement. It shows what
we have been saying all along that Bush has a good track record with
blacks and that he will win a larger portion of the black vote this
fall than even President Reagan did.''
   Danette Palmore, deputy manager of Michael Dukakis' Democratic
presidential campaign in Ohio, said the NAACP's support of Bush
threatens the group's non-profit status.
   ``I think they're skating on thin ice,'' Ms. Palmore said.
   Ms. Mitchell and McCleary are registered Republicans.
</TEXT>
