<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Zambia     10-27 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zambia,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kaunda Winning 90 Percent in Zambian Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER HEARING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Partial returns showed President Kenneth
Kaunda, the only candidate for the only legal party, winning more
than 90 percent of the vote in Zambia's election, officials said
Thursday.
   They said about two-thirds of the 2.6 million registered voters
participated in Wednesday's election for president and members of
the legislature, about the same as 1983.
   Kaunda, 64, led the British colony of Northern Rhodesia to
independence as Zambia on Oct. 24, 1964, and has been president
since, winning elections every five years as the sole candidate. He
declared a one-party state in 1972.
   His United National Independent Party put up 609 candidates for
125 seats in the National Assembly, with 11 competing in one
district.
   Voters were asked to vote for or against Kaunda.
   Presidential ballots carried the symbols of an eagle and a frog.
Voters chose the eagle if they were for Kaunda, a frog if they were
against him.
   Election officials said the vote for Kaunda was running above 90
percent with one-quarter of the votes counted. Official results are
not expected until Saturday.
   Wezi Kaunda, the president's son, was elected to the National
Assembly from Malambo in Eastern province with 5,849 votes, 4,514
more than his nearest rival.
   President Kaunda has avoided the civil disorder afflicting other
African countries. He remains popular with his 7 million people
despite serious economic problems caused by mismanagement,
corruption and a slump in the world price of copper, which provides
90 percent of Zambia's foreign exchange.
   Zambia is burdened by high inflation and unemployment, increasing
urban crime and a $5 billion foreign debt that absorbs 40 percent of
hard currency earnings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881027-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthAfrica Bjt   10-27 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa, Bjt,0772</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Local Elections Leave All Sides Claiming Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All major factions, ranging
from black activists to hardline white segregationists, claimed
success Thursday after the country's largest and most divisive
municipal elections.
   President P.W. Botha's National Party, although beaten by the
far-right Conservative Party in dozens of white towns, triumphed in
several major battlegrounds and claimed that a 33 percent turnout in
contested black wards was a rebuff to activists who had urged a
boycott.
   Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu, one of the leading boycott
proponents, said the government's claims were ``quite hilarious''
and noted that only a small fraction of blacks were eligible to
vote. He and other anti-apartheid leaders urged the government to
ignore white extremists and negotiate to give blacks full voting
rights in national affairs.
   ``Manipulate statistics whichever way you like,'' said Tutu.
``The reality remains that black South Africans reject apartheid and
government attempts to give it a coat of new paint.''
   The Conservative Party, campaigning for stricter enforcement of
apartheid laws, fell short of some of its own bold predictions. It
narrowly missed taking power in Pretoria, the adminisrative capital,
where it won 19 council seats to 22 for the Nationalists, and it was
beaten back in much of the range Free State, the most rural of the
four provinces.
   But the Conservatives swept to power in farming towns and small
cities of Transvaal, the most populous province, winning at least 67
municipalities to 30 for the National Party.
   The Nationalists for the first time gained outright control in
Johannesburg, the nation's largest city, and the Conservatives won
their first seats on the council.
   Both the Conservatives and the Nationalists said the overall
results boded well for their prospects in a general election,
expected to held by early 1990.
   Andries Treurnicht, the Conservative leader, said his party now
was in a stronger position to oppose government programs aimed at
desegregating business districts and channeling more tax revenue to
black areas.
   However, Constitutional Development Minister Chris Heunis said
the results would ``give greater momentum to the process of
constitutional reform'' aimed at giving black moderates a limited
role in central government.
   The Conservatives campaigned on many national issues over which
local councils have no jurisidiciton, such as residential
segregation laws. But municipal councils do have power to evict
squatters and segregate public amenities.
   Through representation on regional councils, city councils also
can influence how much of their tax money goes to help develop
nearby black townships.
   These were the first municipal elections contested nationmwide by
the Conservative Party, which was established in 1980 by
disenchanted Nationalists who felt the government was conceding too
much to blacks.
   The elections also were the first in which South Africans of all
races voted on the same day. There were 7,229 seats at stake, most
of them in white communities. Of the 1,839 seats available on black
councils, only 905 had more than one candidate.
   The state-run South African Broadcasting Corp. estimated the
black voter turnout at about one-third of those eligible. That would
amount to more than 400,000 black votes, compared with about 283,000
in the last black local elections in 1983, when a 21 percent turnout
was recorded.
   The black turnout ranged as high as 80 percent in some small
rural towns Wednesday, but was 11.5 percent in Soweto, the largest
black community, where about 28,000 of an estimated 1 million adults
cast ballots.
   In many townships, there were no candidates. In others, there
were allegations that some blacks were coerced into voting and-or
induced by promises that were unable to be fulfilled.
   ``I see they (the government) are claiming today that hundreds of
thousands have voted and that the people elected have a solid
mandate,'' Tutu said in a statement. ``How can there be a solid
mandate when half the seats for blacks were not even contested for
the lack of interest? How does a 10 or 12 percentage poll in Soweto
constitute a solid mandate?''
   Anti-apartheid activists, including many prominent clergymen,
said voting for separate local authorities was an entrenchment of
the system of racial segregation.
   The government banned most major black anti-apartheid groups in
February and outlawed calls for a vote boycott.
   In the white elections, anti-apartheid candidates kept control of
Durban, although right-wingers opposed to intergation of beaches won
three seats. The liberal Progressive Federal Party kept control of
Cape Town, the country's legislative capital, and won 18 of the 51
wards in Johannesburg.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
