<HEAD>Authorities Arrest 13 Suspected Palestinian Terrorists</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with report that Palestinians belong
to Popular Front, BACKGROUND on possible connection to Hamadi trial,
NO PICKUP</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DUESSELDORF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have arrested 13
Palestinians suspected of preparing a terrorist attack, a prosecutor
said today.
   Jochen Ruhland, chief prosecutor in Duesseldorf, said the
Palestinians were arrested in raids throughout the country Wednesday
and today.
   Hesse state radio in Frankfurt said they were believed to belong
to the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
   Authorities previously said they were concerned about possible
terrorist attacks linked to the Frankfurt trial of confessed TWA
hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem.
   However, Ruhland told The Associated Press that no such
connection had been made.
   He said authorities still were trying to determine the precise
target of the planned terrorist strike.
   Arno Falk, spokesman for federal police headquarters in
Wiesbaden, confirmed the arrests but declined to give details.
   However, a source at the police headquarters, speaking to the AP
on the condition of anonymity, said authorities were looking for
more suspects.
   A Frankfurt judicial official, also speaking on condition of
anonymity, said authorities recently circulated warnings about plans
for an imminent strike by Palestinian terrorists in West Germany.
   Ruhland said police searched apartments and offices in West
Berlin, Hamburg, Frankfurt and Neuss, just outside Duesseldorf, and
seized explosives and detonators.
   Documents were also found, but he did not tell reporters what
they were.
   Hesse state radio said the Palestinians were seized in 16
apartments and businesses throughout West Germany.
   It said a 30-year-old man, whom it did not identify, was
suspected of being the ringleader and was also arrested.
</TEXT>
