<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HealthInsurance     10-27 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Health Insurance,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Nearly 20 Percent of U.S. Children Lack Health Insurance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 20 percent of children in the United
States have no health insurance, and youngsters in poor working
families are less likely be covered than are children of the
unemployed, a research group reported Thursday.
   The Employee Benefit Research Institute, in an analysis of data
collected by the Census Bureau, found that the higher rates of
coverage for children of the unemployed occurred because it was
easier for those families to qualify for Medicaid.
   ``Despite greater rates of employer coverage, poor children in
worker families are about 38 percent more likely than children in
poor, non-worker families to be uninsured,'' the institute said in
its report, ``Uninsured in the United States.''
   It said that among children in poor, single-parent families
headed by a full-time worker, 53.1 percent had no health insurance,
either public or private. Among poor, single-parent families headed
by an unemployed adult, 30.1 percent of children were not covered.
   Overall, the report found that 88 percent of the 37 million
Americans who were uninsured in 1986 either were workers themselves
or lived in families that included workers. Nearly 18 percent of the
civilian population under age 65 reported no health insurance from
any source.
   Deborah Chollet, the senior research associate who completed the
study, said that even among workers where family income was four
times or more of the poverty level, there were 5.2 million
individuals without health insurance.
   ``A surprising number of them have family incomes that are quite
high and that at least you would expect they would both value and
buy health insurance and they don't for some unknown reason,'' she
said.
   Ms. Chollet said some of these people may think they can't afford
health insurance but haven't thoroughly checked around for
affordable coverage. Some may be uninsurable because of certain
health problems, and others may not be educated about the need for
coverage.
   Ms. Chollet said both presidential candidates' health insurance
proposals still would leave millions of Americans uninsured, but
that Democrat Michael Dukakis' plan would cover far more than
George's Bush's.
   Dukakis' proposal to expand employer-provided health insurance
could extend coverage to 23 million uninsured individuals at a cost
of $22 billion to employers and $5 billion to workers, she said.
   Bush's proposal, still sketchy, would allow more low-income
people to ``buy in'' to the Medicaid program, but his plan to spend
$400 million in the first year and $200 million thereafter is
inadequate to bring in very many people, Ms. Chollet said.
   The institute is a non-partisan research organization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
