<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1435EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Network-Polls     10-27 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Network-Polls,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Networks Challenge Minnesota Law Restricting Exit Polling</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Long Ballot Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BAENEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Minnesota law banning exit polls, used to
project election winners, within 100 feet of a polling place
violates free speech, a lawyer for the three major television
networks argued Thursday.
   The networks are seeking a court order blocking the law through
the Nov. 8 election. U.S. District Judge David S. Doty took the
request under advisement and said he would rule before Election Day.
   Floyd Abrams, a New York attorney representing CBS, ABC and NBC,
told Doty the 1984 law would prevent family members from asking each
other how they voted if they were within the zoned area.
   ``Here is an amendment, on its face, which makes it illegal for
my daughter to ask me how I voted,'' he said.
   Peter Ackerberg, a special assistant state attorney general,
noted that the state has imposed other restrictions on activities
near the polling place, such as distributing political literature.
   ``Voters should not be required to run a gauntlet of
questioners,'' Ackerberg said. ``They should be allowed to walk away
in peace from this sanctified place.''
   He added: ``Election Day is not an event staged for the media.''
   Exit polling became controversial in 1980 when it became clear
after polls closed in the East that Ronald Reagan would defeat
President Jimmy Carter by a landslide. Many Westerners were still
voting when the networks declared Reagan the winner.
   The three major networks say this year they will project winners
of the presidential race state-by-state as polls close, but will
refrain from declaring a winner overall until after voters on the
West Coast cast their ballots.
   Abrams said the networks have successfully fought similar exit
polling restrictions in Florida, Georgia, Kentucky, Montana,
Washington and Wyoming. He said Minnesota is the last state where
such a law is being challenged.
   Abrams said the state has a legitimate interest in passing laws
to alleviate congestion around polling places. ``But this is a
blunderbuss way of dealing with that problem,'' he said.
   The intent of the law, he argued, is to prevent the networks from
conducting exit polls.
   ``What they (legislators) were after is speech they didn't like,
and that's simply off-limits to them,'' he said.
   Abrams said the law prevents anyone from approaching a voter
within 50 feet of a polling place and prevents the voter from being
asked how he or she voted within 50 feet to 100 feet of the polling
place.
   ``There's no evidence one could do exit polling that works at
that distance,'' he said.
</TEXT>
