<DOCNO> AP881027-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1438EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MedicareDoctors     10-27 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medicare Doctors,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medicare Payment Changes Need More Study Says JAMA Editorial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release 5:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Proposed changes in the way Medicare payments to
physicians are calculated should be studied carefully before they
are put into practice, say editorials in the latest Journal of the
American Medical Association.
   The recommendations, made last month, would sharply increase the
amount of money physicians are paid for office visits and reduce
fees for surgery and other procedures, such as installing pacemakers.
   The plan developed by economist William Hsiao at the Harvard
University School of Public Health needs to be reviewed by the
medical profession, Dr. James Todd wrote in an editorial appearing
in Friday's JAMA.
   ``There must be external review and validation of the study's
credibility, reliability and validity,'' Todd wrote. ``No less
important will be the consideration of whether and how this academic
research should be translated into the cold, hard realities of
Medicare policy.''
   The proposal is ``certain to stir controversy among physicians''
and should be examined further, Dr. Philip Lee, chairman of the
Physician Payment Review Commission and Paul Ginsburg, the panel's
executive director, wrote in a second editorial.
   The Washington-based organization was created by Congress in 1986
to advise it on reforms in Medicare's methods of paying physicians.
It commissioned the Harvard study.
   Todd said the American Medical Association would ``work closely
with specialty societies and state medical associations'' to
evaluate the Harvard proposal.
   The plan places a non-monetary value on tasks doctors perform.
For example, a comprehensive visit by a new patient to a general
practitioner is 248, while a well-baby visit is 64 and a triple
coronary bypass is 2,871.
   The value would be multiplied by a monetary conversion figure,
determined by Congress for Medicare, or by insurance companies, to
figure out how much doctors should be paid.
   Under current Medicare policies, physicians are paid less for
day-to-day management of their patients than they are for exotic
tests and other procedures. The new proposal would not penalize
doctors for spending time with patients.
   Todd said the values were based on averages and ``cannot
recognize differences among physicians in patient mix, quality or
practice costs.
   ``A properly working ... fee schedule will require the
flexibility that comes with physicians' ability to determine their
own charges using (the value scale) as a foundation,'' he wrote.
   Lee and Ginsburg said the proposal should not be the only
criteria in determining new fee schedules for doctors. ``Other
components should include geographic multipliers that determine how
payments would vary from one locality to another,'' they wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
