<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GMRecall     10-27 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GM Recall,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vehicles Recalled to Replace Defective Switch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. has begun recalling nearly
750,000 1984-model cars and trucks bearing Chevrolet, Pontiac and
GMC nameplates to replace a defective switch in the pollution
control system, the Environmental Protection Agency said Thursday.
   The action brings to 2.4 million the number of GM cars and trucks
from the 1982, 1983 and 1984 model years recalled to install new
thermal vacuum switches, which control emissions during warmup. A
defective switch can cause excessive emissions of carbon monoxide
and unburned gasoline.
   Models affected are the Chevrolet Impala, Caprice Classic,
Camaro, Monte Carlo and El Camino; the Pontiac Firebird, Bonneville,
Grand Prix and Parisienne and the GMC Caballero. They are equipped
with 3.8-liter (231 cubic inches) six-cylinder and 5.0-liter (305
cubic inches) and 5.7-liter (350 cubic inches) V-8 engines.
   Of the 749,802 vehicles being recalled, 53,114 were sold in
California, which has separate standards from the rest of the
country and sometimes is not affected by recalls.
   Recall letters ask owners to schedule appointments with dealers
for free replacements, EPA said.
</TEXT>
