<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSTest-Deaf     10-27 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Test-Deaf,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Ask for AIDS Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at a school for the deaf asked to
be tested for the AIDS virus after learning that a former school
worker had contracted the virus and that there may have been sexual
activity between staff and students.
   The Mississippi School for the Deaf will ask parents of students
age 12 and over if they want the state Health Department to test
their children for exposure to the virus that causes acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
   Superintendent Alma Alexander said Wednesday that she had called
a meeting of students after hearing that most had learned of a
possible problem from news reports the day before.
   ``Some of them asked if they could be tested,'' Alexander said,
``so I asked what their feeling was, if I could have a show of hands
on who would like to be tested, and almost all of them raised their
hands.''
   Dr. Ed Thompson, state epidemiologist, said the youths would be
tested ``as soon as they have the parents' permission for it.''
Results probably would come a few weeks later.
   The state had received information earlier that a former employee
had contracted the AIDS virus and that there had been sexual
activity between staff members and students.
   The first allegation was verified, Thompson said. While there was
no hard evidence of sexual misconduct, he said, there was sufficient
evidence to warrant testing.
   About half of the school's 160 students are 12 and older.
   Alexander said the former employee left the school in the summer.
She said she is confident the employee who resigned had not had
sexual relations with anyone on campus.
</TEXT>
