<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1959EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-WestGermany     10-27 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-West Germany,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Gets Assurances On Sales To Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany has promised the United States
that it will reject domestic pressures and prevent the sale of
militarily sensitive technology to the Soviet Union, U.S. officials
said Thursday.
   The assurances were made last week in Bonn in advance of this
week's trip to Moscow by Chancellor Helmut Kohl and a group of 30
businessmen who have signed deals estimated at over $1 billion, said
an official.
   The West Germans consulted with the United States about the deals
they intended to sign, ``and we could see they were being very
careful,'' said the official, who spoke on condition he not be
identified.
   At the same time, the United States has warned West Germany and
other allies in the Coordinating Committee for Multilateral Export
Controls, or COCOM, against being lulled into a false sense of
security by recent Soviet reforms, the official said. COCOM
determines which technologies members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization and Japan can sell to the Soviet bloc.
   ``We have received assurances from (West Germany) that it will
observe established COCOM procedures when it comes to carrying out
the various commercial agreements reached by German firms in
Moscow,'' said State Department spokesman Charles Redman.
   The West German assurances were given last week to Ambassador
Allan Wendt, the State Department's specialist on export controls,
who held talks in Bonn, Paris, Rome and London as part of regularly
scheduled consultations on COCOM.
   The Paris-based organization has been seeking to streamline its
complex list of banned technologies in response to the economic
liberalization of several Soviet bloc countries.
   The next full round of consultations on the changes is not
expected until next spring, when the new U.S. administration is in
place.
   ``We and our allies sometimes can and do differ on specifics or
exactly what needs to be done ... to ensure that we have strong
barriers around critical technologies,'' Redman said.
   ``As allies, we settle these differences on an ongoing basis
within COCOM,'' he added.
   But the other official said ``some people'' within COCOM have
been urging a wholesale lifting of controls on exports to the Soviet
bloc. He declined to name names but indicated that West German
officials were among those to whom he referred.
   ``There are domestic political pressures in some countries to
relax COCOM restrictions,'' this official said. ``If you are living
across the border from East Germany, for example, the temptation to
believe the Soviet threat is over is great.''
   West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher has been
advocating greater trade with Moscow as a way of stimulating the
stagnant economy and creating jobs.
   But Wendt made it clear to the allies that ``the Soviet threat
has to change before COCOM can relax its rules,'' the official said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
