<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Teen-NewTrial     10-27 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teen-New Trial,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-aged Murder Convict Wins Appeal On Confession</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court has ordered a new
trial for a girl sentenced to life at age 15 for the murder of her
grandfather, ruling that evidence should have been allowed
undermining a confession she later recanted.
   It noted, for example, that she had used drugs for 12 years.
   The 4th District Court of Appeal on Wednesday overturned the 1986
murder conviction of Cara McIntosh of Pompano Beach, now 17, who is
serving a life sentence with a mandatory minimum of 25 years.
   ``When I called her at the prison she just cried, she was so
happy,'' said her attorney, Keith Krasnove. ``She's been waiting for
so long to hear some good news, and I think she was starting to
think we'd lost.''
   Cara, her mother Paulette, and one of her mother's friends, Dean
Dameron, were convicted of murder in the death of Paulette's father,
Emmett Richardson. His body was found in a canal May 30, 1986. All
three were sentenced to life in prison.
   In a confession she later recanted, Cara told police that she was
present during the crime and had held a sock to her grandfather's
mouth while others tied and gagged him while stealing money for
drugs from his business.
   ``The jury believed the tape and didn't believe what she said on
the stand,'' said prosecuting attorney Jack Coyle.
   The appellate ruling said the trial court should have allowed
testimony about Paulette McIntosh's psychological grip over her
daughter and about Cara's drug addiction.
   Cara was introduced to marijuana at the age of 3{ by her parents,
the News and Sun-Sentinel reported Thursday.
   ``Testimony regarding (Cara's) mother's control and domination
over (Cara) was a circumstance surrounding (Cara's) confession
because her mother was being interrogated in a nearby police room
and had told (Cara) to go along with whatever she said,'' the appeal
court opinion said.
   ``During (Cara's) interrogation, the police told her that her
mother had said certain things and that if she agreed with them, she
could go home.''
   The opinion also said she was ``coming down from a high'' at the
time of the confession.
   The state has two weeks to file a motion for a rehearing, or it
could proceed with a new trial.
</TEXT>
