<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BrowniesUnite     10-27 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brownies Unite,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Color His Politics Brown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You could call Bill Biamonte a political junkie,
but don't bore him with talk about George Bush or Michael Dukakis.
He wears his loyalty on his lapel, on a brown-and-white button that
says it all:
   ``We Need Jerry Brown Back Again!''
   That is not, perhaps, the message you'd expect to hear this year,
especially not from a Long Island man who's been to California just
once in his life, and then for only a brief vacation.
   This is a man who ranks himself as the world's foremost collector
of Jerry Brown political memorabilia, who once ran for college
president on the Jerry Brown ticket, who has followed the former
California governor through the political wilderness and sees the
Promised Land ahead.
   Biamonte _ who tracks reluctant witnesses for the Nassau County
district attorney and is a local political consultant _ started an
organization earlier this year called Jerry Brown Watch and
published the first issue of what he hopes will be a regular
publication, ``The Brownie Journal.''
   The publication, reprinting newspaper articles, goes out to 180
former Brown campaign contributors whose names were on a list
Biamonte bought from the Federal Election Commission.
   ``All along, I think his strength has been that he has a very
dedicated constituency,'' Biamonte said of Brown.
   Biamonte's fascination dates to 1976, when Brown first ran for
president. His interest waned a bit in the succeeding few years, but
when he met Brown during the 1980 presidential campaign, the spark
was rekindled in a hurry.
   ``That's when I got the idea that he was the candidate for the
future,'' he said.
   Brown, the son of a former California governor, was embraced by
many as a sort of new-age Democrat _ an ex-seminarian, a student of
Zen Buddhism, companion of singer Linda Ronstadt and enthusiast of
alternative energy sources like windmills. He often was accused of
blowing with the political wind, as well _ opposing tax cuts, but
then embracing them and pushing through his own cuts.
   Brown lost a bid for U.S. Senate in 1982 and retired from
politics. Biamonte followed his subsequent international wanderings
from afar and began to establish a network of fellow Brownies who
fed each other information.
   Now Biamonte believes his patience may be paying off. Brown
recently announced his candidacy for chairmanship of the California
Democratic Party.
   What does Brown think of this unsolicited support? The former
governor, reached at his Los Angeles law office, seemed momentarily
nonplussed by the question.
   ``Um,'' he said. ``Uh, he ... he's someone who met me several
years ago and he's been an enthusiastic supporter ever since. He's
got a lot of energy and a lot of enthusiasm and he keeps a lot of
people who supported me together.''
   ``He's a completely independent operator in all this,'' Brown
added.
   Biamonte acknowledges that his is strictly a unofficial effort.
But he dreams of a more official role in some future Brown campaign.
   ``That's one of my fantasies,'' he said, ``having a really good
job working for Brown.''
   Such dedication prompts expressions of wonderment from some
former Brown supporters, such as 1980 campaign official Josiah
Beeman.
   ``The guy is just a dedicated, 100 percent Brownie,'' Beeman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881027-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 2053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContraArms     10-27 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Arms,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Documents Show FBI, Military Intelligence, Knew Of Illegal Aid To
Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men accused of violating U.S. law by illegally
aiding the Nicaraguan Contra rebels regularly briefed the FBI and
intelligence agencies about their activities, according to documents
released in a criminal case.
   The documents also show Miami police informed the FBI in
September 1984 of the existence of the Contra-supporting group
Civilian Materiel Assistance, and that drug-trafficking money was
being used to finance the Contra cause.
   The FBI in turn was sending its reports to Oliver North at the
National Security Council.
   FBI spokesman Paul Miller in Miami said Thursday he had not seen
the documents, but added: ``I doubt we will be able to comment
because it concerns a matter before the courts.''
   He did, however, say that the Miami police intelligence report
which told of drug money going to Contra supporters, and said
dynamite was shipped to them on commercial airliners, had been
investigated and found vague.
   The FBI, Miami police, National Security Council and Defense
Intelligence Agency reports were contained in a motion by defense
attorney John Mattes accusing the government of selectively
prosecuting his client, Jack Terrell.
   Terrell and six other men, including CMA founder Thomas Posey and
his Miami coordinator, Jose Coutin, were indicted in Fort Lauderdale
in June on charges of violating the U.S. Neutrality Act in 1984 and
1985. They are accused of illegally recruiting mercenaries and
shipping weapons to aid the Contras.
   ``The documents clearly show the FBI acquiesced in all this
conduct,'' Mattes said. ``They detail the exact persons, their
names, their property and even the exact air strips the Contra
supporters were working from.''
   A declassified report from military intelligence agent Franklin
Camper showed the DIA not only knew of the activities in April 1984,
but outlined for Posey and a Contra official a plan for ``deep
penetration raids into Nicaragua'' by U.S. volunteers and Nicaraguan
rebels.
   As early as January 1985 Posey and Coutin were both reporting
regularly to FBI agents in Miami, Birmingham, Ala., and other
places, advising them of their plans to aid the Contras, their
contacts in Washington and their frequent trips to Central America,
according to the documents.
   Both the FBI and the two men were aware the network might violate
U.S. neutrality laws, which bar launching military activities
against a government with which the nation is at peace.
   A Jan. 23, 1985, FBI report from Birmingham quoted Posey as
saying that on a trip to Washington he was told that the
``neutrality matter'' would be closed.
   Posey told FBI agents in Alabama he had been assured he would not
be prosecuted ``if he continued to cooperate and to provide
intelligence info re: current developments in Central America,'' the
FBI report said.
   A Jan. 8, 1985, FBI report from Miami concludes with a note that
the National Security Council had asked to be given all information
on the case.
   ``FBI headquarters is requested to disseminate above information
to Oliver North, National Security Council, White House,'' it says.
   In all, Coutin and Posey talked to FBI agents in Miami and
Birmingham at least six times in January 1985, and Posey also spoke
to agents in New Orleans.
   Coutin also talked in September 984 to a Miami police unit
investigating a bombing at a bank and mentioned his pro-Contra
activities, the Miami police report said.
   The report also said Coutin told the police that alleged cocaine
trafficker Francisco Chanes was giving money to anti-Castro and
Contra groups, and that ``the monies comes from narcotic
transactions.''
   It said a police source, Jose Sosa, claimed Chanes spent
thousands on the rebels, and that Rene Corvo _ indicted this summer
in an associated Neutrality Act case _ put dynamite in his luggage
on a commercial flight to Costa Rica for delivery to the Contras.
   Miller said a full FBI investigation cast doubt on Sosa's account.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
