<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BabySwap     10-27 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby Swap,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Both Sides Ready for Custody Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who believes a child they have
never met is their daughter are prepared to push ahead with a
courtroom custody battle if necessary, their lawyer said Thursday.
   On Wednesday, Robert Mays, a 43-year-old Sarasota roofing supply
salesman, revealed that he has told his 9-year-old daughter,
Kimberly Michelle, of the claims of Regina and Ernest Twigg of
Langhorne, Pa.
   The Twiggs say their healthy newborn was switched for a sickly
infant at Hardee Memorial Hospital in Wauchula, and then hospital
records were altered to cover up the baby-selling scheme.
   The child they took home from the hospital, Arlena, died of a
heart defect in August, after genetic testing that revealed she
could not have been their biological daughter.
   John Blakely, the couple's Florida attorney, said, ``If Kimberly
is their daughter, they do not know of any fact at this time that
would cause them not to pursue custody of their child.
   ``They are simply driven by their natural paternal and maternal
instincts to pursue and protect their own offspring.''
   The Twiggs already have asked a Sarasota court to order a genetic
blood test, a sophisticated scientific means of determining
parentage. No hearing has been set.
   Mays has vowed to fight any effort to remove the child.
   The Twiggs are disturbed that Mays told Kimberly and are unhappy
that he held a news conference and publicly revealed their
identities, Blakely said. Mays' identity had been known to
reporters, who withheld it in order to protect the girl.
   ``Mr. and Mrs. Twigg are upset that Mr. Mays talked to Kimberly
without first talking to them. At this point they believe Kimberly
is their daughter,'' their attorney said. ``If there's been no
genetic testing done ... why expose her to that news before
confirmation is obtained?''
   Mays, whose first wife, Kimberly's mother, died and who is
divorced from his second wife, said he told Kimberly about the
dispute because he was afraid she'd learn of it from a stranger.
</TEXT>
