<DOCNO> AP881027-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1611EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Czechoslovakia 2ndLd-Writethru a0541 10-27 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Czechoslovakia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0541,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Celebrate Czechoslovakia's Independence Day</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to CORRECT that official rally held today,
sted Friday, UPDATE with turnout for rally. Pickup 8th graf pvs,
``Once reviled...''
^By ALISON SMALE</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people turned out
today for the first official communist celebration of the nation's
independence in 1918.
   Hundreds of policemen cordoned off downtown Wenceslas Square,
where spectators massed behind red flags and slogans that sought to
link the pre-World War II democracy to today's communist republic.
   Also today, hundreds of people joined an American tribute to the
founder and president of pre-Communist Czechoslovakia.
   Seven prominent signatories of the Charter 77 human rights
document, including dissident playwright Vaclav Havel, Roman
Catholic activist Vaclav Benda and Petr Uhl were detained early
today, according to dissident sources. Tomas Dvorak, a prominent
peace activist, and at least five other young activists also were
detained, said the sources who demanded anonymity.
   The anniversary of independence in 1918 falls on Friday, but
officials decided to hold the rally one day early. Authorities
banned an independent rally called for Friday and warned citizens
not to attend.
   However, for the first time in four decades of rule, communist
authorities proclaimed Oct. 28 a national holiday.
   About 300 people crowded into the entranceway of the U.S. Embassy
today for an American-hosted ceremony honoring Thomas Garrigue
Masaryk, founder and president of Czechoslovakia's democracy.
   Once reviled by the communist authorities, Masaryk remains a
potent national symbol for most Czechoslovaks.
   Masaryk's granddaughter Herberta was among the crowd who sang
anthems and listened to a stirring patriotic poem before bursting
into applause and calling to the American hosts in Czech, ``Thank
you, thank you.''
   Bouquets were placed on and around a plaque showing Masaryk, his
Slovak ally Milan Rastislav Stefanik and President Woodrow Wilson,
who helped them win independence for Czechoslovakia.
   Dozens of people crowded round U.S. Ambassador Julian Niemczyk
after the 20-minute ceremony to thank him for the event, which takes
place each year.
   Elsewhere, for the first time since 1968 when the Communist-led
``Prague Spring'' reforms still held sway, officials laid three
wreaths on Masaryk's grave at Lany, 30 miles west of Prague.
   Only about 100 local villagers attended the low-key ceremony
which, unlike other official events, was little publicized in
advance.
   Masaryk is buried near his country residence of Lany with his
American-born wife Charlotte and their son Jan, a former foreign
minister who died under mysterious circumstances just after the
Communist takeover in 1948.
   With the backing of the United States, Britain and France,
Masaryk and other campaigners for Czechoslovak independence
proclaimed a democratic republic on Oct. 28, 1918.
   World War I was coming to an end, and the giant Austro-Hungarian
empire of which Slovakia and the Czech lands of Bohemia and Moravia
were part was on the verge of breaking up.
   Masaryk was four times elected president of democratic
Czechoslovakia before his death in 1937.
   In 1938, the nation he built was dismembered by the Munich Pact,
which allowed the Nazis to march into Czechoslovakia's
German-speaking territories.
   At a ceremony at Prague's Hradcany Castle, the current president,
Gustav Husak, lauded Masaryk as a figure of authority at home and
abroad in his time.
   But, according to a text of his speech from the state news agency
CTK, he made no mention of Masaryk's role as a democratic
philosopher and did not refer to the kind of government Masaryk and
his colleagues founded.
   Western diplomats invited to the ceremony had said Communist
Party leader Milos Jakes would speak. But CTK said no speech by
Jakes was expected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
