<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NAACPEndorsement     10-27 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NAACP Endorsement,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NAACP Official Retracts Bush, Metzenbaum Endorsements Under Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The local NAACP president, threatened with
suspension by her national headquarters, reluctantly retracted on
Thursday her day-old endorsement of Republican presidential nominee
George Bush and Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio.
   Benjamin Hooks, executive director of the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People, had disavowed the
endorsements by Columbus chapter president Melanie J. Mitchell and
demanded a retraction by late Thursday.
   Hooks said the NAACP is a non-partisan organization whose bylaws
forbid political endorsements.
   Ms. Mitchell said she stood by her endorsements but agreed to
Hooks' demand for a retraction to avoid jeopardizing the chapter's
tax-exempt status as a non-profit organization.
   ``I felt that a message needed to be sent to the black community
of the impending danger of supporting one political party,'' she
said in an telephone interview. ``I believe that in order for
progress to take place for blacks, they must be intricately involved
in the entire political process, which includes involvement in both
political parties.''
   Hooks said Ms. Mitchell was told in a telegram and a telephone
call Thursday ``to issue a public statement repudiating, in its
entirety, this position immediately upon receipt of this
communication.''
   ``Failure to do so will result in your immediate suspension,''
she was told.
   Ohio NAACP president James Daniels also condemned the
endorsements, made in a news release issued Wednesday under the
NAACP's letterhead.
   In that statement, Ms. Williams said the NAACP ``does not give
political endorsements ... (but) we must offer support to those
persons who hold political offices, or are seeking such offices,
whose ideals, activities, practices or policies are in the best
interest of minorities.''
   Cornell McClearly, vice president of the Columbus chapter, told
The Columbus Dispatch on Wednesday that the decision to endorse Bush
and Metzenbaum was prompted by a belief that loyalty solely to the
Democratic Party was ``totally counterproductive.''
   Before Ms. Mitchell's retraction, Keith McNamara, the Ohio
chairman of the Bush campaign, said he was ``absolutely delighted''
by the endorsement, which he said supports GOP expectations that the
vice president ``will win a larger portion of the black vote this
fall than even President Reagan did.''
</TEXT>
