<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Hostage, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0641,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Staff Members Taken Hostage At New Jersey Prison; One Later
Released</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to update with hostages freed, inmates
surrender, picking up at the 8th graf previous, beginning ``Earlier,
negotiators.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two murder convicts took a counselor and a
teacher hostage today in the library of Northern State Prison, but
released both of them unharmed and surrendered within several hours,
authorities said.
   The incident ended about 4 p.m. when the inmates released the
second hostage, Joan Mason, 51, of Newark. About 2{ hours earlier,
the two men had freed Annette Martin, 46, also of Newark.
   Capt. Robert Baker of the state Department of Corrections said
the women were uninjured and that inmates Angel Guzman, 26, and
Edward Robinson, 27, surrendered peacefully after releasing their
hostages. They had been armed with homemade, spear-like weapons.
   Martin, a teacher assistant, and Mason, a counselor, were taken
hostage shortly after 9 a.m. while they conducted a teaching session
in the library of the year-old Northern State Prison.
   James Stabile, spokesman for the corrections department, said the
two inmates' only demands were that they be transferred to a federal
prison outside New Jersey and that officials take no reprisals
because of the hostage taking.
   Stabile described the inmates' weapons as long, metal rods with
sharpened points.
   Earlier, negotiators talked through a meshed metal window to the
inmates who used Martin as a shield.
   ``The hostage was right in front of the window between the inmate
and the window with a metal rod pointed right at her head or her
neck,'' Stabile said.
   Guzman, formerly of Woodbine, N.J., was sentenced in 1982 to 17
years in prison for shooting his uncle to death over a $70 debt in
Cape May County. Robinson, formerly of Camden, N.J., was sentenced
to life in prison in 1979 for a murder in Camden County. Prison
records showed both men had records of assaulting fellow inmates.
   Mason is a vocational counselor who has worked at the prison for
about a year. Martin is a teaching assistant who started working at
the prison in March. Both women are from Newark.
   The $18 million Northern State Prison opened last year, making it
the newest prison in the state. The medium security prison houses
about 1,000 inmates at the $18 million prison in individual cells.
   After the women were taken hostage, authorities locked the other
inmates in their cells and called in the state's special operations
group, which consists of negotiators, emergency rescue crews and a
heavily-armed, black uniformed assault team.
   Warden Robert Stephens and Gary Hilton, the assistant state
commissioner for adult institutions, were leading the negotiating
team.
</TEXT>
