<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NuclearSafety 2ndLd-Writethru a0677 10-27 1010</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Safety, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0677,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Demands for Safety Overhaul at U.S. Nuclear Weapons Plants</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 6th graf pvs, bgng: `Four of,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with administration comments and CLARIFY there are 17 sites overall.
Picks up 7th graf pvs, `In other'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demands for improved safety procedures at U.S.
nuclear weapons-making plants mounted Thursday as 31 members of the
House Armed Services Committee appealed directly to President Reagan.
   ``This crisis has not arisen suddenly but over a long period, and
it stems from inadequate attention to maintenance, safety and
operating conditions,'' the lawmakers said in a companion letter to
Energy Secretary John S. Herrington.
   The letters, drafted by Rep. John Spratt, D-S.C., and signed by
committee chairman Les Aspin, D-Wis., urged Reagan to appoint
quickly the five-member Nuclear Facilities Safety Board, which
Congress ordered created this fall to oversee the troubled weapons
complex.
   The lawmakers expressed particular concern over the Savannah
River Plant at Aiken, S.C., where the Energy Department's last three
operational weapons production reactors have been shut down for
safety reasons. The first will not resume producing nuclear weapons
material until January, Energy Department officials have said.
   ``We will expect the department not to restart a reactor befor
assuring our committee that the applicable operating procedures
assure an adequate margin of safety,'' they said in the letter to
Herrington.
   National security adviser Colin Powell, answering questions
Thursday during an appearance at the National Press Club, said
resolving the problems was ``a top priority'' in the Reagan
administration. But he added that ``this is going to take more than
a few slogans. ... It's going to take a lot of money.''
   ``There are no magic-bullet solutions,'' he said. ``These
problems developed over a long period of time. We did not make the
necessary investment during the '50s and '60s to upgrade these aging
facilities.''
   Four of DOE's 17 sites have been partially or wholly shut down
this year over safety concerns, prompting hearings before House and
Senate panels. On Wednesday, a nationwide anti-nuclear group,
Physicians for Social Responsibility, said the problems ``constitute
a public health emergency,'' and urged medical studies on cancer
rates among workers and neighbors of the plants.
   In other developments, government documents obtained by The
Associated Press show that the Energy Department gave a manager of
the Savannah River Plant $59,750 in awards for excellence despite
continuing problems there.
   The manager, Robert Morgan, who retired early this year, is one
of many individuals and organizations that received cash bonuses
totaling millions of dollars despite a steady decline in safety at
Savannah River, which is a weapons production facility run by the
Energy Department for the Pentagon.
   A DOE spokesman, Will Callicott, said he was not aware of any
plans to review the system of awards.
   Morgan received the bonuses in 1981-1987 despite growing safety
problems which finally forced the department this year to shut down
the reactors at Savannah River, according to Energy Department
documents and Capitol Hill testimony. The three reactors began
operating in 1954.
   Memoranda in 1987 and 1988 document the failure of department
officials to persuade Morgan to implement safety guidelines.
   On Oct. 16, 1987, Mary L. Walker, then the assistant energy
secretary for environment, safety and health, wrote Morgan and Troy
Wade, then deputy assistant secretary, complaining they were not
heeding an order for stricter operating procedures and evaluation of
potential damage from an earthquake at Savannah River.
   ``The cited inability of SR (Savannah River) to adequately
implement its safety oversight program, including sufficient
day-to-day surveillance and deficiency follow-up, is unacceptable,''
wrote Walker, who has since left the job.
   On March 21, 1988, Morgan sent a letter to Walker's temporary
successor, Garry W. Gibbs, saying that his ``office considers that
the concerns raised are unfounded and feels that much
misunderstanding exists within the Office of Environment, Safety and
Health in the area of SR seismic design and criteria.''
   On May 20, 1988, Richard W. Starostecki, who has assumed Walker's
duties, wrote a blistering letter to Morgan's successor, Paul W.
Kaspar.
   ``It appears that the seismic upgrading that has been
accomplished (and is now under way) has been a piecemeal, largely
reactive response and that planning, control and documentation have
been seriously neglected,'' Starostecki wrote.
   ``Criteria, analytical methods and analyses appear fragmented,
incomplete and inconclusive,'' he wrote.
   Morgan was of many individuals and contractors who received cash
awards for excellence at Energy Department nuclear facilities,
despite mounting problems. Other such individuals cited in an Oct.
26, 1983, letter from Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the
House subcommittee on oversight and investigations, included:
   _Herman Roser, then assistant secretary, received $36,917 in
bonuses 1980-83, although according to Dingell he ``killed the
independent assessment program which had been severely critical of
his security program'' when he ran the department's regioffect when longer-term
loans
are agreed to. Economic forecaster Jonathan Heath said the agreement
would help Mexico out of a short-term economic trap.
   An official of the Department of Energy, Mines and State-Owned
Companies said Mexico has lost at least $2 billion in anticipated
1988 revenues because of the depressed oil market. Last year's oil
revenues totaled about $8.6 billion.
   Mexico's first-half merchandise trade surplus through June was
$2.4 billion, well below 1987's first-half surplus of $4.76 billion,
according to the Center for Private Economic Studies.
   The price of Isthmus, a major grade of light Mexican crude,
dropped from $13.77 a barrel in August to $12.80 in September for
U.S. customers; it was as high as $17.00 in December 1987. In 1985
and 1986, Isthmus went from $25 a barrel to $10.
   Pemex, the government oil monopoly, has sharply criticized the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries for overproduction and
for indulging in an undeclared price war, especially in the U.S.
market, Pemex's largest customer.
   Mexico, the world's sixth-largest oil producer, doesn't belong to
OPEC but usually follows its pricing policies. Pemex, however, said
it didn't plan to join in price cutting and would not try to produce
more to make up for lost revenue.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 30</NOTE>
