<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 2143EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Nuclear     10-27 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Nuclear,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philippines to Sue Westinghouse For Losses In Nuclear Power Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philippines will sue Westinghouse
Corp. for building a $2.3-billion nuclear power plant that never
went into operation because of alleged safety defects, a top
presidential aide said Thursday.
   Adolfo Azcuna, President Corazon Aquino's legal adviser, told
reporters the suit was likely to be filed in the United States
``within a month.''
   ``We are suing for damages and breach of contract,'' Azcuna said.
He said other parties may be sued too but he declined to identify
them.
   Construction of the plant began in the mid-1970s, with completion
delayed by scandals involving alleged kickbacks to then-President
Ferdinand Marcos and questions about its safety.
   The plant was completed nearly three years ago, but Mrs. Aquino's
government decided to junk it for reasons of safety. Officials said
the plant would have required hundreds of millions of dollars more
for safety guarantees which her financially strapped government
coult not afford.
   In addition to questions about its design, opponents of the
plant, located on Bataan province 50 miles west west of Manila, say
it sits on an earthquake fault and is near a volcano.
   After being rocked by the kickback scandal in 1978, construction
was suspended for nearly a year while the plant's design was studied
following the Three Mile Island accident. The re-evaluation ended in
design modifications that further bloated the plant's cost.
   Much of the money for the plant came from foreign loans.
   Aquino administration officials often cite the plant as an
example of the needless expenses incurred during the administration
of Marcos which burdened the Philippines with a $28 billion foreign
debt.
   Officials said that interest alone on the loans for the nuclear
power plant totalled more than $300,000 a day.
   Azcuna told reporters the government decided to sue Westinghouse
failing to reach a settlement with the Pittsburgh-based company.
   ``The legal panel is studying the alternatives of filing the case
either in the United States or in the Philippines, and the
probability is that it will be filed in the United States,'' he
said. ``We have engaged U.S. counsel to help us in doing this and
the timing would be very soon.''
   Pressed by reporters for a date, Azcuna replied, ``It was about
to be foiled last month, so I would say within a month.''
   He refused to give more details of the suit. Other sources said
the complaint won't cite any specific amount in damages and would
leave it to the U.S. courts.
   The Aquino government was under pressure two years ago to
repudiate loans to the nuclear project, but it refused to do so for
fear of possible backlash from foreign banks with which she is
renegotiating her country's outstanding debts.
   Officials who asked not to be identified said that litigation was
the safest way to deal with the problem especially because the
government has convincing evidence that the plant is unsafe and its
construction characterized by fraud.
</TEXT>
