<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HijackingPrevention     10-27 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijacking Prevention,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Pool Planned to Combat Hijacking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal to draw up an international list of
governments and experts willing to cooperate against airplane
hijackers has won overwhelming approval from an international
conference on aviation security, Britain's top aviation official
said Thursday.
   Lord Brabazon of Tara, parliamentary undersecretary of state for
aviation, said methods are being worked out by the International
Civil Aviation Organization.
   ``A hijacking is an attack on us all, an offense to us all, and a
danger to us all and we must act collectively to diminish the risk
and to lessen the consequences,'' he told the Fifth International
Civil Aviation Security Conference.
   The four-day meeting, sponsored by the Federal Aviation
Administration, ended on Thursday.
   Lord Brabazon noted the ICAO had also quickly taken up and
approved the British position that a hijacked plane should not be
refueled or allowed to take off unless that is necessary to protect
human life. The idea was endorsed by President Reagan and the
leaders of six other major non-Communist governments at their
meeting in Toronto last June.
</TEXT>
