<HEAD>Campaign Staff Bus, School Bus Collide; No Serious Injuries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus from Dan Quayle's motorcade
collided Thursday with a school van carrying five children, but
witnesses said there were no serious injuries.
   The vice presidential candidate was not aboard the campaign staff
bus when it smashed into the side of the van, said Rep. Jim Courter,
R-N.J., who was on it along with Quayle's aunt and mother and aides
to Quayle.
   ``We're fine,'' said Quayle's mother, Corinne.
   Courter said the school bus driver appeared ``very shaken up.''
Police and ambulance crews tended to the children at the scene.
   Three students _ two girls and a boy _ and a driver were taken to
nearby Morristown Memorial Hospital for treatment of bumps and
bruises and other minor injuries.
   Quayle took time to visit the students, all in their early teens,
and said afterward ``they were all in very good spirits.''
   Courter said the school bus ``pulled right out in front of us.''
The motorcade, under police escort, was driving through stop lights
and signs, he said.
   Quayle, in a limousine ahead of the bus with New Jersey Gov.
Thomas H. Kean and New Jersey GOP Senate candidate Peter Dawkins, at
first continued on, apparently unaware of the accident.
   The accident occurred at 3:30 p.m. while the Quayle motorcade was
en route from Morristown Municipal Airport to a campaign appearance.
