<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     10-27 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Teenager Killed, 20 Wounded In Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers killed a teen-ager and wounded
20 other Palestinians during street confrontations Thursday in the
occupied lands, hospital officials and Arab journalists reported.
   Officials at Shifa hospital in Gaza City said 16-year-old Zyad
Sabit was shot in the heart at the Nuseirat refugee camp.
   At least 304 Palestinians and six Israelis have died since a
rebellion against Israeli occupation began last Dec. 8 among the 1.5
million Palestinians of the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Israel
captured the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip from Egypt in
the 1967 war.
   The immediate cause of violence in Gaza was the death Wednesday
of a 3-year-old whose parents said she was suffocated by tear gas.
The army however said Narin Jihad An-Nahajha died of pneumonia.
   Dozens of young Palestinians set tires ablaze and threw stones at
Israeli soldiers in Khan Yunis, where Narin died. Troops responded
with plastic bullets, wounding three teen-agers and three women,
said officials at Nasser hospital in the city.
   Plastic bullets wounded two Palestinians during a stone-throwing
melee on Palestine Street in Gaza City, hospital officials said.
   The army confirmed three wounded in Khan Yunis and a spokesman
said he was aware ``there could be more casualties. It wasn't quiet
today in Gaza.''
   But Israel's chief of staff, Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, toured Gaza
and said ``today is a nice day, quiet.''
   ``Let's return to proportion: There are no riots in the strip, no
possibility for riots,'' Shomron said on Israel radio. ``When a
child dies in the Gaza Strip, rumors abound and heat the tempers.''
   Journalists in Nablus, largest city in the West Bank, said young
Arabs attacked soldiers with stones and bottles in a protest called
by underground Palestinian leaders of an Israeli demand that car
owners buy expensive new license plates identifying their city of
residence.
   Soldiers responded with tear gas and live ammunition, wounding
seven Palestinians aged 14 to 27, said officials at Al-Ittihad and
St. John's hospitals.
   Arab reports said hundreds of cars and trucks blocked roads in
response to loudspeaker appeals for vehicles to stop at 9 a.m. to
protest the order to purchase the new plates, which cost the
equivalent of about $250.
   Five Palestinians were reported wounded in Jenin, Tulkarem and
Idna in the West Bank.
   The army command confirmed five casualties in Nablus and said it
was checking the other reports.
</TEXT>
