<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CampaignAds     10-27 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Ads,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Dukakis Ads Target Blacks, Hispanics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' campaign said Thursday it is
doubling its budget for Hispanic ads, with most of the money
earmarked for a radio blitz in seven states with large and still
fluid Hispanic voter populations.
   The announcement from Rep. Bill Richardson, D-N.M., heading the
Democratic presidential nominee's drive for Hispanic votes, came the
same day Jesse Jackson began urging a vote for Dukakis in spots on
radio stations with black listeners.
   The Dukakis campaign is spending about $3 million _ 10 percent of
its media budget _ on black-oriented television and radio
advertising which began three weeks ago. Jackson has recorded five
radio ads.
   ``We have the power to make Mike Dukakis president. Let's use
it,'' he says in one of them. ``More people have fallen into the
deep hole of poverty because of Republican policies,'' he says in
another.
   Dukakis, who is fluent in Spanish, started running TV ads in
Spanish on two national Hispanic networks, Univision and Telemundo,
last week. One stresses education, another drugs and a third his
immigrant heritage. All three end with the tagline, ``He speaks our
language.''
   Richardson said Thursday the Hispanic ad budget will be expanded
from $500,000 to $1 million. He said three-quarters of the new money
will go for radio saturation in Texas, California, New Mexico,
Colorado, Illinois, New York and New Jersey. The three new spots
were scheduled to start Friday.
   The Dukakis campaign believes Hispanics can provide the margin of
victory Nov. 8 if they turn out in force and vote Democratic. But
Republican George Bush is counting on Cuban-American support in
Florida and is not ceding Hispanic votes elsewhere.
   The new Dukakis radio offensive does not include Florida, where
Bush holds a huge lead and Richardson said Dukakis has had trouble
making inroads with Cuban-American voters.
   And Bush was scheduled Friday to receive the endorsement of El
Informador Hispano, a Hispanic newspaper in Fort Worth. The
endorsement editorial praised Bush for being ``tough on crime and
drug dealers.'' It also says that ``like most Hispanics, he believes
abortion is wrong except in case of rape or danger to the mother's
life.''
   Bush is running a Texas TV ad featuring his Hispanic
daughter-in-law Columba, who is married to his son Jeb, and the
couple's three children. The ad, running in both English and
Spanish, concludes with the vice president saying he'll ``have a lot
of reasons to help Hispanics everywhere, because I'll not only be
answering to my grandchildren, I'll be answering to history.''
   In other media developments:
   _Four new Dukakis spots unveiled earlier this week, combining a
populist ``on your side'' pitch with the vow that ``the best America
is yet to come,'' started Thursday in spot markets across the
country.
   _The California Democratic Party said it had begun airing two ads
aimed at turning out younger voters for the Democratic ticket. The
spots in markets around the state attack the GOP record on education
and the environment.
   _Bush spokesman Mark Goodin said the campaign had temporarily
shelved a 60-second version of a 30-second ``tank'' ad mocking
Dukakis' tank ride photo opportunity as a narrator lists weapons
systems allegedly opposed by the Democrat. Goodin called the
expanded version ``devastating'' and said Bush, who holds a
double-digit lead in most polls, would not bring out the ``heavy
artillery'' unless it is needed.
</TEXT>
