<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0603,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Calls for Talks to Begin Without Preconditions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 12th `Walesa accused' with Interior
Ministry statement. PICKS up 13th pvs: `People who ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa demanded
Thursday that talks between the government and opposition begin
without preconditions and called on the authorities to clarify the
prospects for union pluralism.
   ``We demand that talks begin without preconditions and without
intervention, but we cannot open the talks at any price,'' Walesa
said at a news conference.
   Walesa met earlier with three of his most senior Solidarity
advisers, one of whom expressed doubt over the future of the talks,
which are to consider the future of the banned union and broader
issues of political and economic reform.
   ``I must say that today I am very pessimistic. I could say that
perhaps the round table is over without a start. But you know that
in all countries everything can change,'' said Andrzej
Stelmachowski, a law professor and opposition mediator.
   Government objections to two members of the Solidarity delegation
delayed the start of the talks. But Walesa said again Thursday he
would not change his team.
   Walesa on Tuesday refused a government demand he meet with
Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak to clear final obstacles to
the talks. The government said they could begin Friday if Walesa
agreed to meet Kiszczak.
   Stelmachowski said Kiszczak was asked Thursday to make a
statement declaring the government's intentions on the prospects for
pluralism and the future of Solidarity.
   ``This morning they refused to make such a declaration. The
situation is very bad,'' Stelmachowski said.
   Walesa noted a change in the authorities' attitude toward the
talks. ``I see a lack of political will to solve the problems that
divide us.'' he said.
   He agreed to take part in the talks at a meeting with Kiszczak on
Aug. 31 while strikes continued in Poland's worst labor unrest in
seven years.
   After being guaranteed the talks would include the subject of
Solidarity's future, Walesa called a halt to the strikes. He had
joined striking workers at the Gdansk shipyard during the first
strike wave in April and again in August.
   Walesa accused the authorities of bad faith by failing to
reinstate more than 100 miners fired in the Silesia region after
strikes in mid-August.
   The official news agency PAP carried an Interior Ministry
statement saying Kiszczak had urged managements to rehire dismissed
workers and asked prosecutors to drop proceedings against strike
leaders.
   It said he was ``urgently'' collecting information about
individual cases brought to his attention by the Roman Catholic
Church.
   ``This proves that no `political repressions' are being used .. .
and the appeals of Gen. Kiszczak are being gradually implemented,''
the ministry declared.
   In response to questions, Walesa said more strikes are possible
unless the workers are rehired and the promise of round-table talks
is fulfilled.
   ``People who were fighting then are ready now again,'' he said.
``I am ready to jump over the fence for the third time although we
don't want it.''
   Walesa also complained about government attempts to interfere in
the composition of Solidarity's delegation.
   The government has objected to the participation of regime
critics Adam Michnik and Jacek Kuron, whom it says do not respect
Poland's constitutional order which guarantees a ``leading role'' of
the communist party.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban on Tuesday called on the two men
to publically declare their respect for the constitutional order.
Walesa has refused to drop the two men from his team.
   Walesa met Thurdsay with historian Bronislaw Geremek and
journalist Tadeusz Mazowiecki in addition to Stelmachowski.
   The advisers say it seems the real obstacle is not the
particpants, but the authorities' lack of clarity on the future of
Solidarity.
   ``What Walesa said at the beginning means all the problems are
blocked because there is no answer to the basic question. It's not
the pretext, but the question of the lack of political will to solve
the central problem of the legalization of Solidarity,'' Geremek
said.
   Walesa and his advisers appear worried that chances for the talks
are diminishing as time elapses.
   ``We have no time and we don't want empty words ... Talks are
already late.'' Walesa said.
   A communique earlier this week said the Politburo was committed
to the talks and expressed hope that ``remaining controversies will
be quickly removed in the course of preparatory talks.''
   Urban's office did not return a phone call requesting comment on
the future of the talks.
</TEXT>
