<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 2044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PrisonHostages     10-27 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Hostages,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Civilians Held Hostage For Several Hours At N.J. Prison, Freed
Unharmed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two convicted murderers held hostage a
counselor and a teacher's aide at a state prison for several hours
Thursday in an attempt to get transferred to another prison,
authorities said.
   Both hostages were released unharmed and the inmates, armed with
sharpened metal rods, surrendered peacefully, said Capt. Robert
Baker of the state Department of Corrections.
   Annette Martin, 46, a teaching assistant, and Joan Mason, 51, a
vocational counselor, both of Newark, were taken hostage at 9:07
a.m. as they conducted a teaching demonstration in the library of
the year-old Northern State Prison.
   Mrs. Martin was released at 1:34 p.m. and Ms. Mason was taken
from the library on a stretcher at 4:06 p.m., ending nearly seven
hours as a hostage.
   Negotiators spent hours talking through a metal mesh window to
the inmates, who used the women as shields.
   ``There were repeated threats that they were prepared to do
violence to the hostages,'' said Gary Hilton, deputy corrections
commissioner. He said the women were ``emotionally battered'' but
not physically harmed.
   The only demands from inmates Angel Guzman, 26, and Edward
Robinson, 27, were that they be transferred to a federal prison
outside New Jersey and that officials take no reprisals for the
hostage taking, said Corrections spokesman James Stabile.
   ``The negotiators agreed that the grievances of the two inmates
would be reviewed,'' Hilton said. Robinson also asked to be allowed
to call his mother, a demand Hilton said would be granted.
   He said Guzman and Robinson will be transferred Thursday to
another state prison.
   Mrs. Martin's husband, Isaac, said in a telephone interview that
he learned of his wife's plight from a noon radio broadcast. ``I
just had to pray that it would come to a happy ending,'' Martin said.
   Hilton described the inmates as longtime friends who had been
imprisoned at Riverfront State Prison in Camden before being
transferred to Northern State Prison about two weeks ago.
   Guzman of Woodbine was sentenced to 17 years in prison in 1982
for murdering his uncle during an argument over $70. Robinson of
Camden was sentenced to life in prison in 1979 for shooting his
victim in the back of the head. Prison records did not give details
of the case.
   Northern State Prison is a medium security prison that holds
about 1,000 inmates in six two-story units. The $18 million complex
opened in May 1987.
   Newark Mayor Sharpe James, who went to the prison after learning
of the hostage taking, said he was unaware that the lockup housed
murderers. The state has two maximum security prisons near Rahway
and Trenton.
   Hilton said it was not unusual for murderers to be kept at a
medium security prison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
