<DOCNO> AP881027-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 2248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DeficitCommission     10-27 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deficit Commission,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Executive Says Deficit Panel Leans Toward $120 Billion
Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Strauss, co-chairman of the National
Economic Commission, has told business executives that he believes
his panel will support a $120 billion deficit reduction package
split evenly between budget cuts and increased taxes, one of the
executives said Thursday.
   John Sloan, president of the National Federation of Independent
Business, said Strauss told the business leaders at a dinner in New
York City on Wednesday that ``he thinks he has nine votes'' on the
12-member commission for a combination of $60 billion in government
spending cuts and $60 billion in tax increases to close the budget
gap.
   However, James Hildreth, a spokesman for the commission, quoted
Strauss as terming Sloan's version of the meeting ``totally
inaccurate.''
   ``All he said at the dinner was that the most support he could
hope to get for any program would probably be eight or nine votes
out of the current 12 members,'' Hildreth said. ``But he denies
saying in any way, shape or form what the final package will be.''
   The commission was created by Congress to come up with
recommendations on eliminating the federal budget deficit, which
totaled an estimated $150 billion for the fiscal year which ended
Sept. 30.
   The commission hopes to begin taking votes on different options
after the Nov. 8 election when the president-elect will name the
final two members to the panel. The panel has set a deadline of
finishing its work by Dec. 21.
   Sloan, president of an association of 500,000 small businesses,
told reporters at a briefing Thursday that Strauss had indicated he
believed the commission would approve a deficit reduction package
amounting to $120 billion split evenly between increased taxes and
budget cuts.
   Sloan said Strauss said he personally supported a vale added tax
as a way of raising revenues.
   The VAT, which has been adopted by several European countries, is
a form of sales tax. The tax is added to a product at various stages
of the production process. A 5 percent value added tax could raise
an estimated $50 billion in new revenues annually.
   Sloan said his group was adamantly opposed to a VAT, in part
because of the added paperwork burdens involved in administering
such a tax.
   However, he said he believed it would be one of the options the
commission would seriously consider because of the strong backing it
has among lobbyists for big corporations who believe such a tax
would ease the pressure on Congress to boost corporate taxes.
   But Hildreth said Strauss has not expressed any preferences for a
VAT or any other type of tax.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881027-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1827EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0674 10-27 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0674,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis: Truman a Fighter and So Am I</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB grafs 16-17 to CORRECT Bush statement on capital gains,
bgng ``Dukakis aides...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MACHESNEY PARK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis drew
inspiration from ``that feisty little guy'' Harry Truman on Thursday
and charged George Bush with trying to masquerade a tax break for
the rich as a jobs program.
   The Democratic presidential nominee invoked Truman's battling
underdog memory across the Midwest as he pressed his argument that
Bush is an elitist whose proposal to reduce the federal tax on
capital gains would benefit primarily the wealthy.
   ``He said it was a jobs program,'' Dukakis said. ``Who's he
kidding?
   ``What are they going to do with the extra money? Hire a second
butler? A lifeguard for the pool?''
   Dukakis spoke to supporters in the Chicago suburb of Evergreen
Park, Ill., and in Machesney Park outside Rockford, Ill., before
flying to Kansas City, Mo., for a live interview on the CBS Evening
News.
   The interview was part of Dukakis' effort to revive his
struggling campaign by taking advantage of opportunities to speak
directly to the voters through television. He was also taping an
interview with David Frost to appear later.
   He had a question-and-answer session with citizens in
Independence, Mo., hometown of the late former president whose
victory in the 1948 election over Republican Thomas Dewey confounded
the pollsters.
   ``We're going to Kansas City and then to Independence to draw
inspiration from that feisty little guy,'' Dukakis said.
   ``Harry Truman was a fighter and so am I and so are you,'' he
said. ``The Republicans are trying to do in this campaign exactly
what they tried to do to Harry Truman and Jack Kennedy _ distort the
record, try to put labels on people. But we're not going to let them
do it.''
   Dukakis, after several days of discouraging polls, appeared
energized by large, enthusiastic crowds and by a reunion with his
wife Kitty, who had been campaigning separately for several days.
   Bush's tax proposal has become an object of Dukakis' scorn at
every campaign stop, as he depicts it as providing a $30,000 tax
break for someone making more than $200,000 a year _ although the
benefit would depend on an individual's capital gains, such as
profits from the sale of stock or property.
   He focused on Bush's assertion a day earlier that a reduction in
the maximum rate on capital gains to 15 percent would encourage the
investment of capital and thus create jobs.
   Dukakis said the proposal was ``Halloween come early _ a treat
for the wealthiest 1 percent and a trick for the rest of us.''
   ``That's not the way we're going to create good quality jobs in
this country,'' Dukakis said.
   ``This is classic Republican trickle-down economics,'' he said.
``Give the people at the top the money and hope a few crumbs fall
off the table for the rest of us.''
   Dukakis aides distributed a statement saying Bush's claims for
the tax cut ``grow more fantastic'' and calling his assertion ``a
lie.'' Dukakis campaign spokesman Leslie Dach later said the
campaign based its statement on an Associated Press report Wednesday.
   That report erroneously quoted Bush as saying ``most capital
gains are realized by people who earn less than $50,000 a year,'' a
statement about the value of gains realized rather than the number
of people claiming such gains. In fact, Bush said ``the majority of
capital gains recipients earn less than $50,000 a year, and the cut
will create jobs.''
   In Illinois, Dukakis leveled new criticism at Bush for a
regulatory relief task force that the vice president headed and
which Dukakis said sought to roll back worker safety regulations. He
cited the death of a chemical worker after the task force ``told
OSHA to ease up on the kind of inspections being made in plants like
his.''
   ``And they talk about `a kinder, gentler nation,''' Dukakis said,
using a favorite Bush line. ``In a Dukakis-Bentsen admininstration,
we're going to put safety first and people first.''
</TEXT>
