<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-USEmbassy     10-27 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-US Embassy,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Say U.S. Charges Of Bugged Embassy Unfounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Moscow Embassy, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. decision to rebuild its embassy in Moscow
is based on unsubstantiated charges that the facility is riddled
with listening devices, the official Soviet news agency said
Thursday.
   Tass said in a dispatch from Washington that both countries will
suffer because opening new embassies in both capitals will be
delayed.
   Earlier Thursday, President Reagan said he recommended that the
new U.S. Embassy in Moscow be razed and rebuilt ``because there's no
way to rid it of the many listening devices that were built into
it.''
   ``We're going to start and have an American-built one,'' Reagan
said of the embassy.
   Tass, in the first Soviet reaction to the U.S. decision, said the
spying allegations were unproven.
   ``The Soviet side was again presented with groundless, obviously
far-fetched charges of ... U.S. state sovereignty having been
outraged,'' the news agency said.
   ``Just as in previous cases, however, the U.S. administration did
not provide any material proof to back up those claims this time as
well.''
   U.S. State Department spokesman Charles Redman repeatedly
declined to tell reporters what devices the United States discovered
in the new structure or how they were installed because ``it's never
in anyone's interest to let the other guy know what you know.''
   Tass said the American taxpayer will suffer because of the extra
cost of rebuilding the Moscow diplomatic outpost.
   Without giving figures, Redman said tearing down the existing
structure and building a new one under high security conditions will
involve ``a very elaborate and costly process.''
   U.S. inspectors first discovered eavesdropping bugs, in
structural elements built by Soviet workers and transported to the
site, in the spring of 1987. The United States and the Soviet Union
agreed in 1972 to build new, larger embassies in each other's
capital.
</TEXT>
