<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 2300EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Strike     10-27 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Strike,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Police Station and Army Base During Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BOG4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas exploded bombs and
attacked a naval base and a police station during a general strike
Thursday, but millions of workers went to their jobs.
   One man was killed when a bomb exploded in the office of a
leftist party that supported the one-day strike, said the minister
of defense, Gen. Rafael Samudio.
   Workers clung to the outside of the few packed buses that
continued to operate and clambered into government trucks and army
vehicles to get to work.
   Labor Minister Juan Martin Caicedo said an estimated 97 percent
of workers showed up for their jobs despite the strike, called by
the three largest labor unions.
   He said he was surprised by the display of ``democracy and
sensibility.''
   Guerrillas attacked the police station and naval base in the
northern town of Turbo at 2 a.m., but the assault was repulsed and
no one was injured, the Defense Ministry said. It did not say how
many guerrillas attacked.
   Rebels elsewhere blew up electric lines, railway tracks and a
bridge, Gen Samudio said.
   All of Colombia's 300,000 policemen and soldiers were ordered to
duty during the strike. Armored cars and jeeps mounted with machine
guns patrolled streets.
   Samudio said the fatal bomb exploded in the offices of the
Patriotic Union party at Apartado in the banana-growing north.
   The area has been plagued with violence. Guerrillas attacked four
towns this week and ordered townspeople to support the strike.
   Right-wing death squads have killed more than 100 peasants in the
six months in the area, where labor unions are active among
plantation workers.
   It appeared only about 10 percent of the businesses in downtown
Bogota, a city of 6 million people, were closed for the strike.
   The Caribbean resort city of Cartagena was without electricity
Thursday because guerrillas blew up an electricity tower, the
national police said.
   Guerrillas also blew up a power pylon in the northwest city of
Medellin and rail lines in Medellin and Bogota, but no one was hurt,
police said.
   The unions called the strike to demand higher wages, lower
inflation, a price freeze on basic foods and government action
against right-wing death squads.
   Colombia's minimum wage is about $90 a month and inflation has
been running at an annual rate of 22 percent this year.
   Rightist death squads have killed 800 people in last two years,
including about 180 union members.
   The three unions, whose 800,000 members are only about 10 percent
of Colombia's workers, are the Workers' Unitary Central, General
Confederation of Labor and the Colombian Confederation of Workers.
</TEXT>
