<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 2158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ControllerPay     10-27 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Controller Pay,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agency Approves 20 Percent Pay Bonus at Hard-to-Staff Airports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration received
permission Thursday to offer pay bonuses next year to air traffic
controllers and other personnel at hard-to-staff facilities in
Chicago, New York and Los Angeles.
   The Office of Personnel Management has approved what the FAA
described as a ``demonstration project'' testing whether incentives
will attract qualified employees to unattractive assignments.
   About 2,000 FAA employees in the three metropolitan areas will be
eligible to receive an additional allowance of up to 20 percent of
their basic pay under the five-year test program, Transportation
Secretary James Burnley said.
   The FAA cited bonuses as part of its plans to ease pressure on
overworked controllers at the nation's busiest airport, O'Hare
International in Chicago.
   O'Hare controllers have had 30 flight-handling errors this year
compared with 12 mistakes in all of 1987 and their previous record
of 22 in 1986.
   ``This project should make it possible for the FAA to achieve
full staffing at facilities where living costs, highly complex
operations or other factors have made them less attractive locations
for employees to move to,'' Burnley said.
   The law under which OPM approved the bonuses requires a 180-day
waiting period to give Congress time to review its decision, so the
incentives cannot begin until May, said the agency's director,
Constance Horner.
   However, Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., said he would introduce
legislation in January to waive the waiting period because more
experienced controllers are needed at O'Hare.
   More than 60 percent of the employees eligible for the bonus pay
will be controllers, the FAA said. The rest are safety inspectors
and the technicians who service and maintain air-traffic control
computers and other equipment.
   The FAA said facilities chosen for incentives include air route
traffic control centers at Chicago and New York, control towers and
terminal radar approach control centers at O'Hare and Los Angeles
International Airport, terminal radar approach centers at New York
and Santa Anna, Calif., and flight standards district offices at Los
Angeles; Farmingdale, N.Y.; Valley Stream, N.Y.; and Teterboro, N.J.
</TEXT>
