<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Whales     10-27 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Whales,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Say Cooperation With U.S. On Whales Should Extend To People</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trapped Whales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American-Soviet rescue of two whales off Alaska
was an example of superpower cooperation that should include helping
people, government spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said Thursday.
   Two Soviet icebreakers cut a channel in thick ice off northern
Alaska on Wednesday, allowing the whales to start their long journey
to their winter home off Baja California.
   Millions of Soviets learned of the success on the evening
television news program Vremya, which has covered the story for at
least a week.
   In a report sandwiched between news of sports and the weather, an
announcer said:
   ``And one more piece of news: Soviet ships, with the assistance
of American specialists and numerous volunteers, freed two gray
California whales who had been taken prisoners of ice off the shores
of Alaska.''
   Television showed the whales swimming freely, the Soviet
icebreakers and helicopters overhead.
   The announcer then said the whales had stopped moving, apparently
because slivers of ice blocked their way, and the Soviet ships would
try to clear the channel Friday.
   U.S. officials said the whales still were some distance from open
sea, in the path cleared by the icebreakers Admiral Makarov and
Vladimir Arseniev.
   At an earlier news briefing that focused on the weightier matters
of arms control and civil war in Afghanistan, Gerasimov turned
attention to the whales.
   ``The United States and us, we've saved those unfortunate
whales,'' he said. ``There's now a path broken down in the ice and
we hope that the whales will go the way they're supposed to, that is
towards the Gulf of Mexico, the coast of Mexico, although the
reports show that they now seem to be very dependent on the
foodstuffs they get there.''
   While reporters chuckled, he praised the international rescue as
an example of superpower cooperation.
   ``We've done all we could to save them, and it would be good if
the United States and the Soviet Union acted in such a concerted way
when what's involved is the saving of human life,'' Gerasimov said.
   The concern for the whales is a change of position for the Soviet
Union, which killed hundreds of the mammals in violation of
international agreements.
   In April, the Soviets followed up on informal pledges and
officially notified the United States it had stopped commerical
whaling. The International Whaling Commission, to which the Soviet
Union belongs, ordered commercial killing of whales to stop in 1986.
</TEXT>
