<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NATO 1stLd-Writethru a0666 10-27 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0666,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ministers Argue Over Nuclear Report at NATO Meeting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 12th `A summary' with more on
distribution of sumary. PICKS up 13th: The report generally...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO's defense ministers tried to
unravel a snag in talks Thursday after Belgium balked at joining a
call for modernizing short-range nuclear weapons.
   The recommendation is contained in a report prepared by
high-level defense officials from NATO nations. The study details a
continuing need for short-range nuclear arms now that the
superpowers have agreed to scrap medium-range nuclear weapons.
   In December, the United States and the Soviet Union signed the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty. That pact will eliminate
in three years all U.S. and Soviet land-based missiles with ranges
from about 300 miles to 3,400 miles.
   Officials said participants at this week's talks were trying to
gain Belgian endorsement of the classified report presented to U.S.
Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci and defense chiefs from 14 other
nations in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization. They were meeting
at a resort outside The Hague, Netherlands.
   Belgian Defense Minister Guy Coeme told a Belgian radio station
Wednesday night he intended ``to ring the alarm bell'' about the
report.
   Foreign Minister Leo Tindemans said in an interview with a
Brussels daily the report might set the stage for a final decision
to moderize short-range nuclear arms. ``I think we can wait with
that,'' he said.
   Dan Plesch, director of the British American Security Information
Council, said the report by high-level defense officials was
worrisome.
   ``Just when you thought you were safe (with the
intermediate-range treaty), along comes a lot more missiles and the
idea that you can have limited nuclear war,'' he said.
   The issue of modernizing short-range weapons is controversial in
Europe, where critics argue the weapons would likely be used on
their soil because of their range under 300 miles.
   However, several ministers at the talks said Thursday that
Belgium's objections were minor and that it would eventually approve
the report.
   British Defense Minister George Younger said the Belgian position
was ``extraordinarily close to the other positions.''
   A summary of the report, made available by the Security
Information Council, said it outlined several options for
restructuring NATO's nuclear forces.
   Copies of the summary also were released by the Campaign fpr
Nuclear Disarmament, based in London, which opposes nuclear weapons
and led the fight against deploying medium-range missiles in Britain.
   Efforts to reach Belgian officials for comment were not
successful.
   The report generally recommends a continued role in NATO strategy
of short-range nuclear forces.
   It calls for continuing support for U.S. and British efforts to
develop a new, longer range tactical air-to-surface missile that
could be fired at Soviet air defenses from fighter planes.
   The report also backs U.S. efforts to develop a replacement for
the Lance surface-to-surface nuclear missile, which military
analysts say will be obsolete by 1995.
   The defense ministers gather twice a year to discuss nuclear
strategy. Fourteen of NATO's 16 members take part, with Iceland
attending as an observer. France operates outside NATO's military
structure.
   No final decision on modernization of the weapons was expected
until next year at the earliest, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881027-0183 </DOCNO>
