<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LawnDart     10-27 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lawn Dart,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Child Injured by Lawn Dart Kept in Coma; Congress Voted to Ban Game
Last Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old girl accidentally stabbed
in the forehead by a lawn dart was kept comatose Thursday as her
doctors waited for swelling in her brain to subside.
   Amy Herrin of McMinnville was in critical condition in the
pediatric intensive care unit of Vanderbilt University Medical
Center after eight hours of surgery to remove and repair damage
caused by the 1-pound steel and plastic dart.
   ``They've been keeping her asleep,'' Amy's mother, Sue Tucker,
said Thursday. ``They didn't want the brain to do any functioning on
its own till they found out whether or not the brain was going to
swell. It's just wait and see how things are and do a lot of
praying.''
   The girl was injured Tuesday evening as she played the
horseshoe-like game with a cousin outside a neighbor's house. The
object of the game is to toss the darts, which have 4-inch-long
metal points, into a ring placed on the ground.
   The accident came after Congress passed legislation last week
ordering the government to ban the sale of lawn darts, a game that
is blamed for the deaths of three children and injuries to thousands
of others.
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission was ordered to prohibit
sale of the darts within 60 days unless it determines that the game
cannot cause puncture wounds. It was to consider the matter at a
meeting Friday.
   Mrs. Tucker said the cousin raced into her kitchen at about 5:30
p.m., followed by Amy, with the dart still protruding from her head.
   ``She just said, `Momma, it's in my head.' All else I remember is
me screaming,'' Mrs. Tucker said.
   The girl has suffered some brain damage but doctors don't know
how much, said Amy's stepfather, Lamar Tucker. He said she faces
more surgery.
   Surgeons had to cut into her skull to get the dart out, Tucker
said, ``and they're going to have to go back in and put in a plate
in her forehead.''
   The cousin who threw the dart ``was real tore up,'' Mrs. Tucker
said. ``He came down (to the hospital) with his mother and dad. He's
only 11 years old. He brought (Amy) ... flowers and a big balloon.''
   Federal law currently requires that the darts carry warning
labels stating the game is not for children and can cause serious
injury or death. They are not to be sold in toy stores or in toy
departments.
   ``No toy could do the damage that's been done to my baby,'' Mrs.
Tucker said.
</TEXT>
