<DOCNO> AP881027-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 2123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-USReport     10-27 0780</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-US Report,0805</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Citizens Group Says U.S.-U.N. Relations in Disarray</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leading U.S. citizens group on the
United Nations said Thursday that the world body is in need of major
changes and that the next administration in Washington should make
U.N. reform a top priority.
   The report released by the United Nations Association of the
United States and its chairman, Elliot L. Richardson, lamented that
U.S.-U.N. relations are in disarray and urged the next
administration to pay U.S. arrears of more than $400 million.
   ``With the U.N. enjoying renewed credibility as it brings some of
the world's most bitter conflicts to an end ... the prospects for
U.N. purposeful global action ... are brighter than at any time in
recent history,'' it said. ``A new realism in both the Third World
and the Soviet Union has created new opportunities for international
cooperation in the U.N. _ but also America's own relations with the
U.N. are in disarray,'' Richardson, a former U.S. attorney general
and defense secretary, noted in the report.
   The disarray results from U.S. nonpayment and withholding of its
budget dues, which the United States is legally obliged to pay.
   In addition, the Reagan administration has been estranged from
the organization for nearly eight years, accusing it of anti-Western
bias, a bloated bureaucracy and wasteful spending. Reagan has balked
at giving up any U.S. prerogatives to act for itself in favor of
multilateral solutions.
   The administration acknowledged, however, that the 159-member
world body has instituted major reforms and made dramatic
contributions to conflict resolution, from Afghanistan to the
Iran-Iraq war.
   The United Nations Association of the United States is a
nonpartisan, nationwide organization with more than 20,000 members.
Its recommendations are based on public meetings in about 100
communities.
   Its report made about 85 specific recommendations, including
changing the General Assembly voting system and enlarging Security
Council membership.
   It said the next U.S. administration should increase U.S.
participation in the United Nations and should not try to reduce its
25 percent share of the budget. It should instead use its financial
leverage to make the United Nations more effective in promoting both
U.S. interests and world peace.
   The report found many U.N. decision-making bodies too unwieldy to
be effective forums for negotiations. It said Washington should
insist on reforms that would enhance the U.N. system as the center
for resolving global problems.
   The study said the United States should make sure that U.N.
budgetary reforms adopted in 1986 are implemented and result in
greater efficiency in use of U.N. resources.
   It said the United States should renew its campaign for
``weighted'' voting on budgetary issues in the General Assembly,
effectively giving the United States and major donors a greater say
in how their funds are spent. But it said ``weight'' also should
consider a nation's population.
   The report said the 15-member Security Council should be
restructured to include a category of semi-permanent members,
representing major powers in each region. This might warrant an
increase of up to four members in council size.
   The council also should meet at least once a year at foreign
minister level and defense ministers also should meet periodically,
it said.
   The council's Military Staff Committee should be revitalized and
oversee limited joint military exercises among the five permament
members _ a sign of their willingness to collaborate in guaranteeing
international peace and security. The five are the United States,
the Soviet Union, China, Britain and France. They traditionally play
no part in peacekeeping operations.
   The study proposed that the council look into establishment of a
training program for countries that contribute troops to U.N.
peacekeeping forces. It said U.N. members should establish a reserve
fund under the Security Council to cover initial outlays of new
peacekeeping missions.
   Among other recommendations:
   _Creation of a multilateral drug enforcement assistance unit
within the United Nations.
   _Establishment of a U.N. elections commission to monitor and
conduct free elections at the request of individual nations.
   _An international ban on chemical weapons, with the United States
and Soviet Union assuming the bulk of verification.
   _An international convention on environment and development.
   _An international tribunal to rule on disputed drug trafficking
cases.
   _A ministerial board at the helm of the Economic and Social
Council to oversee U.N. responses to emerging economic,
environmental and social problems.
   And it said the U.N. secretary-general should guard against
demands by member states for political appointments.
   The report is entitled ``Pulling Together: A Program for America
in the United Nations.'' Eleanor Roosevelt founded the New
York-based association 24 years ago to foster better understanding
of the United Nations and the U.S. role in it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
