<HEAD>Dukakis Had $20 Million Left for 11th-Hour Push</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Bush report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, underdog in his
battle with Republican George Bush for the presidency, had nearly
$20 million as of last week to mount his final push to Election Day,
while Bush had $14.3 million, according to docuents filed Thursday
with the Federal Election Commission.
   The reports of campaign spending and receipts were the
candidates' last mandatory filing before Nov. 8.
   The Dukakis-Bentsen Committee reported that it had spent $26.7
million through Oct. 19, the end of the reporting period, and had
$19.9 million cash remaining. More than a third _ $10.4 million _ of
the campaign's general election expenditures were made during the
19-day period in October.
   Bush, who leads Dukakis in the polls, spent $31.8 million through
Oct. 19, $13.5 million of that during the 19-day period. The
campaign ended the reporting period with $14.3 million cash on hand.
   Both presidential nominees received $46.1 million for the general
election from a federal Treasury fund supported by the voluntary $1
checkoff on individual income tax returns.
