<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TeaParty 1stLd-Writethru a0710 10-27 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tea Party, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0710,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Explorer Seeks State Permission to Bring Back Tea Party Chests</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS date of Boston Tea Party to Dec. 16, sted Dec. 13,
in
14th graf, `The Boston ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When colonial patriots tossed 342 chests of tea
into Boston Harbor, they thought they had rid the city of the
symbols of tyranny. But now, an explorer says he has located the
dump site and wants to salvage the chests.
   Barry Clifford, who located the first pirate ship found in the
New World four years ago, appeared Thursday before the state Board
of Underwater Archaeological Resources for permission to survey the
Tea Party site.
   ``Boston Harbor is an archaeological site,'' Clifford said in his
presentation to the board. ``In this day and age, when we have
knowledge of what's at the bottom of the harbor, it's too bad not to
plan so we don't put a tunnel through a 17th century shipwreck.''
   The board, however, tabled his bid for a reconnaissance permit,
which would have awarded Clifford and his team exclusive rights to
survey a nautical square mile in Boston Harbor. Officials asked
Clifford to return for the board's next session Dec. 1 with more
details about the site.
   Acting board director Jim Bradley said the explorer must provide
more specific proof that he has found the location of the Tea Party
chests before the board awards him exclusive rights. Until then,
Bradley said, Clifford and his team are free to electronically scan
the harbor but will not be given an exclusive right to the area.
   Clifford said at the meeting that he did not include specific
data about the site in his permit application because of a security
risk in publicizing the area.
   Clifford, president of Maritime Explorations Inc. in Chatham,
surprised skeptics when he found the treasure-laden Whydah off the
coast of Cape Cod in 1984 and brought up the ship's bell.
   Still, experts have doubts about Clifford's latest venture.
   Paul Johnston, curator of marine history at the Peabody Museum in
Salem and a maritime archaeologist, is dubious about Clifford's
claim that the tea crates were elaborate Chinese chests. Johnston
said the museum has similar ornate Chinese boxes but said that they
were gift boxes. He said he doubts that the British would have
exported tea in fancy containers.
   ``They were probably standard wooden crates,'' said Johnston.
   Johnston also said that he recently learned the site of the tea
dumping was at Griffin's Wharf, which lies considerably inland from
today's Boston Harbor. The wharf is now located beneath a concrete
pad under a Boston Edison substation, he said.
   ``It seems unrealistic to think he could find the tea chests
now,'' said Johnston. ``The whole landscape of the harbor has
changed since then.''
   Clifford and his team have been researching the harbor for 18
months and hope to look for shipwrecks as well as the Tea Party
chests. He wants to examine what he believes is the Tea Party site
with the Maritime Explorer, his 166-foot excavation ship.
   The Boston Tea Party commenced just after dusk on Dec. 16, 1773,
when 30 patriots, angered over King George III's three-penny tax on
a pound of tea, raided three ships, the Eleanor, the Dartmouth and
the Beaver.
   Disguised as Indians, the patriots located the crates in the
ship's hold, brought them on deck, opened them and pitched them
overboard.
</TEXT>
