<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia     10-27 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prestrike Violence Kills 64; President Alerts Military</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from leftist guerrillas
this week rose to 64 and Colombians prepared on Wednesday for more
violence during an impending general strike supported by the rebels.
   Many drivers in Bogota tied small tree branches to their front
bumpers, hoping they would sweep away nails and tacks being spread
in the streets by strike sympathizers.
   Most businesses and all schools routinely close during general
strikes.
   The three largest labor unions called the one-day strike for
Thursday, demanding an increased minimum wage, lower inflation, a
price freeze on basic foods and action against right-wing death
squads.
   President Virgilio Barco ordered Colombia's 300,000 police
officers and soldiers to be on duty Thursday.
   A guerrilla ambush of a civilian bus carrying policemen killed 20
people, Gov. Antonio Roldan Betancur of Antioquia state told a news
conference Wednesday in the state capital Medellin.
   He said rebels knocked the bus off the road with a dynamite
charge Tuesday morning in a remote part of the Andes in northern
Colombia, then it with automatic weapons fire.
   Ten policemen and 10 civilians, including a pregnant woman and a
1-year-old boy, were killed in the ambush and 12 people were
wounded, the governor said. the ambush occurred near Peque village,
200 miles northwest of Bogota.
   On Tuesday and Wednesday, 10 buses were set afire in Medellin,
Tunja, Bucaramanga, Valledupar and Popayan, national police said in
a statement.
   A bomb exploded Wednesday in a Medellin, shopping center but no
one was hurt, police reported.
   Soldiers and police set up checkpoints in major cities, searching
cars for guns and explosives. Army squads with assault rifles and
jeeps mounted with .30 caliber machine guns patrolled streets
Wednesday.
   Two people were found trying to plant a bomb Tuesday in Bogota's
convention center where the minister of mines and energy, Oscar
Mejia Vallejo, was speaking to an oil industry convention, police
said.
   In the northern, banana-growing region of Uraba, guerrillas
raided three plantations, burned eight vehicles and destroyed an
airport and banana processing equipment, national police said in
Antioquia state.
   Guerrillas raided two villages in eastern Colombia on Tuesday and
harangued residents to back the strike, said the army's 5th Brigade
in Bucaramanga.
   Unions organizing the strike want the minimum wage raised from
the current equivalent of about $90 a month for a six-day work week
and the inflation ratelowered from 22 percent. Death squads are
accused of killing about 800 people in the past two years, including
180 union members.
</TEXT>
