<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen: Allies Should Pay More in Own Defense</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS five grafs on Chico appearance.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen said Thursday he wanted U.S.
allies in Europe and Japan to pick up a bigger share of the free
world's defense costs within the next four years.
   Bentsen, speaking before the World Affairs Council, said that the
United States spends 6.5 percent of its output on the military, that
it can no longer afford to carry the burden for other nations and
that allies strapped after World War II can now afford to do more.
   Afterward, at a news conference, Bentsen said it cost $3.5
billion to protect Japan. ``They could pick up that tab,'' he said,
though he does not support re-arming Japan.
   European allies should also spend more to equalize the burden, he
said, although he added that they were now doing more with their own
troops.
   In his speech, Bentsen said he and Democratic presidential
nominee Michael Dukakis were firmly committed to U.S. defense
strength but the Republicans had ``twisted the truth to imply that
Governor Dukakis is an apostle of military weakness.''
   ``That's just not so,'' he said. Both parties plan to spend the
same amount of money on defense, but the Democrats recognize that
there are other threats to national security, he said.
   ``I would suggest that it will profit America little to gain the
whole world of military superiority if we lose the soul of our
economic capacity,'' he said. ``It will profit us little to be
military hawks if the competition is between economic eagles and we
are sitting ducks.''
   Republican policies have turned the United States into an
international debtor, dependent on foreign investors to sustain an
economy saddled with huge trade and budget deficits, he said.
   ``The United States must be able to compete not only militarily
but economically'' if it intends to maintain leadership in the free
world and set an example for developing nations, he told the
council, a private group of business and academic people.
   Taking questions from the group afterward, Bentsen said he
supported some forgiveness of the international debt owed to U.S.
banks by Mexico on a ``case by case basis'' but not as a nation as a
whole. Mexico needs to be treated ``like a company that went
bankrupt'' that pays part but not all on its obligations, he said.
   The council, a Los Angeles based group is scheduled to hear
President Reagan on Friday. Bentsen joked that he was warming them
up for the president.
   But he complained the Republicans ``have found it useful to shape
the discussion as if military strength were the sole touchstone of
national strength. They have twisted the truth to imply that
Governor Dukakis is an apostle of military weakness.''
   ``The American people need to understand that Michael Dukakis and
Lloyd Bentsen are firmly committed to U.S. military strength,'' he
said. ``Any implication to the contrary is not just negative
campaigning, it is a misrepresentation of fact.''
   Bentsen called for tough enforcement of the new trade bill which
he helped push through the Senate, to open up new markets for U.S.
goods.
   In addition, he said investment in non-military research and
development needed to increase, after being cut 23 percent during
the Reagan years.
   ``While following a passive policy on trade, our government
unfortunately has countenanced retreats on other fronts as well,''
he said. ``Our industrial and academic research base, once the
world's foremost, is losing ground,'' he said.
   In Chico, with a little help from actor Rob Lowe, Bentsen drew
the biggest crowd of his campaign so far at a rally at California
State University.
   A crowd police estimated at 7,000 students and local citizens
heard Bentsen continue his attacks against Republican ``negative
campaigning'' and call for the election to be a ``national referendm
against mudslinging.''
   ``We're going to turn this election around,'' he said, saying the
Democrats were coming back in the polls.
   Lowe told the crowd, including young women who were
enthusiastically screaming at the sight of the celebrity, that the
67-year-old Bentsen was ``a man for the young people.'' The two were
mobbed as they left the outdoor stage, and the Texas senator shook
hands, gave ``high-fives'' and even kissed one woman student as he
worked his way through the crowd.
   Local people said it was the first appearance there by a national
candidate since John Kennedy in 1960.
</TEXT>
