<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0711 10-27 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0711,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Has No Details On College Opportunity Program</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS 15th graf, But some..., to show how Quayle handled
hecklers, and ADDS one graf on Syracuse appearance.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASHEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle is promising the chance
for a college education to anyone who wants it under a George Bush
administration, but admitted Thursday he did not know how the
Republican presidential contender plans to make it happen.
   ``I haven't sat down and talked with George Bush on this,'' he
told local reporters in Asheville. ``So I can't go in and tell you
anything.''
   Later Thursday, Quayle campaigned in a high-technology part of
New Jersey, visiting an AT&T long distance headquarters in
Bedminster.
   There he spoke by satellite hookup to employees at 29 AT&T
facilities in the state.
   On the way to the appearance, a campaign staff bus collided with
a school van, and a number of children were taken to a local
hospital for observation. Quayle arranged to visit the children.
   He said the company represents the technological changes of the
future, adding, ``Anyone prepared to lead us into the 1990s and then
into the 21st century must be prepared to harness this change _ to
capture its spirit, its momentum and its excitement so that we turn
challenge into achievement.
   Quayle also told reporters asking him about homelessness he
thinks there is enough low-income housing in the country and the
number of low-income housing units has increased under Reagan. ``But
that doesn't mean that is the only answer or solution,'' Quayle said.
   He said he government should identify other factors contributing
to homelessness, and then work with state and local governments and
the private sector on solutions.
   On the question of higher education, Quayle repeated a comment
that he made a day earlier in Miami: ``We're going to make sure that
a student that wants to go on to higher education will have that
opportunity.''
   But he could give no specifics when reporters asked him what he
dould do toward that goal.
   He said he has spoken to Bush ``about education issues in
general'' but they ``haven't sat down and discussed detailed
proposals.''
   The remarks came on a campaign day in which he kept the
rhetorical heat on Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis,
joked to a Charlotte, N.C., audience that Dukakis was like the
California whales that got trapped beneath an Alaskan ice floe.
   He said one eskimo told another the whales were named Dukakis.
   ```Know what Dukakis means?' the eskimo said. `Hopelessly stuck
in the ice.'''
   Although Quayle generally dealt skillfully with hecklers
throughout the day, some supporters seemed to think he was going a
bit too far in putting down a group of them by referring to the
severely polluted Boston harbor in Dukakis' home state of
Massachusetts. The harbor is a centerpiece of Bush's attack campaign
against Dukakis.
   ``Ever hear of Boston Harbor,'' Quayle asked the campus rally.
   ``Matter of fact, I think Boston Harbor is right over here,'' he
said pointing to the pro-Dukakis signs.
   ``Ouch,'' said one Quayle supporter, as a couple nearby groaned.
   He dealt with a more boisterous crowd in Syracuse, N.Y., where
hecklers forced him to interrupt his speech. The noise level rose
when Quayle supporters in the Civic Center tried to shout down the
pro-Dukakis hecklers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
