<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Reagan 2ndLd-Writethru a0634 10-27 0852</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0634,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Bush Will Win Fair and Square</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Shows speech delivered; INSERTS graf after 4th pvs, ``They
didn't..., to give crowd color.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan returned to his home
state on Thursday and predicted that Vice President George Bush will
``win fair and square'' in the Nov. 8 election.
   ``Now that the game seems to have turned against them, the
liberals have started squealing that he's running a negative
campaign,'' Reagan told a Republican rally at the San Diego Sports
Arena.
   ``Well, I hope the people of Oakland will forgive me, but that
would be a little like the A's complaining that the Dodgers ran a
negative World Series,'' the president said.
   ``They didn't,'' he told his Southern California audience. ``The
Dodgers won fair and square, and come Nov. 8, the Republicans are
going to win fair and square too because they know we stand for the
future and they know the opposition is liberal, liberal, liberal.''
   The crowd, which assistant White House press secretary Ben
Jarratt said was estimated at 11,000, interrupted with frequent
cheers and applause and waved small American flags as the president
spoke. A large banner reading ``We love Nancy'' hung prominently in
the center of the arena although Mrs. Reagan traveled separately to
California and missed the rally.
   The San Diego stop was the president's first in California during
a week-long campaign swing. He and First Lady Nancy reagan will take
a weekend break at their ranch near Santa Barbara before he resumes
campaigning. The White House said Reagan would vote by absentee
ballot during the trip.
   Republicans count on the Californian in the White House as a
major factor in their hopes of garnering the state's 47 electoral
votes.
   Earlier, at Little Rock, Ark., Reagan said Americans should vote
for the GOP ticket ``as an act of self-defense'' because Democratic
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis favors gun controls.
   At Springfield, the president who once was a Democrat courted
votes for Sen. John Danforth and other GOP candidates in President
Truman's home state.
   ``Today, Harry Truman's party is the Republican Party, and it's
time to give that party a bigger stick in the Congress and cut the
liberals down to size,'' Reagan said.
   ``We don't want a president who would raise taxes; why elect a
Congress that would?'' he asked. ``We don't want a big-spending
president, why should we want a big-spending Congress? We don't want
a president who would cut our defenses; why vote for a Congress that
wants to do that?''
   The San Diego speech marked the president's second visit to his
home state since the GOP National Convention in New Orleans in
mid-August. During his previous visit in August, Reagan campaigned
in Orange County, a center of GOP conservatism south of Los Angeles.
   ``Nothing is more important in the California race than the
turnout in Orange County and Northern San Diego County and the
Inland Empire,'' said Alan Heslop, a specialist in California voting
patterns.
   ``Those are the great vote-rich areas for Republican candidates
in this state and to wheel Reagan through the Southland is to give
encouragement to the party workers. It is to gear up the turnout and
the get-out-the vote drive,'' he said.
   It is also to raise money.
   Before his current swing, Reagan's 21 political appearances in 13
states since Labor Day had raised an estimated $8.8 million for
national and state GOP campaign treasuries.
   Before he returns to Washington next Wednesday, he will rest at
his Santa Barbara area ranch over the weekend and then speak in
Reno, Nev.; Milwaukee and in another state the White House has not
identified.
   In Arkansas, with its six electoral votes, Reagan told his
airport audience that ``America needs the strength, the vision, and
the true grit of George Bush and Dan Quayle.''
   Reagan, a former movie actor, had previously evoked the memory of
the John Wayne film classic, ``True Grit,'' in extolling his vice
president, but in Little Rock he extended the remark to include the
youthful Indiana senator who is Bush's vice presidential running
mate.
   It was the only reference to Quayle in the speech, which was
devoted largely to praising Bush's record as vice president.
   ``I have come to know George Bush very well,'' Reagan said. ``And
I also know what is required to be president of the United States; I
know who should be the man at the desk, and ladies and gentlemen,
George Bush is the man.''
   ``You and I and George Bush worked much too hard to cut your
taxes to let our opponents come into office and raise them all over
again,'' he said. ``So on Nov. 8, go into that polling booth and do
some negative campaigning of your own, the right kind of negative
campaigning: Say `no' to new taxes and say `yes' to the Republican
ticket.''
   Bush, like Reagan, has vowed to oppose tax increases. Dukakis,
who has not said he will raise taxes, has accused the Bush campaign
of negative campaigning that distorts his record.
</TEXT>
