<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PrisonSlaying     10-27 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Slaying,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supervisor Beaten To Death at Illinois Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOLIET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prison supply supervisor who fled war-torn
Cambodia for a new life was bludgeoned to death Thursday at the
maximum-security institution.
   Stateville Correctional Center ``is under lockdown. It will stay
on indefinitely ... until we get to the bottom of this,'' said
Corrections Department spokesman Nic Howell.
   He said one prisoner was caught near the scene of the killing,
and was being held in separate custody. No charges were filed
immediately.
   The victim, Suon Troeung, 53, of Romeoville was struck on the
head and was dead on arrival at Silver Cross Hospital, Howell said,
adding he did not know how many times Troeung was struck.
   Will County State's Attorney Edward Masters, whose office will
handle the case, said prosecutors were awaiting a report from prison
officials before deciding whether to file charges against the
suspect.
   ``We did recover some physical evidence that links the inmate to
the attack,'' said Howell. ``We also recovered a piece of pipe we
believe may have been used in the attack.''
   The suspect was serving a 60-year term for the murder of an
off-duty police officer, Howell said.
   Troeung's body was found early in the day at the prison store he
operated where inmates buy cigarettes, shampoo and other items,
Howell said in a telephone interview from Springfield.
   Troeung, called ``Sonny'' by co-workers, left Southeast Asia in
1975. He had been a captain in the Cambodian army, where he served
as a supply officer.
   Troeung began working at Stateville as a correctional officer in
1978 and was promoted to supply supervisor a year later. He was put
in charge of the prison commissary in 1985, Howell said.
</TEXT>
