<DOCNO> AP881027-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 2337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Hostages     10-27 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Hostages,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Steen Letter Appears Fake</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A letter found in a Lebanese woman's luggage
and bearing the name of U.S. hostage Alann Steen appears to be a
fake, police said Thursday.
   The letter and photographs of two U.S. hostages _ Steen and Terry
Anderson _were found Oct. 20 in a false bottom of luggage belonging
to the woman after she arrived at Milan's Linate airport from
Beirut. She was identified as Aline Ibrahim Rizkallah, 36.
   ``We have examined the document (Steen's letter), and for the
moment we can only say that it appears evidently false,'' said
Achille Serra, head of the police anti-terrorism unit in Milan.
   He said U.S. and Italian experts compared the signature to
samples of Steen's handwriting. ``If you just take a look, you see
that this one is fake,'' he said.
   Police said earlier the photographs were reproductions of ones
issued by kidnapers months ago. A third photograph has not yet been
identified.
   Police said the woman was to deliver the letter, photographs and
other documents to Aldo Anghessa, an Italian arms trader with links
to the Italian and Swiss secret services, and he was supposed to
give the pictures and letter to a third party.
   Prosecutor Ferdinando Pomarici, the investigation chief, said
Thursday that Anghessa ``said he was working to free the hostages,''
but Pomarici expressed doubts Anghessa had been truthful. He would
not elaborate.
   The U.S. government has denied any involvement in the case.
   The Lebanese woman was arrested after she was found to be
carrying $1,000 in counterfeit U.S. bills and 50 grams (1.7 ounces)
of heroin.
   She said she received the pictures, documents and drugs in
Lebanon from a man called ``Shant'' who was in contact with
Hezbollah, the organization linked to pro-Iranian extremist groups
holding the hostages, Pomarici said.
   One faction with ties to Hezbollah, Islamic Jihad, reiterated
Thursday it was not connected with the woman and did not provide
Anderson's photo.
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, was seized on March 16, 1985 and is believed held by Islamic
Jihad.
   Steen, an educator from Boston, was kidnapped Jan. 24, 1987 at
Beirut University College. Islamic Jihad for the Liberation of
Palestine claimed responsibility.
   Nine Americans, three Britons, an Irishman and an Italian are
missing and believed held hostage in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
