<DOCNO> AP881027-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 2352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Kashmir     10-27 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Kashmir,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>40 Injured In Kashmir Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SRINAGAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb, a firebomb attack on a police
post and a confrontation between police and youths throwing stones
injured at least 40 people in Srinigar on Thursday, including 22
police, authorities said.
   Three people were in serious condition, police said.
   The bombings were the latest in a series of explosions that
jolted the summer capital of Jammu-Kashmir state this week, but no
one was hurt until Thursday, said G.J. Pandit, director-general of
police.
   The violence coincided with a strike call by three Moslem
fundamentalist groups _ the Islamic Students League, the People's
League and the Moslem Students Federation _ on the 40th anniversary
of Jammu-Kashmir's entry into the Indian union.
   No one has claimed responsibility for any of the blasts. But
authorities have blamed pro-Pakistan militants, who oppose Kashmir's
becoming Indian.
   Kashmir has been an issue in three wars fought between India and
Pakistan and remains an issue.
</TEXT>
