<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1347EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Kristallnacht-Attacks ADV06   10-27 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Kristallnacht-Attacks, ADV 06,0712</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Night of Terror Stretched Throughout Third Reich 50 Years Ago</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Kristallnacht-50 Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer_</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adolf Hitler and his henchmen had for years been
targeting Jews for persecution, trying to force them out of the
Third Reich. By November 1938, they were looking for an excuse to
crack down more savagely.
   They found it when Herschel Grynszpan, a 17-year-old Jew enraged
by his family's deportation to Poland, shot and mortally wounded
German Embassy Third Secretary Ernst vom Rath in Paris on Nov. 7,
1938.
   Nazi leaders, in Teleptyped orders sent to local party heads
throughout the Reich, demanded brutal reprisals. In the Nazi capital
alone, seven main synagogues were burned in the hours of ransacking
and wanton violence.
   Here are brief descriptions of some of what happened in just nine
of the hundreds of other towns and cities where Nazi thugs ransacked
Jewish homes and businesses and burned synagogues on the night of
Nov. 9-10, 1938.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LEIPZIG: Hammers, axes, crowbars and firebombs are the preferred
attack weapons in this once-proud city. Firebombs hit three
synagogues at once. Mobs attack poor and rich Jews. One member of
the mob rams a stick through a priceless medieval painting depicting
a Biblical scene. Wives and mothers of men dragged off to
concentration camps desperately seek help at the U.S. consulate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   OBER-ERLENBACH: Mobs destroy the small variety store owned by the
Jordans, the last Jewish family in this town north of Frankfurt.
Someone tries to burn down the store, but a roofer stops him.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   DUESSELDORF: Nazi storm troopers push their way into the
apartment of Rabbi Max Eschelbacher chanting, ``Revenge for Paris.
Down with the Jews.''
   ``There were many dead. It was a pogrom,'' the rabbi said later.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BADEN-BADEN: Jews are rounded up at 7 a.m. on Nov. 10, to lessen
disruptions for foreign guests still visiting the world famous spa.
   Nazi SS officers order the Jewish men to march two by two through
the city behind a huge Star of David. Some local residents jeer as
they go by.
   The Jews are shoved into the synagogue, where they are forced to
read aloud passages of Adolf Hitler's viciously anti-Semitic work
``Mein Kampf.''
   Later, as they are about to be forced onto buses for the trip to
Dachau concentration camp, the men hear the fateful words, ``Our
beautiful house of worship is in flames.'' Huge flames burst from
the stone building.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LESUM: Mayor Fritz Koester listens incredulously to the local
Nazi leader's voice barking orders to him on the other end of the
telephone: ``All-out alarm of the SA in all of Germany! Reprisal
actions for the death of vom Rath. When evening comes, there can't
be any more Jews living in Germany. Jewish businesses also must be
destroyed.''
   Koester responds, ``Yes, but what's supposed to happen to the
Jews?''
   The answer rings in his ear as he sits in this northern German
town: ``Destroy, Herr Buergermeister, destroy!''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WROCLAW: Mobs burn the main synagogue along the Olawa river.
Nazi-mandated labels on storefront windows identifying which
businesses are Jewish-owned makes it easy for club-wielding thugs to
find their targets. Wroclaw, known as Breslau when it belonged to
Germany, was turned over to Poland at the end of World War II.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ZEVEN: Gangs rip fixtures from the local synagogue in this town
near Bremen and pile them three feet outside with a sign saying
``Revenge for the Death of Vom Rath.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ESSLINGEN: Gangs break into a Jewish orphanage with axes,
screaming, ``Get out!'' Prayer books and other holy writings are
tossed from windows. They threaten to burn the children to death.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   VIENNA: Twenty-one synagogues and 68 other Jewish sites are
entirely or heavily damaged. Homes are ransacked.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Information for the above came from various sources, including
history books and contemporary accounts. A major source was the book
``La Nuit de Cristal,'' a comprehesive work on the subject by Paris
University professor Rita Thalmann.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881027-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1348EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Kristallnacht-Youth ADV06   10-27 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Kristallnacht-Youth, ADV 06,0701</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Half-Century Later, Students Grapple With `Crystal Night' Legacy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Kristallnacht-50 Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>USINGEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As in hundreds of other towns across
Nazi Germany, terror struck Jews in this picturesque village on the
infamous ``Kristallnacht.'' A half-century later, students there are
still confronting the Nazi past.
   Last month, the 23 students in Stephan Kolb's history class heard
a former Jewish resident describe the tensions that led up to the
brutality of Nov. 9-10, 1938.
   Later, in a roundtable discussion with The Associated Press,
students in this town of 11,400 people north of Frankfurt discussed
the night when thugs ransacked the homes of the 10 to 15 Jews who
lived in Usingen, then a rural village.
   Martin Stenzel, 18, said Kristallnacht, named for the sparkling
shards of broken glass that littered streets and sidewalks after the
vandalism, was a ``channeling of aggression'' against the Jews.
   Asked about constant reminders of Kristallnacht and other Nazi
atrocities, he said: ``There is the danger the Nazi era could be
disposed of, or settled in a way. But this history should always be
alive.''
   Stenzel also sees sharp differences among generations in West
Germany, which has paid more than 80 billion marks ($44 billion at
1988 values) to Nazi victims and their families.
   ``The older generation has kept the prejudiced view of Jews,'' he
said, adding that this wasn't true with younger generations.
   Sonja Moses, 20, said: ``I can well imagine there were feelings
of jealousy because the Jews were merchants and in general were
better off financially. But I just don't think it could happen
again. People are more broad-minded now. They wouldn't do it again.''
   None of the six students taking part in the Oct. 13 discussion at
the Christian-Wirth School was Jewish. All are working toward the
Abitur, the examination which grants a prestigious diploma roughly
equivalent to a junior college degree in the United States.
   Ms. Moses, like her classmates, also said the older generation
views the Nazi era far differently from today's younger Germans.
   ``My grandmother tells me that Hitler brought order to the
country,'' said Ms. Moses, adding that her grandmother dwells on the
chaos that plagued the Weimar Republic after World War I. ``She says
after Hitler came to power, it wasn't that way anymore. You could
walk down the street without being afraid.''
   Albrecht Pachl, 18, agreed the ``biggest danger'' was that the
legacy of the Nazis could eventually be put aside.
   But he, too, noted that some Germans think it is time to stop
dwelling on the past.
   ``Many people feel under attack, including from people outside
the country,'' Pachl said of Holocaust reminders.
   He said he remembered watching television documentaries as a
child.
   ``I had the feeling it was aimed at me as a German,'' Pachl said.
   Kerstin Dumke, 18, said of Kristallnacht violence, ``I can
imagine that some people were swept up by what was happening, even
if they didn't have any hatred for the Jews beforehand.''
   Like the others interviewed, Ms. Dumke has traveled to other
countries, and she said the Nazi past comes up there, too.
   ``There's less interest in what is happening today than what
happened in the past. It's something that you drag around with you
all the time,'' she said.
   The students had heard from Ernst Lilienstein, 67, an Usingen
native who emigrated a year before that terrible night. A retired
New York City educator, Lilienstein studied at the Christian-Wirth
School more than 50 years ago, according to the 42-year-old Kolb.
   ``For some of them, it was the first time they'd ever seen a Jew,
knowing it was a Jew. Certainly, it was the first time many had
really talked to a Jew,'' Kolb said.
   In a telephone interview from his home in New York City,
Lilienstein said of his meeting: ``I was amazed both at their lack
of knowledge about what really happened, but also at their interest
in questioning me.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881027-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Kristallnacht-Israel ADV06   10-27 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Kristallnacht-Israel, ADV 06,0765</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Researcher: Hundreds Of Synagogues Destroyed in Nazi Pogrom</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Kristallnacht-50 Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Isroel in grafs 7-9 is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The scope of death and destruction in the
Kristallnacht pogrom against the Jews of the Third Reich 50 years
ago was much broader than widely believed, an Israeli researcher
says.
   Vandals torched synagogues and smashed Jewish property the night
of Nov. 9-10, 1938. The next day, Nazi officials announced that 36
Jews had been killed and 195 synagogues destroyed. These figures are
still widely used in history books.
   But Jerusalem professor Meier Schwarz says he has uncovered
evidence that about 1,000 Jews were killed or committed suicide, and
that at least 1,118 synagogues were vandalized.
   Kristallnacht is considered the start of the Holocaust, the
systematic destruction of European Jewry by Nazi Germany. By the end
of World War II, the Nazis had killed 6 million Jews.
   ``For German Jews, it was the final sign that they no longer had
a place there,'' said the German-born Schwarz, the only member of
his family to survive the Holocaust. ``After the Kristallnacht, we
all understood what it means to be a target.''
   Schwarz said he began his research four years ago after being
angered by official indifference on a visit to his birthplace, the
southern German city of Nuremberg, once a hotbed of Nazism.
   ``I was at city hall, and asked some official why there was no
plaque to commemorate the Adas-Isroel synagogue where my family
prayed,'' said Schwarz. ``They told me it never existed.''
   Schwarz was 12 when he saw Adas-Isroel go up in flames on
Kristallnacht. Later that night, five Brown Shirts trashed the
Schwarz family apartment with axes and knives.
   The newspaper ``Nuernberger Zeitung'' wrote about the destruction
of Adas-Isroel, an ornate three-story building with tall arched
windows: ``A heap of broken benches and ritual equipment was set up
in the middle of the building which was then set on fire. The entire
building burned down.''
   Scenes like this were repeated throughout the Reich, mostly in
Germany and Austria.
   In Nuremberg, 15 stormtroopers broke into the apartment of Else
Dormitzer and her husband, Sigmund, smashing furniture.
   ``Later, several bandits returned and beat us both. They broke my
husband's nose with a steel rod,'' Mrs. Dormitzer wrote in an
account kept at the Yad Vashem Holocaust Memorial in Jerusalem. ``We
were pushed out into the street, our bodies covered with blood.''
   Hertha Hurtig said she had just seen a Nelson Eddy-Jeanette
MacDonald movie and was riding home on a streetcar in Breslau _
today's Wroclaw in Poland _ when she saw Brown Shirts smash display
windows.
   ``They spared my husband for two days, but on the third day he
did not return from work,'' Mrs. Hurtig, who now lives in Ramat Gan
near Tel Aviv, said in a telephone interview.
   Mrs. Hurtig's late husband was one of 30,000 Jews rounded up in
the days after Kristallnacht and sent to concentration camps.
   According to Schwarz, 500 Jews died on Kristallnacht, either
killed or pushed into suicide, and 500 more perished in
concentration camps in the following days.
   In addition, at least 1,095 synagogues were torched or vandalized
in Germany and 23 others in Austria, Schwarz said in an interview.
   The figures are the result of painstaking research. Using a 1932
guide to Jewish communities in Germany, Schwarz and a few volunteers
wrote letters to German municipal officials, asking for information
about the local synagogue and an account of what happened in each
town and village on Kristallnacht.
   About 60 percent of the municipalities responded. Schwarz also
received information from German-born Jews now living in other
countries.
   The Nazis tried to portray the rampaging as the result of popular
anger over the assassination of Ernst vom Rath, third secretary at
the German Embassy in Paris, by Hershel Grynszpan, a Polish Jew. Vom
Rath was shot Nov. 7 and died two days later.
   But Schwarz and other historians say a large-scale pogrom had
been planned for several months, with the Nazis waiting for the
right time to carry it out.
   Still, Schwarz said, German Jews, the most assimilated and
secular in Europe, were taken by surprise.
   ``They said, `We are Germans, and this will pass,''' Schwarz
recalled. ``They said, `The world will not keep quiet.'''
   As history knows, they were wrong.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881027-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Kristallnacht-Habonim ADV06   10-27 0973</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Kristallnacht-Habonim, ADV 06,1001</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Out of the Ashes of Kristallnacht, a Synagogue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Kristallnacht-50 Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The flames that consumed synagogues across the
Third Reich 50 years ago still burn within hearts at Congregation
Habonim, where survivors of the Nazi assault on the Jews rebuilt
their lives and their faith.
   An altar is built of stones from synagogues demolished the night
of Nov. 9-10, 1938 _ Kristallnacht, or the Night of Broken Glass. A
charred Torah scroll hangs on the wall, its Hebrew characters
twisted as if in agony.
   The congregation is a monument as well. Rabbi Bernhard N. Cohn,
who escaped Germany as a teen-ager in 1937, estimates that more than
65 percent of the synagogue's members are survivors of the Nazi era.
   The synagogue was founded on the Upper West Side of Manhattan on
Nov. 9, 1939, precisely a year after Kristallnacht. Its name, Hebrew
for ``the builders,'' was a defiant answer to those who had
destroyed the synagogues, the shops, the homes and the comfortable
lives of German Jewry.
   ``Still, after 50 years, one cannot believe that any civilized
nation could do what was done,'' Lotte Marshall, Habonim's executive
director, said in an interview.
   She remembers seeing the synagogue of Mannheim aflame. She
recalls streets littered with glass, days spent hiding in her
family's home, the subsequent arrest of her brother and his
transport to the Dachau concentration camp.
   Mrs. Marshall gained her brother's release with forged papers.
She herself spent time in a concentration camp in France before
fleeing to America.
   Lotte Kahn, 76, also remembers.
   She and her husband were awakened by a 2:30 a.m. call from her
mother-in-law: ``Get out of your apartment right away, the furniture
is flying through the windows!''
   Mrs. Kahn took shelter with her parents while her husband set out
in search of a safer place, hoping the violence was isolated to
Dortmund. But chaos and Nazi hooligans were everywhere. He holed up
in a Protestant church and returned two days later.
   All the Jewish men of Dortmund were arrested, including Mrs.
Kahn's husband, father and uncle. Her menfolk were released in a
fortnight: ``If you ask me why they were let out ... I cannot tell
you to this day,'' she said.
   Ludwig Boettigheimer remembers the melancholy among Jews in
America.
   ``Too many of our people lost so much _ their parents, relatives,
friends were caught in Germany, and it became more and more obvious
that there was no way to get them out,'' said Boettigheimer, 80, a
Habonim founder who arrived in the United States in 1936. ``But
there was also a sense of hope. We were alive.''
   That hope was marshaled by Hugo Hahn, a charismatic rabbi who had
watched as Nazi marauders wrecked his Essen synagogue. Hahn and his
followers were determined that German Judaism would endure.
   Habonim started with three dozen founding members and services at
Manhattan's Central Synagogue. It drew some of Germany's leading
intellectuals, people like Martin Buber and Leo Baeck, to lecture
and teach. A prominent Bible expert from Frankfurt, Eduard Strauss,
came to Habonim and resumed his lessons at the precise point where
he had been interrupted by the Nazis.
   ``It grew by leaps and bounds, like wildfire,'' said
Boettigheimer. ``There was a need for prayer _ there always is in
time of trouble.''
   Membership swelled to 1,200. Separate services were conducted in
Queens, and Town Hall was rented for the High Holy Days.
   The German Jews began to assimilate. The amount of German spoken
at services diminished until it was eliminated in the 1950s; board
minutes were recorded in German for only a year or two. ``We tried
to hide our language,'' Boettigheimer explained.
   The end of the war brought numbing news of what had happened to
those left behind. Memorializing the dead became a major priority.
Each year, a Holocaust memorial service is held near the anniversary
of Kristallnacht.
   A wall of plaques records names of the dead: ``Tilly Jacobsen
perished in Theresienstadt March 1943.'' ``Emil and Lima Hertz,
Adolph, Rudolf and Herman Hertz, perished in Europe 1940-45.''
   Stones were collected from the synagogue ruins after the war;
nearly 30 years later, artist Emanuel Milstein incorporated them in
an altar as a monument to victims of the Holocaust.
   The charred Torah scroll was discovered in the gutter outside the
Essen synagogue the night after it was destroyed. It was sent for
safekeeping to a relative in Princeton, N.J., who gave it to
physicist Albert Einstein.
   Einstein, who had emigrated from Germany in 1933, displayed it
when he spoke on behalf of refugee relief. Eventually, it went to
Habonim.
   In a Queens cemetery, Habonim is about to dedicate a marble
column etched with victims' names. A brochure says, ``We will never
forget them, but let us be sure that those who come after us will
remember them, too.''
   The synagogue has had its struggles. Hahn, the synagogue's
founder and its heart, died in 1967, replaced by Cohn, his
son-in-law and an associate rabbi. Membership dropped to 600, and
religious school enrollment, once as high as 250, fell to 50. It is
60 this year.
   Habonim has attracted new, younger members, but they are in the
minority.
   ``These people don't die,'' Cohn said of the older members.
``Fiftieth wedding anniversaries are a dime a dozen in my
congregation.''
   But they do die, of course, and the congregation shrinks some
each year. The names of those who perished in Europe are read at the
annual memorial service; they are removed when their survivors die.
This year, there will be about 100 names.
   This does not sadden Boettigheimer.
   ``It is much sadder,'' he said, ``if you have a tremendous list.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 6</NOTE>
