<1ST_LINE>a a BC-BehindtheWheel ADV05-06   10-27 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Behind the Wheel, ADV 05-06,0588</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv05</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 5-6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Nissan Sentra Is Tough Little Car</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nissan Sentra is a tough little car with a
tough assignment.
   It has to battle both similarly priced subcompact cars and
lower-priced competitors. It works to attract both young singles of
moderate income and upscale parents and couples, Nissan says. And,
as the best-selling auto in the Nissan family, it's working to
bolster sales.
   The Sentra, which is imported from Japan for buyers in the
western United States and is shipped from Nissan's Smyrna, Tenn.,
plant to buyers in the eastern part of the country, has done a
commendable job.
   Redesigned for the 1987 model year, it was the eighth
best-selling nameplate in the United States with sales of more than
239,000. Also in the 1987 model year, it was rated No. 1 in quality
among subcompacts by the auto marketing research firm J.D. Power and
Associates of Westlake Village, Calif.
   For 1988, the Sentra continues to be a quality leader in
subcompacts, though it fell behind the Chevrolet Nova, Toyota
Corolla and Plymouth Colt in the 1988 J.D. Power survey of owners
who had their cars for 90 days.
   Also, a Nissan spokesman reports that sales are nearly flat for
calendar 1988. Through July, 123,625 Sentras were sold vs. 124,468
in the same period in 1987.
   The test car, a 1988 Sentra GXE sedan, had fine fit and finish
inside and out, except for the plastic fuel-cap holder on the fuel
filler door.
   The holder came right off when I tried to use it. But it also was
easy to put back on. I ignored it and put the cap on the car roof
while refueling.
   The car's interior was spartan and easy to live with. Dashboard
gauges were simple to read and seats were comfortable. Because it is
a subcompact, however, the Sentra offers a snug fit for three adults
in back, and legroom there also was tight.
   The trunk was flat and sizable, though it was covered with a thin
layer of material that tended to bunch up under luggage. Road noise
was moderate, and you can count on getting decent fuel economy.
   The engine, a 1.6-liter, fuel-injected four cylinder teamed with
three-speed automatic transmission, was a bit sluggish. There were
times when it chugged and the car jerked, trying to get in the right
gear. This was also when the air conditioner was on full blast.
   Base price for the GXE sedan with automatic transmission is
$10,844. Competitors include the Honda Civic sedan, which is priced
around $11,000 with automatic transmission, and the Hyundai Excel
sedan, which is priced around $7,400 with automatic transmission.
   Nissan says Sentra buyers have median age of between 30 and 39.
Median income is from $30,000 to just under $50,000. Many buyers are
couples and parents, and there also are a number of single females
who earn more than $50,000 annually, the company says.
   From 1982-86, the latest years available, Consumer Reports'
trouble survey of owners showed Sentras having average, better than
average or much better than average ratings.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Job, former executive business editor of The
Detroit News, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The Associated
Press. She has covered the automobile industry for six years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 5-6</NOTE>
