<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1318EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s p BC-Quayle-Veep ADV30   10-27 0928</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Quayle-Veep, ADV 30,0946</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 30 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Silver Spoon' Past, Experience Cloud Quayle Candidacy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON (AP)_ Dan Quayle's vice presidential campaign has been
haunted by his past, doubts about his qualifications and the
perception he has led an easy life in which the truly tough problems
were solved by mom and dad.
   Controversy marred his elevation from relative obscurity to the
national spotlight as George Bush's running mate. And it stymied his
attempt to show the country he was more than ``just a pretty face.''
   The notion that the Indiana senator was born with the proverbial
silver spoon, never having to struggle for money or power, is borne
out by his past. As Quayle once told an interviewer, ``Life has been
very good to me. I never had to worry about where I was going to
go.''
   Quayle, 41, has constantly had to defend himself against charges
he is unqualified to be a heartbeat away from the presidency. In
response, he touts his chief accomplishments in 12 years in
Congress: co-authorship of a job training act and detailed work on
the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces Treaty and other arms-control
issues.
   Before his Oct. 5 debate with Democratic vice presidential
nominee Lloyd Bentsen, Quayle frequently added another point, saying
he has about the same legislative experience that John F. Kennedy
had when he sought the presidency in 1960. That line was dropped
after Bentsen's devastating rebuke: ``Senator, you're no Jack
Kennedy.''
   Quayle denounced as ``side-events'' questions about his military
service, academic record and personal life, but his campaign has
never completely escaped them. Signs reading ``Chickenhawk,'' ``Who
died in your place, Danny?'' and ``Sissy Rich Kid'' confront him
from one state to another.
   Quayle's grandfather was the conservative, self-made publishing
magnate, Eugene C. Pulliam. In 1955, at the age of 8, Quayle and his
family moved from his native Indianapolis to Phoenix, where his
father, James, ran Pulliam newspapers and joined the John Birch
Society. The Quayles returned to Indiana in 1963 and his father
became publisher _ and young Dan eventually became associate
publisher _ of The Huntington Herald-Press.
   Quayle has spent a good part of the campaign of 1988 explaining
how he spent the 1960s. Drugs were ``totally unbeknownst to me,'' he
said, and while that may seem ``a sheltered life, ... that's a life
in the Midwest ... a life in a small town in Indiana.''
   His performance at DePauw University was average. Graduating in
1969 during the Vietnam War, Quayle would have been eligible for the
draft but instead sought admission to the National Guard. He
explained to reporters that he did ``what any normal person would do
... call home to mother and father and say, `I'd like to get in the
National Guard.'''
   One of Congress' more ardent hawks, Quayle insists he wasn't
trying to dodge the draft _ just to be able to attend law school _
and that no undue pressure was applied to get him into the Guard.
Guard officials said there were openings even in the public
relations unit he joined. But a retired major general acknowledged
that he asked that a space be held for Quayle after a retired Guard
commander _ a Pulliam employee _ called to recommend him.
   The future politician also had to do some explaining about how he
managed to get into Indiana University School of Law when his grades
clearly were lacking.
   James Quayle said his son was able to convince the law school
that he was qualified on grounds his undergraduate education at the
small, private DePauw was more intense than might have been
available at a public institution.
   Young Quayle was accepted into law school after meeting with the
admissions dean, a Republican judge in Lebanon, Ind., where the
family owns the local paper. The same judge would later marry Quayle
and his wife, Marilyn Tucker, who met in law school and wed after a
10-week courtship.
   After questions were raised this summer about his academic
background, Quayle acknowledged he had never been an exemplary
student but refused to release his law school records. He deemed
them irrelevant to the campaign and contended ``no rules were
broken'' to get him admitted.
   During the campaign, Quayle was peripherally touched by an old
scandal. Former Washington lobbyist Paula Parkinson claimed he had
propositioned her on a 1980 golf outing in Florida when she was
staying in a vacation house with several lawmakers, including
Quayle. Quayle angrily denied the accusation and said he had been
there only to play golf.
   His often-stilted delivery and early avoidance of the press
contributed to the image of a shaky political newcomer tightly
controlled by Bush headquarters. His wife was especially protective,
pulling his sleeve or abruptly saying, ``Thank you, senator'' to end
press encounters.
   When, two months into the campaign, Quayle declared his
independence from his ``handlers,'' reporters were skeptical. The
candidate turned affable and accessible _ but he didn't abandon the
mission that the party had laid out for him: to portray Democratic
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis as a liberal out of touch with
mainstream America.
   While Democrats have preyed on voter doubts about Quayle's
qualifications _ polls suggested he was a drag on the ticket _ he
did not attempt to dispel the idea he could be president one day. In
fact, Quayle says that at one point he talked with his wife about
running for president himself this year.
   ``It was a very casual discussion,'' he added.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 30</NOTE>
