<HEAD>Democrats' No. 2 Had to Fight Liberal Label Too</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen knew what it was to
run against the ``liberal'' label and tough negative advertising
long before he was chosen to be Michael Dukakis' running mate. He is
using that experience in a late effort to take the edge off the
Bush-Quayle campaign.
   Bentsen, a 67-year-old native Texan, was at first shy about
directly attacking GOP presidential nominee George Bush, whom he
considered a friend. Now, judging that two months of negative
Republican advertising has damaged the Democrats, Bentsen has taken
off the gloves.
   In an Oct. 18 speech in Los Angeles, he made the GOP ads the
central focus of his own campaign, unleashing a blistering attack on
the Republicans and their effort to destroy Dukakis' character.
   ``What happened _ almost without notice _ is an utterly vicious
assault of distortion and character assassination'' carried out by
Republicans spending ``millions of dollars on television cutting him
up,'' Bentsen said. ``They don't seem to mind if what they say is
untrue ... misleading ... downright mean.''
   Little of the GOP fire has been directed at Bentsen. Instead,
Bush and running mate Dan Quayle have zeroed in on Dukakis, taunting
him at every turn as a liberal. Bentsen, hre a grand jury in Suffolk County,
where Profeta's church is located, and answered questions about her
former pastor. Her lawyer said that the grand jury was investigating
matters that included a break-in at her Long Island apartment last
year and ``the whole Jim Bakker thing.''
   According to today's indictment, Profeta tried to get Ms. Hahn to
lie to the grand jury about gifts she received from him, including
fur coats, casino trips, hotel stays, jewelry, apartment rent and
automobile payments.
   Since the publicity about her involvement with Bakker, Ms. Hahn
has been featured in Playboy pictorials and interviews and stayed at
the Playboy mansion in California.
   Albany County Judge Joseph Harris issued the protection order for
Ms. Hahn at Crusco's request, despite contentions by Profeta's
lawyer that such an order would add to a ``media circus''
surrounding the case and deprive Profeta of a fair trial.
   Attorney John Gross said the order implied that the witness
tampering allegations against the minister were true.
   Harris replied there was no such implication and that Profeta
would receive a fair trial.
   Profeta, dressed in a pinstripe suit, lavender shirt, striped tie
and ankle-high boots, offered no comment as he was led out of the
courtroom and taken to a holding cell in the courthouse. His lawyer
refused to discuss the case.
   ``These charges represent a scheme to cheat the state and all
law-abiding taxpayers,'' said state Attorney General Robert Abrams.
``But more importantly, Rev. Profeta allegedly abused the
not-for-profit status of a religious organization for his own
personal gain.''
   In setting $25,000 bail, Harris said he wanted assurances from
Gross that the money wasn't from church funds. Gross had argued that
no bail was needed while Crusco asked for $100,000 bail.
   ``This man has been a minister for over 30 years,'' Gross said.
``He's got a congregation of over 1,000. There is no proof to these
charges.''
   Glenda Profeta, 41, had her case postponed until next month. She
is recuperating at home from an infection she contracted after
surgery, Gross said.
   The Profetas each face a maximum of four years in prison on
charges of tax evasion and offering a false instrument for filing,
the most serious charges against them.
