<2ND_LINE>BC-Reagan, ADV 30,0766</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 30 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reagan Seizing Every Opportunity to Put in a Good Word for Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whether campaigning around the country or
hosting an official White House event, President Reagan is seizing
on every opportunity to plug George Bush's candidacy and warn
Americans against sending a ``liberal'' to the White House.
   Academics and political experts differ on the extent to which the
presidential race between Bush and Democrat Michael Dukakis is a
referendum on Reagan's nearly 8-year-old presidency. And they
disagree about Reagan's impact on the electorate.
   But no one questions the 77-year-old president's sincerity in
waging a tireless campaign on behalf of his vice president.
   ``I think he's made the whole Republican Party learn and remember
the experience of 1960,'' said Larry Sabato, a University of
Virginia governmental studies scholar. ``He's doing for Bush what
(Dwight D.) Eisenhower wouldn't do for (Richard M.) Nixon.''
   Since Labor Day, Reagan has traveled to 13 states, the bulk of
them in the tossup Midwest, and has raised $8.8 million for local
and state Republican parties and congressional candidates. He's
picked up the tempo in the waning days of the campaign, with a
whirlwind tour of California and visits to such border states as
Arkansas, Maryland and Missouri.
   Wherever he goes, Reagan delivers a standard stump speech,
telling Americans they'd be risking their future by electing Dukakis
as his successor. He sprinkles stump speeches with the word
``liberal.''
   Most of all, Reagan has reveled in the many appearances he has
made at high schools and college campuses, predictably invoking Gen.
George C. Marshall's quote about ``the best blankety-blank kids in
the world.''
   Standing in a corner of the hardwood floor in the Western
Kentucky University fieldhouse on Oct. 21, Reagan launched a gift
basketball in the direction of a basket. While some 12,000 young
people roared, he missed, missed again, and then bounced one in off
the backboard.
   His most enthusiastic receptions have come from young people such
as those in Kentucky, many of whom flashed ``We Love Ronnie'' and
``Thanks Mr. President'' signs.
   ``He has an infectious way about him,'' mused Kentucky Republican
Party Chairman Bob Gable. ``Clearly, they understood him. I have to
think the kind of exuberance you saw there will translate into Bush
as his successor.''
   ``I think he loves it,'' said White House political aide Frank
Lavin, who said Reagan has appeared at 21 campaign events since
Labor Day, including one with Bush in Houston, and has appeared at
several events for Republican Senate candidates.
   Reagan's top aides have said that the election of Bush is just
one of Reagan's campaign goals. He believes that it must be
accompanied by some major GOP strides in Congress.
   White House chief of staff Kenneth M. Duberstein, discussing
Reagan's political role before a Chamber of Commerce audience, said
the president wants to push GOP candidacies at the local level ``to
encourage fair reapportionment by increasing Republican
representation in state legislatures.''
   Speaking of Reagan's influence in the campaign, Brookings
Institution presidential scholar Stephen Hess said, ``We can't have
a controlled experiment because we don't know what it would be like
if he sat on the sidelines. But clearly, there's an awful lot of
referendum in this election.''
   Hess said that Bush has not taken policy stands that are
``measurably different'' from Reagan's, and thus the president has a
right ``to claim credit, in fact most of the credit'' if Bush beats
Dukakis on Nov. 8.
   ``To that degree, he's (Reagan) an important factor because he's
incredibly popular. It's phenomenal for a president in his eighth
year to have 60 percent approval ratings.''
   Richard Wiener, chairman of the Democratic Party in Michigan,
disagreed.
   Unimpressed by Reagan's foray earlier this month to the
blue-collar enclave of Macomb County, and by the president's appeal
to the so-called ``Reagan Democrats,'' Wiener said, ``I don't think
the visit made much of a difference once way or another.''
   ``We saw that in both 1984 and 1986, when he had no coattails
here,'' Wiener said.
   But Michigan GOP Chairman Spencer Abraham said he thought Reagan
had been fortunate to be able to take such a high-profile role in
Bush's presidential campaign, noting that Lyndon Johnson in 1968
``had become a political liability'' and that he likely could not
have been used in Hubert H. Humphrey's behalf, even if both men had
wanted that.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 30</NOTE>
