<1ST_LINE>s i BC-OilBarrel-Algeria ADV30   10-27 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Oil Barrel-Algeria, ADV 30,0466</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 30, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Declining Oil Prices Give Rise to North African Unrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Oil Barrel Blues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RACHID KHIARI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Underlying Algeria's recent violent
demonstrations is an economic crisis blamed in large measure on the
plummeting price of oil.
   Almost 95 percent of Algeria's export earnings come from
petroleum, and the value of these exports has fallen by more than 40
percent since 1981, from $14.1 billion to $8.4 billion last year.
   If movements in the dollar's value and world inflation are taken
into account, the real purchasing power of these earnings now is
barely one-third of what it was eight years ago.
   The drop in prices was particularly hard on this North African
nation because it was in the middle of several huge development
projects. The current account balance, which had shown a surplus of
more than $1 billion in 1985, fell $1.48 billion into the red in
1986.
   Meanwhile, Algeria's population is among the fastest growing in
the world. Since 1980, the country has grown by 25.6 percent, from
18.7 million people in 1980 to nearly 24 million today. The
population has more than doubled since the country won independence
from France in 1962.
   About 60 percent of the country is younger than 20, and many of
these people took to the streets in October to protest the falling
standard of living, rising unemployment, inflation and food
shortages _ all related to the sharp drop in oil revenue.
   More than 150 people were killed, hundreds were injured and an
estimated 3,000 people were arrested in nearly a week of
demonstrations that rocked the capital and many smaller towns.
   The riots prompted apparent government reforms. President Chadli
Bendjedid, who came to power in 1979, announced a Nov. 3 referendum
on what reporters describe as ``broad democratization.''
   Algeria is only the latest victim of violence prompted by falling
oil prices. Other countries, including Egypt, Nigeria and Tunisia,
have suffered similar unrest and upheaval.
   An International Monetary Fund report published in 1987 noted
that the drop in the prices of oil and other raw materials cost
Third World countries nearly $100 billion in 1986. The loss of
revenue came against a backdrop of sharply declining international
lending to developing countries.
   Algeria is committed to a program of ``trade not aid'' and is
seeking to win back revenues by substitute other exports such as
uranium.
   The country has declined rescheduling payments on its $20 billion
foreign debt. Servicing costs swallow up nearly 60 percent of its
export revenue.
   Algeria also imports most of its food at a cost of more than $1
billion a year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
