<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 2311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-NuclearStandstill ADV30-1stAdd   10-27 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Nuclear Standstill, ADV 30-1st Add,0632</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 30, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHN: billion thereafter.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Another alarming situation exists at Fernald, about 20 miles from
Cincinnati. Workers struck the plant nearly a month ago,
interrupting production.
   The state of Ohio, on behalf of the 14,000 people living near the
plant, has filed a $300 million lawsuit against the federal
contractor there, National Lead, based on admissions by the Energy
Department in January 1985 that the facility spewed at least 200,000
pounds of radioactive uranium oxide dust into the air. The
department also said the plant leaked radioactive waste into the
ground, possibly endangering the Great Miami River aquifer, which
supplies water for communities throughout southwestern Ohio.
   Ohio Gov. Richard Celeste earlier this month demanded that the
Energy Department close down the plant, but thought better of the
idea last Monday and asked the feds to stick around to clean up the
mess.
   ``I shudder to think what would happen if the Department of
Defense washed its hands of this facility,'' said Celeste. ``We know
that a clean-up can be accomplished, and the people best to do it
are the people who work here.''
   The cleanup and corrective costs at Fernald have been estimated
by the Energy Department at $1.1 billion through 1995 and $1.2
billion thereafter.
   Lesser problems have been reported at two nearby plants, in
Dayton and Portsmouth, and the department envisioned no clean-up
costs for the remaining Ohio plant, at Ashtabula.
   Meanwhile, problems at the Rocky Flats Plant are snowballing.
Building 771, where plutonium is reprocessed, was closed down after
two workers suffered low-grade contamination Sept. 29.
   Pat Echart, a spokesman for contractor Rockwell International,
said the 6,000 employees at the plant have continued working at
other buildings on the site. Among their jobs _ processing plutonium
for nuclear triggers.
   Last August, it was disclosed that Energy Department officials
had considered shutting down Rocky Flats because of repeated safety
violations and ``lax attitudes,'' charges that were repeated in a
congressional study released earlier this month.
   Safety complaints at the plant jumped six-fold from 1982 to 1987,
officials of the United Steel Workers Local 8031 announced in March
1987.
   The Environmental Protection Agency, meanwhile, reported last
June that 103 waste-disposal sites needed to be cleaned up. The
Energy Department has estimated the cost of cleanup and correction
there at $576 million to $900 million through 1995, plus $185
million subsequently.
   At other facilities:
   _The Pinellas Plant on central Florida's Gulf Coast grabbed
national headlines in 1983 when the House Energy Committee reported
that its security system failed in a series of mock attacks.
   Security has been tightened there, but investigators have
reported that radioactive and toxic wastes from the 100-acre site
had seeped into Boca Ciega Bay, a popular residential and
recreational area. The cost of cleaning and correcting the seepage,
and coping with other waste problems is forecast to cost $42.4
million through 1995, and up to $9 million thereafter.
   _Environmental improvement at the Oak Ridge site in Tennessee is
expected to cost $1.3 billion through 1995, with much of the money
going to locating buried nuclear waste and cleaning up sediment
ponds. Four research reactors at Oak Ridge have been closed down.
   _Early atomic weapons tests at the Nevada test site were
conducted above ground. Residents of nearby southern Utah contend
the tests caused increased incidences of cancer in their communities
and among veterans who watched the explosions. Tests are conducted
below-ground now, although there have been reports of venting, in
which radioactive material escaped to the surface.
   Environmental costs at the test sites are estimated at $634
million through 1995, and up to $750 million thereafter.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 30</NOTE>
