<DOCNO> AP881027-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0040EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   10-27 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0558</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy expanded at a modest 2.2
percent annual rate during the summer, the slowest pace in almost
two years, as the drought and a worsening trade deficit slowed
economic activity.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday the performance of the
gross national product, the broadest measure of economic health,
slowed sharply from July through September after growing at an
annual rate of 3.2 percent in the first six months of the year.
   The Reagan administration blamed much of the sluggishness on
temporary factors such as the drought.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First-year base wage increases excluding
cost-of-living adjustments or COLAs averaged 3.3 percent in major
union contracts negotiated in the first nine months of this yearm,
according to the Labor Department.
   Union workers under major contracts received effective pay
increases averaging 3.5 percent over the past year, including COLAs
but not lump-sum bonuses now prevalent in manufacturing, the Labor
Department said Wednesday.
   The average annual increase in the new contracts falls to 2.8
percent over their usual two-to-three-year lives, the Bureau of
Labor Statistics said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The proposed $2.2 billion merger between
PacifiCorp and Utah Power & Light has been approved by the Federal
Energy Regulatory Commission, but only on condition that the new
company provide space on its transmission lines for other utilities
to ship electricity.
   The merger approved Wednesday would create the nation's 13th
largest utility serving more than 1.2 million customers in
California, Washington, Oregon, Montana, Idaho, Wyoming and Utah.
   The commission's handling of the case has been closely watched by
the utility industry, which has been swept by talk over the last
several years of deregulation and increased competition.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly $19 billion changes hands in America
yearly as family members help one another _ children aiding aging
parents, mom and dad helping offspring start a household, according
to the Census Bureau.
   Wednesday's report showed that the largest share of the
assistance is child support provided by adults to children no longer
living with them. That accounts for 63 percent of total, the bureau
said in its first survey of monetary help exchanged within families.
   But about one-third of those giving money to relatives were
aiding an adult _ most often elderly parents, the bureau learned.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada's Varity Corp. has halted talks on the
possible acquisition of Fruehauf Corp.
   The troubled Detroit-based truckmaker said Wednesday it would
explore other options. Fruehauf reported a net loss of $41.5 million
on sales of $1.84 billion in 1987.
   Varity spokesman J.R. Nowling said he didn't expect further
efforts to acquire Fruehauf though he didn't rule out discussions
about its Kelsey-Hayes automotive subsidiary. Fruehauf will continue
to explore alternatives.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market retreated as a new government report showed the
economy is slowing. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped
8.18 to 2,165.18.
   The dollar fell Wednesday to its lowest point since late June.
Gold prices rose.
   Bond prices mostly were higher.
   In other markets, crude oil futures rose, livestock and pork
futures fell; and grain and soybean futures rebounded slightly after
declining for four straight sessions.
