<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mixed In Dull Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the absence of any market-moving developments,
crude oil futures prices have been mixed in dull, quiet trading.
   ``The market is just waiting for the next rumor to come out of
OPEC,'' said Peter Beutel, an energy analyst with Elders Futures Inc.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries was scheduled
to meet several times this month to discuss controlling production
as a way to prop up worldwide oil prices, which have fallen sharply
in recent weeks.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the December contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, rose 15 cents
Wednesday to settle at $13.41 a barrel, after rising 9 cents on
Tuesday. Other contract months also were higher.
   Among refined products, unleaded gasoline closed at 51.67 cents a
gallon, down 0.27 cent. The contract had risen 1.98 cents on
Tuesday. The November contract for home heating oil, which rose 0.46
cent in the previous session, closed up 1.19 cents at 41.55 cents a
gallon.
   Analysts said the market had little reaction to a report
Wednesday from the Islamic Republic news agency that Iran would
continue to oppose an OPEC production quota for Iraq, its 8-year war
foe, equal to its own.
   Iraq said recently it would maintain its production at a minimum
2.7 million barrels per day, nearly double its assigned OPEC quota.
Iran, meanwhile, is pushing its daily production toward 3 million
barrels, well above its 2.3 million barrel quota.
</TEXT>
