<DOCNO> AP881027-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SmithBarney Bjt   10-27 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Smith Barney, Bjt,0773</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New CEO Frank Zarb Says Smith Barney Can Succeed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who soon will take the helm of
beleaguered brokerage Smith Barney Inc. says the firm can succeed in
the hotly competitive investment business by serving specific
markets instead of the masses.
   ``Smith Barney is a really sound organization. It has been around
for 114 years,'' Frank G. Zarb said in a recent interview. ``There
is room in this business for a high-quality firm that is in selected
areas and is not trying to be all things to all people.''
   Zarb, 53, a prominent Wall Street figure who served as energy
czar under President Gerald Ford, will be working for old-time
acquaintance Sanford I. Weill effective Nov. 1, as chairman and
chief executive of Smith Barney.
   Weill is chairman of Commercial Credit Group Inc., which is
acquiring Smith Barney's parent Primerica Corp. Weill, 55, will be
chairman, president and chief executive officer of the merged
company, while Gerald Tsai Jr., chairman of Primerica, will be a
director and chairman of the executive committee.
   Weill created the brokerage firm that now is Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. and Zarb worked in various capacities at its predecessor
firms. In addition to serving as President Ford's chief energy
administrator, Zarb currently is an adviser to Congress and several
foreign governments.
   Smith Barney, a mid-size investment bank specializing in retail
brokerage and municipal finance, disbanded its arbitrage department
_ which essentially speculated on takeover stocks _ after losing $43
million in last year's stock market crash. Smith Barney posted a $15
million profit in the first quarter of this year and a $3 million
loss in the second quarter.
   Analysts say Zarb has his work cut out for him.
   Greenwich-based Primerica acquired Smith Barney last year for
$750 million, loading itself up with new debt just months before the
stock market crash, and subsequent slowdown in the securities
business.
   The success of Smith Barney is regarded as a swing factor for the
profit of the entire corporation.
   ``The key to success there is to control the operating expenses
and try to generate additional revenues from high margin
businesses,'' said David Hochstim, equity analyst with Shearson
Lehman Hutton in San Francisco.
   Hochstim said Smith Barney needs a strong merger and acqusitions
department to boost its earnings.
   ``That's not something that is easily built overnight,'' he said
in a telephone interview from his San Francisco office.``They have a
good retail sales force, a good equity research department, but they
are not a real force in M&A (mergers and acqusitions) or investment
banking and that's where the money is being made.''
   But he also said the announcement of the merger between Primerica
and Commercial Credit already had benefited Smith Barney.
   ``One of the key points is that since the announced merger,
morale at Smith Barney has improved dramatically and that's worth a
lot,'' he said. ``You no longer have people worrying about their
jobs and future. They're back to work.''
   Other analysts say Smith Barney needs to be a full-service firm _
right now, it doesn't offer a full line of financial products _ but
Zarb disagrees.
   ``Full service implies a large warehouse that does everything for
everyone, whether they do it well or not,'' Zarb said. ``That's not
what we're going to do.
   ``I want to build on what has been a very old and fine reputation
and built it into a firm in the 1990s that will be an important
participant in the upper ends of the marketplace,'' he said.
   Weill and Tsai say Zarb's record and leadership qualities are
what Smith Barney needs.
   ``Frank has two characteristics that I think are key,'' Weill
said in an interview earlier this week. ``Number one, he is a leader
and I think a leader is a person who knows how to listen and get the
most out of people and move something from point a to point b.
   ``Number two, Frank is a winner. He started in Shearson's back
office...and take that through his success in government. He was
assistant secretary of labor and left as energy czar on the
President's Federal Energy Administration,'' Weill said.
   ``I'm convinced he will bring in new talent and motivate the
current management team,'' Tsai said in an interview Wednesday.
``It's a difficult market and if everybody is having a tough time
and you have a new breath of fresh air...I think he will do a lot.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
