<DOCNO> AP881027-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Mexico-MineSale     10-27 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Mine Sale,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fate of Two Copper Mines to be Decided Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pending sales of two government-owned
copper mines could bring debt-ridden Mexico $2 billion, a government
spokesman says.
   The winning bidders for Mexicana de Cobre and Compania Minera de
Cananea will be announced next Tuesday, the government said
Wednesday. Bidding on the two mines in northern Sonora state closed
today.
   The announcement ended speculation that the government had
changed its mind on the controversial sale.
   Jose Romero Contente, of the government development bank Nacional
Financiera, said he expects Mexicana de Cobre will be sold for at
least $1.1 billion while not less than $910 million will be accepted
for Compania Minera de Cananea, Mexico's most historic mine.
   The two companies have debts totaling about $2 billion, Romero
Contente said, but are considered good investments mainly because of
the price of copper is rising in world markets.
   Under a plan to reduce government subsidies and help Mexico
overcome its economic crisis, President Miguel de la Madrid has sold
many government-owned companies, most of them money losers, to
private investors. Most of Mexico's $104 billion foreign debt is
owed by the government.
   Romero Contente said the mine sales would be the crowning
achievement in de la Madrid's re-privatization plan.
   ``Either one of those is the biggest sale by any government in
Latin America in history,'' Romero Contente said by telephone
Wednesday from Mexico City.
   ``They signify an important part of de la Madrid's pledge to
reduce the size of the public sector,'' said Romero Contente,
coordinator of the mine sales for Nacional Financiera, or Nafinsa.
   But the sale has met opposition in Cananea, 25 miles south of the
Arizona border, where the ``martyrs of 1906'' have not been
forgotten.
   A bloody strike at what was then the American-owned Cananea
Consolidated Copper Co. 82 years ago has come to symbolize the birth
of Mexico's nationalistic spirit and union movement.
   At least 11 men died in the strike, launched by Mexican miners
who got paid less than American workers at the mine.
   Joaquin Quijano Salazar, general secretary of the powerful
National Miners Union Section 65 that represents the 3,000 unionized
workers at Cananea, said in a recent interview that the union would
oppose the sale.
   ``They can sell a company, but they can't sell workers,'' Quijano
said in a telephone interview last month. ``We hope they don't find
someone to sell it to.''
   Calls to Quijano's office at the mine did not go through
Wednesday.
   Romero Contente said Nafinsa has had ``no problem with the union.
It knows the federal government's policy.''
   Two companies have bid on Cananea, Penoles and Protexa, which is
based in this northern Nuevo Leon state capital.
   Protexa's $910 million finanincing package was rejected this
summer by Nafinsa, which led to speculation that the mine would not
be sold during the current administration that ends Dec. 1.
   Romero Contente said four companies have put deposits of nearly
$11,000 for the right to bid Thursday on Mexicana de Cobre.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
