<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     10-27 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges Over Slow U.S. Growth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped sharply today in Tokyo,
apparently reflecting disappointment over the slow growth of the
American economy, while share prices rose on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The dollar's decline followed the release of the latest gross
national product figure, showed the U.S. economy grew at an annual
rate of 2.2 percent during the third quarter of the year compared to
3 percent and 3.4 percent growth in the first two quarters.
   The dollar closed at 125.90 yen, down 0.90 yen from Wednesday's
close of 126.80 yen. The currency opened sharply lower at 125.95 yen
and declined further, ranging between 125.80 yen and 126.15 yen.
   To keep the dollar from declining further, Bank of Japan
intervened and bought dollars shortly after the market opened,
according to Takamasa Yamasaki of the Daiwa Bank.
   Bank of Japan's governor Satoshi Sumita declined comment on the
bank's intervention. The central bank of Japan rarely comments on
its actions.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, meanwhile, share prices gained
102.31 points, or 0.37 percent, to finish at 27,722.92. The index
gained 106.00 points shortly after the market opened and kept most
of that.
   On Wednesday, it closed at 27,620.60 points.
   The lower-than-expected U.S. GNP figure helped end investors'
concerns over inflation and spurred their buying interest today,
said an analyst with a major securities firm in Tokyo.
   Trading was hectic with volume on the first section estimated at
2 billion shares. Among the issues attracting investors were steels
and shipbuilding.
</TEXT>
