<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     10-27 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in Europe today after falling
to four-month lows on a report of unexpectedly low U.S. economic
growth. Gold also was mixed.
   The U.S. currency fluctuated in a narrow range in moderately
active trading. Dealers in Frankfurt and Tokyo reported modest
intervention by the West German and Japanese central bank in support
of the dollar. The banks, as is their custom, declined to comment.
   Dealers said U.S. economic performance was keeping the dollar
low, but market fears of central bank intervention were preventing
it falling further.
   ``The dollar is falling and it has to fall. The only question
mark is the central bank intervention policy,'' said an Italian
trader.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.90 yen to a closing 125.90 yen. Later, in London,
it slipped back even further to 125.70 yen.
   It was the lowest dollar-yen rate recorded in Tokyo since June
17, when the dollar closed at 125.73 yen.
   The dollar's latest decline was triggered by U.S. gross national
product figures which showed the U.S. economy grew at an annual rate
of 2.2 percent during the third quarter of the year compared with 3
percent and 3.4 percent growth in the first two quarters.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.7750 West German marks, up from 1.7745; 1.4975
Swiss francs, down from 1.5065; 6.0635 French francs, down from
6.0725; 2.0035 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0005; 1,322.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,323.50; and 1.1990 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1988.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7580, compared with
$1.7600 Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $408.10 a troy ounce, up
from $407.05 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $407.15.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $406.95, down from $407.10 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 54 cents to close at a bid
$409.22.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.22 a troy
ounce, up from Wednesday's $6.21.
</TEXT>
