<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0913EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pepperell     10-27 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pepperell,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Point Puts Severance Plan In Place To Protect Employees In
Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textile giant West Point-Pepperell Inc., facing a
takeover fight with Farley Inc., has created a financial cushion for
more than 14 percent of its employees who might find themselves
without a job under a new owner.
   However, Pepperell said Tuesday, the severance pay package has
nothing to do with the $1.4 billion tender offer announced Monday by
Farley, one of the nation's largest privately held conglomerates.
   D. Michael Roark, Pepperell's vice president of human resources,
said the severance plan was adopted by the board last week.
   ``This is not something we did in response to Bill Farley,''
Roark said. William Farley heads the conglomerate which owns
underwear manufacturer Fruit of the Loom and other companies.
   ``We had been talking (about the plan) in the management group
for several months,'' Roark said in a telephone interview from the
company's Pepperell, Ga., headquarters.
   ``This was not, and we don't now consider it, `shark
repellent,''' he said, referring to jargon used to describe tactics
companies use to fend off corporate raiders.
   A Farley spokesman said the company would have no comment on the
provision.
   Roark said the plan _ which guarantees at least three months pay
to some 5,900 salaried and clerical employees _ would not involve
enough money to dissuade a suitor. However, he had no estimate on
the amount of money involved, saying it would depend on how many
employees were involved and their level of seniority.
   The decision fits in with a series of moves Pepperell has taken
this year to strengthen its ability to fight a takeover.
   In June, the company adopted a shareholder rights plan which
would allow the board to issue a special class of stock as a
dividend to current stockholders. The ``poison pill'' plan would
take effect as soon as a tender offer is launched or if someone
purchases 10 percent of Pepperell stock.
   Farley notified the company in May it was seeking up to 25
percent of Pepperell stock and so far has spent $88 million for 9.8
percent of the stock.
   The company is also one of the first to adopt Georgia's new
anti-takeover law, enacted by the Legislature principally at the
urging of textile industry lobbyists. The main provision of the law,
which took effect in March, limits a new owner's ability to sell off
parts of a company for five years.
   Pepperell also has had in place for some time so-called ``golden
parachutes'' for executives, including a $1.39 million payout to
Chief Executive Officer Joseph L. Lanier Jr. if he were to be fired
by new owners.
   The new state law, and the ``poison pill'' plan have been
challenged by Farley in federal court and a Pepperell stockholder,
who filed a suit in state Superior Court Tuesday, claiming
stockholders are deprived of the highest possible stock price.
   The severance plan covers all salaried and certain skilled
clerical workers.
   Pepperell is the nation's largest publicly held textile and
apparel company. Earlier this year, the company and the investment
group Odyssey Partners Inc. jointly acquired J.P. Stevens & Co. Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
