<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Earns-Autos 1stLd-Writethru   10-27 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earns-Autos, 1st Ld-Writethru,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Third Quarter Profit Up; Chrysler, GM To Report Earnings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs with Chrysler earnings report; picks up 3rd
graf, On Wednesday, Release time for GM earnings report uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. said today its third-quarter
earnings fell 54.3 percent compared with the same period a year ago,
mainly because of heavy costs for incentives and the retooling of a
Delaware assembly plant.
   The nation's No. 3 automaker said it earned $112.5 million, or 50
cents a share, on sales of $7.01 billion during the July-September
period this year. During the three-month period last year, Chrysler
said it earned $246 million, or $1.12 a share, on sales of $6.17
billion.
   In a statement, Chrysler said that in addition to the high costs
of incentives, which the company used extensively to lure buyers
into showrooms, and the closing for the entire period of the Newark,
Del., assembly plant, the company had a heavier proportion of fleet
sales over more profitable individual car sales.
   General Motors Corp. was expected to announce its third-quarter
results today, a day after No. 2 Ford Motor Co. posted a 21.8
percent rise in its third-quarter earnings _ its 10th straight
report of record quarterly profits.
   For the first nine months of this year, Chrysler's earnings fell
34.4 percent to $616.6 million, or $2.77 a share, from $939.5
million, or $4.33 a share, last year. Sales for the first nine
months of 1988 amounted to $23.17 billion, compared with $18.61
billion in 1987, a 24.5 percent increase.
   Also today, Chrysler Financial Corp. reported record
third-quarter earnings of $59 million, 20 percent more than the $49
million it earned during the third quarter of last year. For the
first nine months of 1988, the financial arm of Chrysler Corp.
earned $185 million, a nine-month record and up 12 percent from the
$166 million it earned during the January-September period last year.
   On Wednesday, Ford said it earned $856.3 million, or $1.78 per
share, on sales of $17.73 billion during the July-September period
this year. That compares with earnings of $703.2 million, or $1.38 a
share, on sales of $15.25 billion during the same period last year.
   For the first nine months of the year, Ford earned $4.1 billion,
or $8.53 a share, on sales of $60.9 billion, up 12.2 percent from
earnings of $3.7 billion, or $7.17 a share on sales of $52.9 billion
during the January-September period last year.
   David McCammon, Ford's vice president for finance and treasurer,
said the company continued to do well overseas, especially in Europe
and South America.
   ``We do have a declining (profit) margin in the United States and
that's been the case all year,'' he said. ``The overseas margin has
been increasing because of outstanding results this year in Europe
and also Latin America has come back substantially.''
   Ford said it earned $384 million from its overseas operations in
the third quarter of 1988, up 249 percent from the $110 million
earned overseas during the period last year.
   The company earned $472 million from its U.S. operations, down
20.4 percent from the $593 million it earned in the July-September
period last year.
   Because of the depressed U.S. results, profit sharing for
unionized workers will be down this year compared with last,
McCammon said. Although he wasn't specific about just how much a
worker would receive, he said it would fall somewhere between the
$3,700 average per worker in 1987 and the $2,100 average the year
before.
   McCammon blamed much of the U.S. decline on development of new
products, lower earnings by the company's Financial Services Group
and higher production of lower-profit cars.
   He said that during the quarter, Ford produced 30 percent fewer
of its high-profit Thunderbirds than it did last year, and made more
lower-profit Ford Tempos and Mercury Topazes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
