<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0956EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Trade     10-27 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Trade,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Narrows Sharply and Unexpectedly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit narrowed
sharply and unexpectedly in September, partly helped by erratic
items such as exports of aircraft repairs and precious stones, the
government said Thursday.
   The pound and British stock prices shot up on the news, which
somewhat eased growing concerns about Britain's ballooning trade
shortfall. The pound's jump, in turn, diminished fears that interest
rates would head even higher.
   The trade deficit narrowed to 1.06 billion pounds, or $1.87
billion, in September from 1.81 billion pounds in August, the
Department of Trade and Industry said.
   The financial markets had expected the deficit to widen slightly.
   The current account deficit narrowed to 560 million pounds from
1.31 billion pounds, the department said.
   The current account includes ``invisible'' trade such as
services, overseas investment earnings and official transfer
payments, which the government estimated to be in surplus of 500
million pounds in the most recent month.
   Exports totaled 7.56 billion pounds in September, up from 6.75
billion pounds in August. Imports totaled 8.62 billion pounds in
September, up from 8.56 billion pounds in August.
   Explaining the erratic items, the department said planes brought
here for repair counted as imports in August and became exports last
month when the work was done.
   Excluding these items, the merchandise trade deficit was 1.49
billion pounds in September, compared with 1.66 billion pounds in
August.
   The pound gained almost 1.5 cents to $1.7735 in very active
dealing minutes after the report was released.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index, off 5.6
points before the report, later was up 8 points at 1,858.7.
   Although markets were heartened by the report, David Simmonds, an
economist at Midland Bank, said it was too early to conclude that
Britain's trade deficit is narrowing significantly. He pointed out
that Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson has said the trade
deficit could remain large until 1990.
   The government's economic policies have come under criticism in
recent months as inflation has heated up, prompting authorities to
push up interest rates sharply. At the same time, the trade deficit
outstripped government forecasts to hit record levels.
   Opposition Labor lawmaker Bryan Gould, party spokesman on trade,
called the latest figures ``a freak.''
   Since the beginning of 1988, Britain's merchandise trade balance
has been in deficit by 13.9 billion pounds, compared with a
6.88-billion-pound deficit a year earlier.
   In March, Lawson predicted the trade deficit for the latest year
would total 4 billion pounds.
</TEXT>
