<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices opened slightly higher while
soybeans and corn were mixed in early trading today on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Wheat prices gained some strength from reports that China may be
targeted for a large wheat purchase, analysts said.
   The U.S. Agriculture Department's plans to take up to 1.5 million
tons of wheat out of a food reserve program also affected trading in
the wheat pit, while expectations that Spain may be in the market
for soybeans added firmness to bean prices, they said.
   Despite some gains, the surge of follow-through buying that had
been anticipated after Wednesday's late rally in grains and beans
did not materialize, analysts said.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to { cent higher, with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.12\ a bushel; corn was 1{
cents lower to 1 cent higher, with December at $2.79 a bushel; oats
were 1 cent to 3 cents lower with December at $2.37 a bushel; and
soybeans were 3 cents lower to 1 cent higher, with November at
$7.66{ a bushel.
   Live cattle and hog futures prices were mixed while pork belly
prices dipped in early trading at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle prices opened .5 cent lower to .25 cent higher with
the contract for delivery in December at 73.95 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were unchanged to .15 cent higher, with October at 81.57
cents a pound; live hogs were .5 cent lower to .10 cent higher, with
December at 41.32 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .15
cent to .72 cent lower, with February at 48.85 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures were lower Wednesday.
