<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MCorp     10-27 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-MCorp,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chairman of MCorp Says Bankruptcy Filing `A High Probability'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of MCorp, a Dallas-based bank holding
company, says there is a high probability the company will file for
reorganization in bankruptcy court or be forced into that action by
creditors.
   ``I think everybody recognizes that there is a high probability
that we will be in (Chapter 11) bankruptcy within 30 days,''
chairman Gene Bishop told the Dallas Times Herald Wednesday. ``It's
obvious that we can be forced and that we may not have any choice.''
   ``In the interest of protecting our assets and our creditors,
it's really the only alternative,'' he said.
   There had been recent speculation that the bank holding company,
Texas' second-largest behind NCNB Texas National Bank, was forcing
the reorganization issue to advance its own plan to recapitalize.
Chapter 11 protection would free the corporation from the threat of
creditor lawsuits until it could develop a plan to put its finances
in order.
   MCorp announced earlier this week it would stop paying dividends
to preferred shareholders and would cease payments on about $470
million in debt. That action effectively put the company's creditors
on notice that they could push MCorp into bankruptcy court after
Nov. 21.
   ``When we made the decision last week to quit paying dividends
and interest (on debt), that gives us 30 days from that date, which
is Nov. 21,'' Bishop said.
   ``It's sometimes very hard to get the government's attention, and
I do think now that we've got their attention,'' Bishop said. ``The
time clock is running now.''
   MCorp proposed a recapitalization package earlier this month that
would include $400 million from the bank holding company itself,
$400 million raised from investors and shareholders, and an
undisclosed amount of aid from the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   Analysts have estimated the company would need at least $1
billion in federal money.
   MCorp has set aside $400 million for the rescue and the FDIC
wants the company to spread that money around to its ailing banks.
   ``The regulators . . . are saying we should use our money, and
put it down in the banks and then they'll see what they can do for
us,'' Bishop said. ``They will give us no assurance they will do
anything.''
   Bishop said MCorp attorneys have told the company to leave the
money where it is, partly for the recapitalization and partly so the
board won't be sued by creditors upset that the holding company was
putting all of its assets into its subsidiary banks.
   ``What we hope is that we'll be able to use that $400 million
(belonging to the holding company) in connection with the
recapitalization of all of the MCorp banks,'' Bishop said.
   The company could work out its differences with creditors,
preferred shareholders and the FDIC in bankruptcy court, he said.
   MCorp depositors, customers, and suppliers would not be affected
by a reorganization proceeding, a spokesman said.
   ``The deposits would still be insured by the FDIC, and it would
be business as usual,'' the spokesman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881027-0256 </DOCNO>
