<DOCNO> AP881027-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1225EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-MorrellFines     10-27 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Morrell Fines,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Morrell Fines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has dismissed fines totaling $690,000
against John Morrell & Co. for safety problems at its Sioux Falls,
S.D., plant, the company says.
   The fines, recommended by the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration in April 1987, were at that time the third-largest in
OSHA's history. They resulted from charges by OSHA that Morrell, the
nation's fifth-largest meatpacker, had willfully failed to record
accidents at the Sioux Falls plant.
   But the company, which is based here, said in a news release
Wednesday that Administrative Law Judge James A. Cronin ruled
against OSHA, saying the statute of limitations governing the
violations had expired.
   The company said the judge he added that even if time had not run
out, he would have reduced the fines should to only $11,000.
   Cronin, a judge with the OSHA Review Commission in Denver, said
the agency was incorrect to fine Morrell $10,000 for each of the 69
safety violations.
   The review commission in the past has said it is fundamentally
unfair to assess multiple penalties for similar violations.
   OSHA representative Terry Mikelson said the agency probably will
appeal Cronin's ruling to a higher review panel. Further appeals
could take the case into the federal court system.
   OSHA is investigating Morrell for repetitive motion injuries
sustained by its workers as well as other alleged physical hazards.
Repetitive motion injuries include tendonitis, various postural
strains and carpal tunnel syndrome, a debilitating nerve disorder.
They occur when workers repeat the same motions over and over.
   Steve Crim, senior vice president at the Sioux Falls plant, said,
``We have always felt the fines were grossly unfair and we would win
our appeal to have them overturned.''
   Morrell chairman Milton Schloss has said he implemented a safety
program that sharply reduced injury rates in the past few months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881027-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Perot-EDS     10-27 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Perot-EDS,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Perot Drops Part of Lawsuit Against EDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dallas billionaire Ross Perot has withdrawn a
request for a temporary order prohibiting Electronic Data Systems
Corp. from interfering with his new data processing company, Perot
Systems.
   With Wednesday's action, Perot dropped part of his countersuit to
a claim filed by EDS, which argued that by founding the new firm,
Perot was violating a non-competition clause in the agreement he
signed when he left EDS.
   In a hearing last week on EDS' suit, a Virginia judge ruled that
Perot Systems does not violate the agreement as long as it is
operated on a non-profit basis until December 1989.
   Fletcher Yarbrough, Perot's attorney, said the ruling negated the
need to seek the preliminary injunction.
   EDS officials called the move a retreat from a ``nonsense''
lawsuit.
   ``Ross has just got to quit being so mad,'' EDS spokesman William
Wright told the Dallas Times Herald. ``There's just so long that you
can carry on a vendetta like that before it becomes detrimental to
business.''
   Perot's attorneys have contended that EDS has tried to put Perot
Systems out of business by interfering with pending contracts,
intimidating prospective clients of Perot Systems and intimidating
EDS employees who might be considering joining Perot.
   The development is the latest in an ongoing legal battle
involving Perot, EDS and General Motors Corp., EDS' parent company.
The dispute centers around several paragraphs of a December 1986
buyout agreement between Perot and GM, in which Perot promised not
to compete for profit with EDS until December 1989.
   EDS had sought to prevent Perot from operating any competing
business until the terms of the contract expired. The full trial is
set for April in Virginia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
