<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Koppers     10-27 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koppers,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koppers To Divide and Sell Chemical Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British industrialist Brian C. Beazer said
Thursday he plans to split up the chemicals unit of his
Pittsburgh-based Koppers Co. and sell them by January.
   Beazer declined to disclose the total selling price, but
indicated it would be more than the $660 million offered earlier
this year by a management-led group.
   The number of employees at Koppers' Pittsburgh headquarters,
which has dropped from 500 to 280 since Koppers was acquired in
June, will be reduced to 90 after the sale of the chemicals units,
he said.
   Beazer also announced that Koppers' name would be changed to
Beazer Building Materials & Services Inc. once the chemical unit was
sold.
   Koppers manufactures construction materials and chemicals and is
one of the largest U.S. concerns producing road-building materials.
   Beazer told a group of investment bankers in New York that he had
received at least three serious bids for each section of the
chemical division, which has been split along product lines.
   ``We would expect to receive sales proceeds higher than if it had
been sold (as one unit) last June,'' he said. ``At the present time
we are negotiating with seven individual buyers. We consider it in
the best interests of all concerned.''
   Beazer PLC, a Bath, England-based homebuilding and construction
materials company, purchased Koppers in June for $1.8 billion after
a bitter struggle by Koppers management. Beazer's stock will be
listed on the New York Stock Exchange starting Friday.
   The company said its expansion efforts had been strengthened by
the acquisition of Koppers, coming after the 1986 purchase of
Dallas-based Gifford-Hill & Co. Inc., which makes cement and builds
houses in several states.
   Since the purchase of Koppers, Beazer has sold four of its units
for $90 million and is in the process of selling two others for $60
million, Beazer said. He said proceeds from all the asset sales,
including the chemicals unit, would total $900 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
