<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     10-27 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower; Gold Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMs version expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell Thursday against most major
currencies in active European trading after hitting four-month lows
on a report of unexpectedly low U.S. economic growth. Gold prices
were higher.
   The dollar came under renewed pressure at midday, partly pushed
down by a report of a narrower-than-expected British trade deficit
in September and continued selling pressure related to Wednesday's
report of a modest rise in the U.S. gross national product.
   ``People are uncertain following the surprisingly good figures
from Britain,'' said a senior dealer at a bank in Frankfurt, West
Germany. ``They were buying (British) pounds and selling dollars.''
   Britain's merchandise deficit narrowed to 1.06 billion pounds
($1.87 billion) in September, partly helped by erratic items such as
exports of aircraft repairs and precious stones, the government said
Thursday.
   The U.S. government said the third-quarter gross national product
rose at an annual rate of 2.2 percent, the smallest rise in almost
two years.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.90 Japanese yen to a closing 125.90
yen. Later, in London, it slipped back further to 125.75 yen.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7695 from $1.7600 late
Wednesday.
   Dealers said the dollar recovered some ground in late European
trading on buying by Japanese traders. Market fears of central bank
intervention had prevented the dollar from falling further.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.7725 West German marks, down from 1.7745; 1.4915
Swiss francs, down from 1.5065; 6.0455 French francs, down from
6.0725; 1.9977 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0005; 1,320.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,323.50; and 1.2024 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1988.
   Gold bullion edged higher in lethargic trading in Europe.
   In Hong Kong, gold fell 54 cents to close at a bid $409.22 a troy
ounce. In Zurich, it rose to $407.20 bid from $407.10 bid Wednesday.
In London, it rose to $407.50 an ounce from $407.05.
   Silver bullion was quoted in London at a late bid price of $6.22
a troy ounce, unchanged from Wednesday.
</TEXT>
