<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 2041EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BuildingOutlook     10-27 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Building Outlook,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Construction Contracts to Fall 4 Percent in 1989, Economist Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Embargoed for Release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contracting for new construction will fall 4
percent next year to a total of $241 billion, an economist said
Thursday.
   Continuing high vacancy rates in offices and apartments, and
rising mortgage interest rates, will bring a decline in both
commercial and residential building, said George A. Christie, vice
president and chief economist of McGraw-Hill Information Services Co.
   In the first nine months of this year, new building contracting
declined about 3 percent from the 1987 level, according to
McGraw-Hill.
   ``The state of the construction industry as we near the close of
1988 is best described as one quarter in decline, another quarter in
limbo, and the remaining half in jeopardy,'' Christie told the
Building Products Executives Conference.
   Contracting is off 40 percent in the overdeveloped commercial
building sector, where high vacancy rates persist, Christie said.
   He said public works construction is in limbo because of the
drive to cut the federal budget deficit.
   Single-family housing and institutional construction are in
jeopardy, Christie noted, since they are sensitive to interest rates.
   ``Rising mortgage and bond rates pose a threat in the near future
to at least half of all construction activity,'' he said.
   Christie predicted that rising interest rates will produce a drop
in single-family housing starts to 900,000 units in 1989 from
975,000 this year.
   The economist forecast that an 18 percent drop in retail
building, to $18.9 billion, will help fuel an anticipated 8 percent
decline next year in commercial construction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
