<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0348</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market posted a broad loss today as
traders showed signs of wariness over the recent wave of corporate
buyout bids.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 24.71 to 2,140.47
by 3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by nearly 4 to 1 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 317 up, 1,185 down
and 430 unchanged.
   Huge bids for companies like RJR Nabisco and Kraft in recent days
have dominated conversations on Wall Street.
   While deals like these bring opportunities for large short-term
profits, analysts said, they have also prompted widespread talk
about the potential dangers of the new debt burdens created to
finance the transactions.
   News reports this morning said investors apparently had balked at
an offering of high-yield Federated Department Stores bonds arising
from Campeau Corp.'s takeover of Federated last spring.
   First Boston Corp., the lead underwriter, said it had not
withdrawn the offering but was engaged in discussions with the
company to ``restructure the transaction.''
   Also, Chairman Alan Greenspan of the Federal Reserve Board said
Wednesday that the Fed has advised banks to be cautious in their
lending for buyouts.
   RJR Nabisco shares dropped 3[ to 81| and Kraft fell 3] to 94[,
ranking among the most active Big Board issues.
   Sears Roebuck, which has climbed sharply of late on talk of a
possible restructuring or other transaction, lost 1| to 43[.
   Pillsbury, the target of a takeover bid by Grand Metropolitan PLC
of Britain, dropped 2\ to 58}.
   On the plus side, General Motors gained 2] to 80. The company
reported third-quarter earnings of $2.46 a share, against $2.28 in
the like period last year.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
2.11 to 156.26. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 3.12 at 300.32.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 171.88 million shares with an
hour to go.
</TEXT>
