<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 2136EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CityGrowth     10-27 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-City Growth,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Growth Seems Fastest in Midwest, Accounting Firm Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic growth in the nation's largest cities
appears to be rising fastest in the Midwest, according to a study
released Thursday by the accounting firm Grant Thornton.
   In the past three years, by contrast, economic growth has been
strongest in Eastern cities, New York-based Grant Thornton said.
   The Grant Thornton index showed that, in the second quarter, the
average rate of economic growth for Midwestern cities rose more than
the comparable rates for cities in the East, West and South.
   The index is a quarterly composite of seven economic indicators
collected for 24 major U.S. cities.
   In the second quarter, the firm said, the seven fastest-growing
metropolitan economies were those of Minneapolis, Detroit,
Cincinnati, Kansas City, Mo., St. Louis, Cleveland and Pittsburgh.
   The index for three cities _ Dallas, Phoenix and Los Angeles _
was unchanged in the second quarter from the first, Grant Thornton
said. Three other cities showed an economic decline: Miami, Seattle
and Atlanta.
   The economic indicators used to rank the cities include
commercial and residential construction permits, average weekly
hours worked by manufacturing employees, business starts and
failures, and retail sales.
   After the seven cities with the fastest-growing economies, the
others in descending order of magnitude are Boston, Milwaukee,
Denver, San Diego, Chicago, Baltimore, Washington, D.C., Houston,
San Francisco, Philadelphia, New York, Dallas, Phoenix, Los Angeles,
Atlanta, Seattle and Miami.
   Grant Thornton is a 64-year-old firm that provides accounting,
audit, tax and management consulting services in more than 50
countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881027-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1612EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneyFunds     10-27 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose-Fell $x.xx Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended
Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 453 money market mutual
funds rose $1.73 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The rise, to $270.52 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a revised $1.21 billion increase in the funds'
assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual
fund trade group.
   The funds' assets hit a record high $280.02 billion in the week
ended Feb. 24.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 223 general purpose funds rose $296.7 million to $85.63
billion, assets of 102 broker-dealer funds increased $519.9 million
to $114.38 billion, and assets of 128 institutional funds rose
$909.0 million to $70.51 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 7.54 percent from 7.49 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose, to 7.50 percent from 7.47 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
unchanged at 37 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
6.07 percent as of Wednesday from 6.05 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, was unchanged at 5.12 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 7.82
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 7.80 the
previous week. Yields were 8.12 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 8.11
percent; 8.33 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.32 percent; and 8.56
percent on 5-year CDs, down from 8.57 percent.
</TEXT>
