<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1626EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Auto Bjt   10-27 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Auto, Bjt,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Increases Profits, Chrysler Loses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. on Thursday reported an
industry earnings record of $859.2 million for the third quarter,
eclipsing rival Ford Motor Co., while Chrysler Corp. said its
earnings dropped 54.3 percent for the period.
   GM said its quarterly earnings, which work out to $2.46 a share,
came on sales of $25.04 billion. On Wednesday, Ford reported
third-quarter earnings of $856.3 million, or $1.78 a share, on sales
of $17.73 billion.
   It was the first time in five quarters that GM has outearned Ford.
   GM Chairman Roger B. Smith and President Robert Stempel credited
the company's performance to growing North American sales and
continued strength in the foreign markets, especially in Europe.
   GM had originally reported a profit of $812.3 million, or $2.28 a
share, for the third quarter of 1987, but said today that accounting
changes made the comparable figures for last year $421 million, or
$1.05 per share.
   Adjusted sales for the third quarter of last year amounted to
$22.6 billion, the company said.
   For the first nine months of 1988, GM said it earned $3.46
billion, or $10.09 per share, up 27.4 percent from $2.72 billion, or
$7.70 per share, during the January-September period last year.
Sales for the first nine months of this year amounted to $81.38
billion, up 7.9 percent from the $75.4 billion in sales during the
first three quarters of 1987.
   GM's results surprised auto analysts.
   ``The consensus for guys on Wall Street for the third quarter was
a $1.50 (per share),'' said Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc. in New York.
   ``I think they did better in Europe than most people expected,''
Heaney said. ``GM, last year through the first three quarters,
didn't make any money on their North American operations. In the
fourth quarter it began to kick in.''
   Maryann Keller of Furman Selz Mager Dietz & Birney agreed,
saying, ``I was up at the high end (at $2 a share) of where the
world was. ... The benefit came from overseas and the benefit came
from North America.''
   While GM was spreading good news about its earnings on Thursday,
Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca was spreading hope for the future in
the nation's third-largest automaker.
   Chrysler said it earned $112.5 million, or 50 cents a share, on
sales of $7.01 billion during the July-September period this year.
During the three-month period last year, Chrysler said it earned
$246 million, or $1.12 a share, on sales of $6.17 billion.
   In a statement, Chrysler said its earnings were hurt by high
costs of incentives, which the company used extensively to lure
buyers into showrooms, and the closing for the entire period of the
Newark, Del., assembly plant.
   For the first nine months of this year, Chrysler's earnings fell
34.4 percent to $616.6 million, or $2.77 a share, from $939.5
million, or $4.33 a share, last year. Sales for the first nine
months of 1988 amounted to $23.17 billion, compared with $18.61
billion in 1987, a 24.5 percent increase.
   ``We're launching promising products here and overseas, and we're
proceeding with our plan to spend $13.5 billion in the next five
years on new products, processes and plant improvements,'' Iacocca
said. ``These investments will give us an edge as we do battle with
scores of competitors from every corner of the globe.''
   Also Thursday, Chrysler Financial Corp. reported record
third-quarter earnings of $59 million, 20 percent more than the $49
million it earned during the third quarter of last year. For the
first nine months of 1988, the financial arm of the corporation
earned $185 million, a nine-month record and up 12 percent from the
$166 million it earned during the January-September period last year.
</TEXT>
