<HEAD>Campeau Puts Off Junk Bond Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. said Thursday it has postponed a
sale of $1.15 billion in junk bonds to consider restructuring the
issue, which is needed to help finance its acquisition of Federated
Department Stores Inc.
   The Toronto-based compaa retail industry analyst with Prescott Ball
&
Turben who tracks Campeau, said investors were uneasy about the
overall leveraged buyout situation, but said there also were
concerns about Campeau's financial health.
   Johnson said the sales of Campeau's Federated and Allied Stores
units had not been strong, noting that the store divisions reported
hefty losses from high interest expenses in its most recent
quarterly report.
   In that report, filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Campeau said sales at Federated's department store units
either declined or eked out gains of less than 1 percent during the
quarter ended July 30. Sales were lackluster even at the company's
star Bloomingdale's division.
   Federated lost $100 million during the quarter, while Allied lost
$107 million.
   The Campeau source denied that Federated's problems had anything
to do with the postponement of the issue.
   ``The business is very strong; the (bond) market is in turmoil,''
the source said.
