<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-27 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Strengthens In New York, Gold Eases</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Precede LONDON BC</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended mostly higher Thursday after a
seesaw session influenced largely by rumors of central bank support,
but money dealers said the underlying trend for the U.S. currency is
down.
   Gold prices eased in New York after strengthening in Europe.
Republic National Bank quoted bullion at $407.50 a troy ounce as of
4 p.m. EDT, down from $408.15 at the same time Wednesday.
   Currency dealers said the dollar weakened early in the day based
on its sharp decline Wednesday, when a government report of
slower-than-expected U.S. economic growth depressed the dollar to
the lowest level in four months.
   But rumors quickly surfaced that the Bank of Japan had intervened
by buying dollars to support the currency. Traders said there were
other rumors, later denied, that the Swiss and West German central
banks were buying dollars.
   The dollar strengthened on those rumors although it lost ground
to the British pound, which surged on news of Britain's narrowing
trade deficit.
   ``We actually saw the dollar move in a relatively wide range,''
said David Jacques, senior corporate dealer at the New York branch
of Barclays Bank PLC. ``Most of the movement on the back of
unconcrete information.''
   Zlatko Glamuzina, a senior trader for the New York branch of
Banco di Sicilia, said that because of the rumors and the dollar's
upward move, ``we lost the drive to push the dollar down.''
   Although he predicted the dollar could rise more over the next
few days, ``there are quite a few people who expect the dollar to go
lower.''
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.90 Japanese yen to 125.90 yen. Later
in London it slipped further to 125.75 yen. But by the time trading
ended in New York the dollar had rebounded to 126.08 yen, higher
than its 125.70-yen value Wednesday.
   The British pound rose in London to $1.7695 from $1.7600
Wednesday. Later in New York the pound fetched $1.7675, higher than
its $1.7610 value Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York vs. rates late Wednesday:
1.7783 West German marks, up from 1.7750; 1.4982 Swiss francs, down
from 1.5041; 1.2050 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1993; 6.0680 French
francs, up from 6.0595; and 1,323.12 Italian lire, up from 1,322.00.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe vs. rates late Wednesday:
1.7725 marks, down from 1.7745; 1.4915 Swiss francs, down from
1.5065; 6.0455 French francs, down from 6.0725; 1.9977 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.0005; 1,320.00 Italian lire, down from
1,323.50; and 1.2024 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1988.
   In gold trading, the Commodity Exchange of New York quoted
bullion for current delivery at $407.60 a troy ounce, down 70 cents.
   Earlier in London, gold rose 45 cents to $407.50; in Zurich it
rose 10 cents to $407.20; in Hong Kong it fell 54 cents to $409.22.
   Silver bullion for current delivery fell 2.4 cents a troy ounce
to $6.20 on the New York Comex. In London silver fetched $6.22,
unchanged from Wednesday.
</TEXT>
