<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Computer     10-27 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Computer,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Data General Losses Widen In Quarter; Prime Earnings Drop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Data General Corp., the minicomputer company, said Thursday its
losses widened to nearly $50 million in the latest quarter because
of a major charge to pay for a cost-cutting consolidation.
   Prime Computer Inc., another minicomputer maker, said its
third-quarter profit fell 26 percent in spite of the increased
revenue from its acquisition of Computervision Corp.
   The company said its fortunes were improving because revenue was
up and income from operations, not counting restructuring charges,
had also increased.
   Data General, based in Westboro, Mass., said it lost $49.8
million in the fourth quarter ended Sept. 24, double the losses of
$24.6 million a year earlier. Revenue rose 3 percent to $341.5
million from $332.3 million.
   A restructuring charge of $48.7 million in the quarter covered
the cost of consolidation of manufacturing and product repair
operations.
   For the full fiscal year, Data General said its losses fell to
$15.5 million from $123.7 million a year earlier. The 1987 period
included a restructuring charge of $53.8 million. Revenue for the
fiscal year rose 7 percent to $1.36 billion from $1.27 billion.
   Prime Computer in Natick, Mass., attributed its own earnings
decline to reorganization and softening demand.
   For the third quarter, earnings totaled $11.7 million, or 24
cents per share, on revenue of $391.4 million, compared with
earnings of $15.9 million, or 32 cents per share, on revenue of
$236.2 million in 1987.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, net income totaled
$33.4 million, or 69 cents a share, down from $43.5 million, or 88
cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $1.16 billion from
$694 million.
   The 1987 results do not include Computervision, which Prime
acquired in February 1988.
</TEXT>
