<1ST_LINE>r f AM-KaiserTech-Maxxam     10-27 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-KaiserTech-Maxxam,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>KaiserTech Stockholders Approve $708 Million Buyout By Maxxam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stockholders of KaiserTech Ltd., parent of
Kaiser Aluminum & Chemical Corp., on Thursday approved a $708
million buyout by Maxxam Group Inc.
   The transaction, which already has been approved by the boards of
both companies, will bring KaiserTech stockholders $19.37{ per
share. When the deal is completed in the next few days, KaiserTech
will be a wholly-owned subsidiary of Los Angeles-based Maxxam.
   KaiserTech is the nation's third-largest aluminum producer.
Maxxam is involved in real estate and lumber.
   James S. Pasman Jr., president and chief executive officer of
KaiserTech and chairman of Kaiser Aluminum, said he and other
company managers will remain in their jobs and the company will keep
its headquarters in Oakland.
   Charles E. Hurwitz, chairman and chief executive officer of
Maxxam, said he will not be involved with day-to-day management of
KaiserTech and intends to preserve the company's identity as an
aluminum producer.
   Pasman said he is part of a broad management group that would
hold about 15 percent equity in the company under terms still to be
negotiated.
   KaiserTech has rebounded in the past year from six years of
losses, amid a major restructuring and cost-cutting effort. The
company had a profit of $166.2 million for the first nine months of
1988 on revenue of $1.72 billion, compared with a nine-month loss of
$406.8 million last year after restructuring costs.
   Maxxam plans to shed many of KaiserTech's assets to help reduce
the debt burden assumed in financing the takeover deal. Those assets
include: a fabrication plant in Ravenswood, W.Va.; a coil coating
plant in Toledo, Ohio; a recycling plant in Bedford, Ind; and the
company's electrical products division.
   Other assets that could be sold are some real estate properties
and foreign joint-venture interests.
</TEXT>
