<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Airlines     10-27 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Airlines,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAL, Delta Post Higher Profit in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines and the parent of United Airlines reported
Thursday that strong passenger traffic boosted their third-quarter
profit substantially from a year earlier.
   Chicago-based UAL Corp. said its net income in the three months
ended Sept. 30 more than quadrupled to $402.4 million, or $18.68 a
share, from $82.3 million, or $1.41 a shre, a year earlier.
   The latest per-share profit was calculated on the basis of about
21.5 million shares outstanding, while the third quarter of 1987 was
based on 58.4 million shares.
   Third-quarter revenue rose to $2.41 billion from $2.26 billion.
   UAL, whose main subsidiary is United, said its revenue passenger
miles increased 5 percent during the quarter from a year earlier. A
revenue passenger mile represents one paying passenger flown one
mile and is used to determine an airline's capacity.
   United is the nation's largest airline.
   In August, UAL completed the sale of 50 percent of its interest
in the Covia partnership, which owns the Apollo computer
reservations system, for $499 million. UAL, formerly called Allegis
Corp., sold the stake to five airlines: Alitalia, British Airways,
KLM Royal Dutch Airlines, Swissair and USAir Group Inc.
   In the first nine months of the year, UAL's profit surged to
$1.10 billion, or $34.35 a share, from $125.2 million, or $2.26 a
share.
   Nine-month revenue rose to $6.75 billion from $6.19 billion.
   ``While we are pleased with the achievements of the last three
quarters, we understand we must produce these kinds of results
consistently if we are to meet the capital requirements of replacing
and expanding our fleet,'' Chairman Stephen M. Wolf said.
   Atlanta-based Delta, the third-largest U.S. airline, said its
third-quarter profit jumped 69 percent to $99.95 million, or $2.03 a
share, from $59.1 million, or $1.22 a share, a year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 15 percent, to $1.88 billion from
$1.63 billion.
   ``Strong growth in passenger revenue was a principal ingredient
in Delta's record financial results,'' said Thomas J. Roeck, chief
financial officer.
   Revenue passenger miles were up 10 percent, reflecting ``general
good economic conditions, the benefits of our merger with Western
Air Lines, and growth in domestic and international operations,''
Roeck said.
   In the first nine months, net income surged 80 percent to $259.4
million, or $5.30 a share. Nine-month revenue increased 18 percent,
to $5.47 billion from $4.65 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
