<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 2203EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DetroitNewspapers     10-27 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Detroit Newspapers,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Appeals Court To Hear JOA Arguments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Decision time may be near for the Detroit Free
Press, a spokesman for the newspaper said as lawyers for and against
its partial merger with The Detroit News prepared to go back to
federal appeals court.
   Newspapers officials are hoping a victory before the U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Washington D.C. scheduled to hear arguments in
the case Friday convinces opponents of a joint operating agreement
to forgo a Supreme Court challenge.
   That would allow the newspapers to merge advertising, circulation
and business operations _ while keeping separate news and editorial
departments _ a move they have said is vital if the Free Press is to
survive.
   An adverse ruling by the three-judge panel could force
Knight-Ridder Inc., owner of the 157-year-old Free Press, to decide
whether it wants to pursue a lengthy Supreme Court battle.
   ``That's such a hypothetical question, I don't see any value in
speculating on something like that,'' Knight-Ridder spokesman Frank
Hawkins Jr. said.
   Gannett Co. Inc., owner of the News, has said it will operate the
News with or without a JOA.
   Knight-Ridder has said if a JOA were denied it would close the
Free Press, putting its 2,200 employees out of work.
   But Hawkins said he didn't know if the chain would choose to ride
out another year or more of uncertainty and newspaper losses that a
Supreme Court battle would involve.
   ``The options are beginning to narrow now,'' he said.
   Former Attorney General Edwin Meese approved a JOA in an Aug. 8
ruling. But hours before it was to take effect, opponents obtained
an order from the appellate court barring the newspapers from
enacting it.
   Federal law provides for a limited antitrust exemption to permit
a JOA if it would preserve competing editorial voices in a community.
   Administrative Law Judge Morton Needelman recommended last
December after hearings in Detroit that Meese deny a JOA, saying the
newspapers failed to prove they would fail without the merger.
   The opponents include Michigan Citizens for an Independent Press,
a group of more than 500 readers, advertisers and newspaper
employees, and Public Citizen, a Washington-based group founded by
Ralph Nader.
   Arguing the newspapers' case will be Washington attorney Clark
Clifford and Justice Department lawyer Douglas Letter.
   Arguing against a JOA will be Public Citizen lawyer William
Schultz.
   Each side will be allotted 20 minutes. There is no deadline for a
ruling by the panel of Judges Laurence H. Silberman, Ruth Bader
Ginsburg and Spottswood Robinson III.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
