<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Import-ExportPrices 1stLd-Writethru f0161 10-27 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Import-Export Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0161,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cost of Imported Goods Down for First Time in Two Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 4th graf bgng, `The report ... to FIX word in 2nd
sentence to second quarter, sted first. Also moving on general news
wires.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price Americans pay for imported goods fell
1.1 percent from July through September, the first decline in more
than two years, the government reported Thursday.
   The Labor Department attributed the quarterly drop to a fall in
crude oil prices and a rise in the value of the dollar against
overseas currencies.
   A stronger dollar boosts Americans' purchasing power for foreign
goods and also tends to make U.S. exports more expensive. U.S.
export prices rose 2 percent during the July-September quarter, the
department said.
   The report said the dollar, after falling in value for three
years, rose by 4.2 percent on a trade-weighted basis against other
currencies during the third quarter. It had edged up by 0.3 percent
in the second quarter.
   Despite these increases, the dollar is still 28.8 percent lower
than its high point reached in March 1985, according to the currency
index used by the Labor Department.
   Many economists contend that further improvement in the U.S.
merchandise trade deficit will require further declines in the
dollar, with some suggesting a drop of 20 percent may be needed.
   The United States ran a record $170.3 billion merchandise trade
deficit for all of 1987. For the first eight months of this year,
the deficit has been running at an annual rate of $139 billion.
   The 1.1 percent drop in import prices from July through September
was the first since a 3.3 percent decline in the first quarter of
1986 that was attributed primarily to a fall in energy prices.
   Lower oil prices also played a large part in the July-September
drop. Without a 7.1 percent plunge in the price of imported energy,
the overall import decline would have been a smaller 0.6 percent.
   There were also declines in other areas, including a 1.1 percent
drop in imported food prices and a 0.5 percent redcution in
machinery prices.
   Even with the July-September decline, import prices are still 4.1
percent higher than they were a year ago.
   The 2 percent rise in export prices followed a 2.8 percent
increase in the April-June quarter. Export prices are now 8.7
percent higher than a year ago.
   Food exports led the list of third-quarter price increases,
shooting up 14.8 percent in reflecting the impact of the summer
drought in the Farm Belt.
   Food exports had risen by 8.6 percent in the second quarter and
are now 36.8 percent higher than a year ago.
   The category of machinery and transport equipment, which
constitutes nearly one-half of U.S. exports, rose by 0.5 percent in
the third quarter following a 0.8 percent rise in the second quarter.
   Prices of crude materials, which had been rising rapidly, edged
up just 0.6 percent in the third quarter, the smallest increase in
two years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
