<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Stocks Down In Tokyo Morning Session</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei closing, later
dollar trading, comments. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar moved higher against the Japanese
yen Friday morning, while stock prices declined moderately.
   After opening at 126.10 yen, up 0.20 yen from Thursday's close,
the dollar held to a narrow range and was changing hands at 126.04
yen by mid-morning.
   Currency dealers said the market was being cautious about
possible intervention by the nation's central bank to brake any
sudden plunge in the dollar.
   The Bank of Japan stepped into the market to buy dollars and prop
up the U.S. currency Thursday when the dollar opened at a four-month
low. The opening followed the release of U.S. quarterly economic
figures showing unexpectedly lower growth during the July-September
period.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 102.31-point
winner the previous day, was down 100.67 points at 27,622.25 by the
close of the morning session.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, dealers said the slip in the
market's main barometer was triggered by profit-taking among some
investors after three consecutive days of gains in the index.
   ``The market still has a lot of energy, but the index isn't
moving yet,'' said one dealer with a major securities firm in Tokyo,
speaking anonymously.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
